WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en-IN

00:00:00.280 --> 00:00:02.400
-So, we just start rolling, okay?
-Yeah?

00:00:02.480 --> 00:00:05.160
-So, how we typically start this...
-Yeah.

00:00:05.240 --> 00:00:09.800
...is each one of us says
something controversial about us

00:00:09.880 --> 00:00:11.400
that nobody knows right now.

00:00:11.480 --> 00:00:12.880
[theme music playing]

00:00:29.160 --> 00:00:30.600
Ready, guys?

00:00:35.080 --> 00:00:38.080
-So, how we typically start this...
-Yeah.

00:00:38.160 --> 00:00:42.240
...is each one of us says something
controversial about us

00:00:42.320 --> 00:00:44.040
that nobody knows right now.

00:00:44.680 --> 00:00:45.800
-Mm.
-Hmm.

00:00:45.880 --> 00:00:46.880
[laughs]

00:00:46.960 --> 00:00:48.440
I'm in a strict company, boss.

00:00:48.520 --> 00:00:49.960
[laughter]

00:00:50.040 --> 00:00:52.120
-I'm part of your company, but it's okay.
-[Nitish chuckles]

00:00:54.680 --> 00:00:57.280
Maybe you can talk about something
not related to the company.

00:00:57.360 --> 00:00:59.040
-More, like, personal, I don't know.
-Yeah.

00:00:59.960 --> 00:01:02.800
-Okay. Shall I go?
-Yeah.

00:01:02.880 --> 00:01:06.920
Well, I'm very temperamental,
which people think I'm not.

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:08.400
You are temperamental?

00:01:08.480 --> 00:01:11.640
Can be. Very explosive, 1% of the time.

00:01:11.720 --> 00:01:13.600
-Wow, I haven't really seen--
-Or 0.1% of the time.

00:01:13.680 --> 00:01:19.440
My image is, in the industry,
to be the most calmest person around.

00:01:19.520 --> 00:01:20.720
Yeah, true.

00:01:20.800 --> 00:01:23.120
And who are you usually
temperamental with?

00:01:23.200 --> 00:01:25.840
Just very moody. Sometimes, very moody.

00:01:25.920 --> 00:01:26.920
-Oh...
-[Nitish chuckles]

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:29.600
So if I were to meet
your childhood classmate,

00:01:29.680 --> 00:01:31.800
-your best friend...
-Yeah?

00:01:31.880 --> 00:01:33.760
...and ask him...

00:01:34.880 --> 00:01:38.840
if Nitish is capable of
one extremely naughty thing in life

00:01:38.920 --> 00:01:41.400
at the age of 40, 50, whatever,

00:01:41.480 --> 00:01:44.680
what would he prophesize
you be capable of doing?

00:01:44.760 --> 00:01:46.240
You wouldn't believe it. Nothing.

00:01:46.320 --> 00:01:47.840
-Come on.
-[Nitish chuckling]

00:01:47.920 --> 00:01:52.400
I was the most simplest,
most quietest kid in school.

00:01:52.480 --> 00:01:53.480
-Yeah?
-Yeah.

00:01:53.560 --> 00:01:55.320
Absolutely. Very introvert-ish.

00:01:55.400 --> 00:01:56.400
Yeah?

00:01:57.200 --> 00:01:58.560
I've changed now.

00:01:58.640 --> 00:02:00.560
-[Sean] Mm.
-[Nitish chuckles]

00:02:00.640 --> 00:02:02.600
Do you consider yourself
an introvert today?

00:02:02.680 --> 00:02:06.720
Yes, but much better than what I was
when I was much younger.

00:02:06.800 --> 00:02:08.800
-And I think YPO changed me a lot...
-[Nikhil] Yeah?

00:02:08.880 --> 00:02:11.160
...in the last decade or so.

00:02:11.240 --> 00:02:14.720
Do you wanna tell everybody
who does not know, what is YPO?

00:02:14.800 --> 00:02:17.400
-[Nitish] Sure.
-Give us a minute on YPO.

00:02:17.480 --> 00:02:20.040
YPO is the Young Presidents' Organization.

00:02:20.120 --> 00:02:22.880
It's originally a US organisation,

00:02:22.960 --> 00:02:29.000
but has 14-- more than 14,
I think, 15 or 16 chapters now in India.

00:02:29.880 --> 00:02:33.480
It brings together businessmen,

00:02:33.560 --> 00:02:37.000
professionals, in a very close group.

00:02:37.080 --> 00:02:38.560
So, in Mumbai, for example,

00:02:38.640 --> 00:02:41.720
I think a total of 300 members
might be there.

00:02:41.800 --> 00:02:43.840
And we organise a lot of learning events.

00:02:43.920 --> 00:02:47.600
Like, I was just saying, right,
we're visiting Seoul next week,

00:02:47.680 --> 00:02:49.480
and we're doing
a lot of learning activity.

00:02:49.560 --> 00:02:52.760
We're actually visiting
Sean's large Krafton office

00:02:52.840 --> 00:02:55.040
where we're meeting the CEO, et cetera.

00:02:55.120 --> 00:02:56.840
I think it's a great networking event,

00:02:56.920 --> 00:02:59.480
and you may get to know
a lot of great people.

00:02:59.560 --> 00:03:02.240
You are in YPO,
so you can add to that, what I didn't.

00:03:02.320 --> 00:03:03.440
But, yeah.

00:03:05.040 --> 00:03:08.120
-I think of YPO very differently.
-Yeah.

00:03:08.200 --> 00:03:11.600
I have very...
first principles questioning

00:03:11.680 --> 00:03:15.920
about why people give so much money
to an organisation

00:03:17.160 --> 00:03:19.960
and then work for the organisation
for free.

00:03:21.480 --> 00:03:25.440
When I was not in YPO--
I say bad things about everybody, okay?

00:03:25.520 --> 00:03:28.600
This is a very open forum,
so feel free to join me.

00:03:28.680 --> 00:03:31.120
And I'm gonna pull all your legs,
so feel free to pull it back.

00:03:31.200 --> 00:03:33.560
Otherwise, I'll feel bad and guilty
at the end of it.

00:03:33.640 --> 00:03:35.680
[laughter]

00:03:35.760 --> 00:03:38.800
YPO, before I joined,
appeared like this organisation

00:03:38.880 --> 00:03:40.200
where rich people hang out.

00:03:40.280 --> 00:03:43.360
-Yeah.
-And I had a lot of curiosity about...

00:03:44.840 --> 00:03:49.280
what rich people might be doing together
when they hang out in a closed room,

00:03:49.360 --> 00:03:53.480
and they're not allowing cameras
and outsiders to come in.

00:03:53.560 --> 00:03:54.880
[Nitish] Correct.

00:03:54.960 --> 00:03:59.320
But, in the few years
that I have been with them,

00:03:59.400 --> 00:04:04.680
I have kind of realised that...
it's like a social network.

00:04:04.760 --> 00:04:06.480
-Right.
-[Nikhil] It's a social network

00:04:06.560 --> 00:04:08.520
for people to hang out,

00:04:10.400 --> 00:04:13.880
-eat, drink, chill...
-[Nitish] Correct.

00:04:16.240 --> 00:04:17.920
-...go on holidays...
-[Nitish] Correct.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:20.240
-...and also learn on the side.
-That's right.

00:04:20.320 --> 00:04:22.600
So I don't know how to put YPO in a box,

00:04:22.680 --> 00:04:25.560
but it feels like,
if you move to a new city,

00:04:25.640 --> 00:04:29.080
and you've been lucky in life,
or you were born lucky in life,

00:04:29.160 --> 00:04:31.920
it's a good way to make friends
very quickly.

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:34.160
That's true.
And there's also a brotherhood, right?

00:04:34.240 --> 00:04:37.400
So you go anywhere in the world,
and you meet a fellow YPOer,

00:04:37.480 --> 00:04:39.800
-there's an instant connect.
-Why is that?

00:04:39.880 --> 00:04:41.840
I think there's a code of conduct,
right, YPO--

00:04:41.920 --> 00:04:43.640
Forget all of that.

00:04:43.720 --> 00:04:46.200
-Deep down, why is that?
-Trust, I think.

00:04:46.280 --> 00:04:47.440
Why trust?

00:04:47.520 --> 00:04:50.600
I think, one,
because you are a YPO member.

00:04:50.680 --> 00:04:54.000
Because you know he is from affluence,

00:04:54.080 --> 00:04:56.800
and he has paid a certain amount of fee
to be in an organisation?

00:04:56.880 --> 00:04:59.720
-[laughter]
-No bullshit on the table.

00:04:59.800 --> 00:05:01.800
Sounds fair, right? Sounds fair.

00:05:01.880 --> 00:05:03.320
No, no. Perhaps, to a bit.

00:05:03.400 --> 00:05:08.360
But, more importantly, I think it's also
because, as a YPOer, over the years--

00:05:08.440 --> 00:05:11.360
I've been a YPOer over ten years, right?

00:05:11.440 --> 00:05:14.240
I think you learn certain codes of conduct
which you tend to stick to.

00:05:14.320 --> 00:05:16.160
For example, confidentiality.

00:05:16.240 --> 00:05:19.080
Do you wanna introduce yourself
professionally as well?

00:05:19.160 --> 00:05:20.480
Yeah, sure.

00:05:20.560 --> 00:05:23.920
So, I'm the founder and CEO
of Nazara Technologies.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:27.320
Nazara is India's only
listed gaming company.

00:05:27.400 --> 00:05:30.280
I actually started coding games
at the age of seven.

00:05:30.360 --> 00:05:36.640
So one of the lucky guys who discovered
his passion at a very young age.

00:05:36.720 --> 00:05:38.720
And I've had the fortune of--

00:05:38.800 --> 00:05:41.600
At a young age,
my parents encouraged me a lot.

00:05:41.680 --> 00:05:45.920
I was doing gaming now,
what, 37, 35 years back,

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:48.000
and I pursued that for my entire life now.

00:05:48.080 --> 00:05:53.120
We became the first listed
gaming company in 2021.

00:05:53.200 --> 00:05:54.720
So three years now.

00:05:54.800 --> 00:05:57.440
And the journey continues,
the game continues,

00:05:57.520 --> 00:06:00.280
-I continue to play it.
-Do you regret it? Listing?

00:06:00.920 --> 00:06:02.680
-Not at all. Not at all.
-No?

00:06:02.760 --> 00:06:06.840
I wouldn't have met you
and got you as an investor.

00:06:06.920 --> 00:06:10.640
Okay, for all the disclosures
that should be made,

00:06:10.720 --> 00:06:12.920
-I am an investor in Nitish's company.
-[Joseph] Okay.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:14.920
And what is it, 4-5%?

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:18.280
-5%.
-5% investor in Nitish's company.

00:06:18.360 --> 00:06:21.560
And we meet often,

00:06:21.640 --> 00:06:26.120
and like I'm gonna bug all of you today,
I bug him a lot on questions and--

00:06:27.040 --> 00:06:29.280
Because I want to understand
this domain a bit more.

00:06:29.360 --> 00:06:31.920
Today is rooted from that same curiosity

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:37.880
because so many people are telling me
that gaming is this next big thing.

00:06:37.960 --> 00:06:41.280
The young, today, are spending
so much more time on gaming

00:06:41.360 --> 00:06:44.160
than traditional forms of entertainment.

00:06:44.240 --> 00:06:46.320
So I have a lot of curiosity around it.

00:06:46.400 --> 00:06:51.800
But most people who I have asked
in person, not on camera,

00:06:51.880 --> 00:06:55.360
if they regret listing and becoming
a public company, say they do.

00:06:55.440 --> 00:06:57.600
-I don't.
-Nine out of ten.

00:06:57.680 --> 00:06:58.760
I absolutely don't.

00:06:58.840 --> 00:07:02.840
But why do you inherently think
listing a company is good?

00:07:02.920 --> 00:07:04.840
Is access to capital cheaper?

00:07:04.920 --> 00:07:10.640
See, from our case, I think--
I really thought... two things.

00:07:10.720 --> 00:07:13.560
Having done this business
for a really long time,

00:07:13.640 --> 00:07:17.600
two decades, at a time
when gaming didn't exist in India,

00:07:17.680 --> 00:07:19.560
I really felt, at that point of time,

00:07:19.640 --> 00:07:24.520
that, one, by going public
as India's first gaming company,

00:07:24.600 --> 00:07:27.440
we could really plant a flag
that India is opening up.

00:07:27.520 --> 00:07:29.960
-Is it good PR?
-Very good PR.

00:07:30.040 --> 00:07:32.840
I mean, if things are going well.
And, for us--

00:07:32.920 --> 00:07:35.880
Are any of your shareholders
also your clients?

00:07:35.960 --> 00:07:38.560
-Is there a significant overlap?
-No.

00:07:38.640 --> 00:07:42.440
In terms of end players, there would be,

00:07:42.520 --> 00:07:45.080
but we don't market
or cross-market to them.

00:07:45.160 --> 00:07:49.440
I mean, we don't cross-market
our equity to our players.

00:07:49.520 --> 00:07:52.200
It's difficult to extrapolate that

00:07:52.280 --> 00:07:53.680
or figure out the exact data,
but there would be.

00:07:53.760 --> 00:07:56.520
So, what is it? When you list a company,

00:07:56.600 --> 00:08:01.120
is it because you're able to get money
cheaply and faster and easily?

00:08:01.200 --> 00:08:04.720
Is it that you're doing
a marketing exercise?

00:08:04.800 --> 00:08:09.880
I'm assuming, when you go
from pre-public to public,

00:08:09.960 --> 00:08:12.160
you spend as much as...

00:08:12.240 --> 00:08:14.720
best case, 1.5, 2%,

00:08:14.800 --> 00:08:20.360
worst case, 4-5%,
in the bankers you bring in,

00:08:20.440 --> 00:08:23.280
the consultants you bring in,
the accounting fees,

00:08:23.360 --> 00:08:24.720
all of that put together.

00:08:24.800 --> 00:08:27.240
So, if somebody is spending
that much money,

00:08:27.320 --> 00:08:28.640
what is the true incentive?

00:08:28.720 --> 00:08:32.760
If you're saying PR, your shareholders
are not really your clients.

00:08:32.840 --> 00:08:34.960
If it's not capital, then what is it?

00:08:35.040 --> 00:08:39.880
No, I think, in the last three, four,
five years, as Nazara went public,

00:08:39.960 --> 00:08:45.720
our brand visibility and company's
credibility significantly increased.

00:08:45.800 --> 00:08:48.200
Credibility to who? To your customers?

00:08:48.280 --> 00:08:51.080
To a variety of stakeholders, I would say.

00:08:51.160 --> 00:08:53.600
When I say customers,
our customers are end gamers.

00:08:53.680 --> 00:08:55.480
I think, maybe, not so much to them,

00:08:56.240 --> 00:09:00.520
but even partners like Sean and Krafton
and global players like that,

00:09:00.600 --> 00:09:02.920
when they're coming into India
and wanting to partner,

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:05.680
I think, today,
Nazara is clearly one company

00:09:05.760 --> 00:09:07.840
that they're very happy
to talk to and partner.

00:09:07.920 --> 00:09:11.080
And maybe, Sean,
you can agree or not agree with me.

00:09:11.160 --> 00:09:13.520
Yeah, I mean, I totally agree.

00:09:13.600 --> 00:09:17.880
I mean, being listed
gives a lot of good publicity.

00:09:17.960 --> 00:09:20.240
Good publicity, and then, like,

00:09:20.320 --> 00:09:25.440
a feeling of trustworthiness to,
especially, the companies outside India,

00:09:25.520 --> 00:09:31.520
which might not have
a very good visibility and understanding

00:09:31.600 --> 00:09:33.080
about the backgrounds of the company.

00:09:33.160 --> 00:09:37.960
Actually, I felt the same
when Krafton got listed,

00:09:38.040 --> 00:09:40.280
maybe around a similar timing--

00:09:40.360 --> 00:09:42.440
-[Nitish] Yeah.
-How big is Krafton?

00:09:43.320 --> 00:09:45.720
-I know Nazara is 5,000 crores.
-Yeah.

00:09:47.080 --> 00:09:52.120
Our market cap is around
$9 billion to $10 billion.

00:09:52.200 --> 00:09:53.880
So that's one reason.

00:09:53.960 --> 00:09:58.680
I think there are many other
related reasons as well.

00:09:58.760 --> 00:10:04.400
I also felt, one of the reasons
for a lot of private companies--

00:10:04.480 --> 00:10:07.640
Like, I was a VC-backed company
for many, many years,

00:10:08.480 --> 00:10:10.480
and there are a lot of commitments,

00:10:11.600 --> 00:10:15.160
SHA terms, preferences
that you give to the investors.

00:10:15.240 --> 00:10:16.880
In my case, I was very lucky.

00:10:16.960 --> 00:10:19.880
I had WestBridge Capital,
which you would know, in Bangalore.

00:10:19.960 --> 00:10:25.000
Sandeep Singhal, who invested in me
from 2015 all the way to 2018, 2019.

00:10:25.080 --> 00:10:28.560
-You also had Rakesh Jhunjhunwala for it.
-Yeah. Of course.

00:10:28.640 --> 00:10:32.680
Rakeshji invested in 2018,
much later. But--

00:10:32.760 --> 00:10:35.440
Are you saying
VCs are the bigger demon in the room

00:10:35.520 --> 00:10:37.080
than public market retail clients?

00:10:37.160 --> 00:10:40.080
No, I'm saying, as an entrepreneur,

00:10:40.160 --> 00:10:43.520
you know that there are a lot of terms
you have signed on...

00:10:43.600 --> 00:10:44.800
Mm.

00:10:44.880 --> 00:10:47.520
...which you don't necessarily like.

00:10:47.600 --> 00:10:49.280
Again, I want to clarify, with me,

00:10:49.360 --> 00:10:52.640
my relation with WestBridge
or Sandeep Singhal was fantastic.

00:10:52.720 --> 00:10:54.600
They were always very patient, I never--

00:10:54.680 --> 00:10:57.600
In 15 years, we never picked up
the agreement and looked at it.

00:10:57.680 --> 00:11:02.080
But, psychologically, once you go public,
all these rights fall away, right?

00:11:02.160 --> 00:11:03.920
Because everybody has equal rights.

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:06.760
And I'm as answerable to one shareholder,

00:11:06.840 --> 00:11:10.240
one single shareholder
having one single share, as I am to you.

00:11:10.320 --> 00:11:11.320
Right.

00:11:11.400 --> 00:11:15.200
It's kind of an empowering feeling,
is what I feel.

00:11:15.280 --> 00:11:20.200
And, yeah, I think, honestly,
I'm enjoying it.

00:11:20.280 --> 00:11:21.720
It has its own challenges.

00:11:21.800 --> 00:11:25.520
For example, quarterly pressures,
every quarter results.

00:11:25.600 --> 00:11:29.000
I think the compliances take care
of themselves after a point, right?

00:11:29.080 --> 00:11:32.040
The hygiene happens,
that's not so much of an issue.

00:11:32.120 --> 00:11:34.120
But it's also how you approach it.

00:11:34.200 --> 00:11:37.080
Like, I have tried in the last three years
as a listed company,

00:11:37.160 --> 00:11:40.920
and that's what I've been sharing
with a lot of entrepreneurs who list.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:44.000
It's not easy to walk the talk,

00:11:44.080 --> 00:11:48.320
but you have to do the right thing,
what you genuinely believe is right,

00:11:48.400 --> 00:11:50.680
versus trying to deliver
the next quarter's result,

00:11:50.760 --> 00:11:53.840
even if, sometimes,
that is a short-term pain.

00:11:53.920 --> 00:11:55.840
Second is, you have to try
and be as transparent

00:11:55.920 --> 00:11:57.720
and disclose as much as you want.

00:11:57.800 --> 00:12:00.120
So, if a shareholder
wants to call you and ask

00:12:00.200 --> 00:12:01.880
what you had for breakfast this morning,

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:05.800
-you should be ready to say.
-I'll say this about Nitish.

00:12:05.880 --> 00:12:12.120
If I were to categorise him
with a word cloud, as a human being,

00:12:12.200 --> 00:12:13.760
I would say conservative.

00:12:13.840 --> 00:12:15.560
I'm not gonna praise him
because he's sitting in front of me.

00:12:15.640 --> 00:12:17.160
-[Nitish] Sure.
-[laughter]

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:20.120
I would say conservative.

00:12:21.520 --> 00:12:25.200
Last person I would assume
will ever do anything reckless.

00:12:28.600 --> 00:12:30.200
I would also say very...

00:12:31.280 --> 00:12:34.560
diligent, detail-oriented,

00:12:34.640 --> 00:12:38.040
and believes in long-term relationships.

00:12:39.440 --> 00:12:44.320
We live in a world where things
go up and down so quickly.

00:12:44.400 --> 00:12:47.080
So, the big, big thing about Nitish is,

00:12:47.160 --> 00:12:49.720
you know, 10, 20, 30 years from now...

00:12:50.800 --> 00:12:52.240
he'll still be here.

00:12:52.320 --> 00:12:54.240
He might not be growing the fastest,

00:12:54.320 --> 00:12:58.320
but he will be doing the right thing
slowly in the background,

00:13:00.400 --> 00:13:02.800
which, strangely enough,
is a really rare thing,

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:06.920
not just here,
but everywhere in the world today.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:08.840
You learn from your lessons, right?

00:13:08.920 --> 00:13:11.480
When I started, I was, like, 17,18,

00:13:11.560 --> 00:13:16.480
right in the start of
the dot-com boom in '99,

00:13:16.560 --> 00:13:18.880
and the crash in 2000, right?

00:13:18.960 --> 00:13:21.040
So I learnt my lessons very quickly then.

00:13:21.120 --> 00:13:24.480
And I think the conservatism
comes a bit from there,

00:13:25.560 --> 00:13:27.400
which is a good thing
and a bad thing, right?

00:13:27.480 --> 00:13:29.720
Because it also has its own handicap.

00:13:29.800 --> 00:13:32.880
But it allows you
to live to fight another day,

00:13:32.960 --> 00:13:35.280
-and sustain, which is a good thing.
-[Nikhil] Correct. Yeah.

00:13:35.360 --> 00:13:37.120
Even my industry's like that,
stock markets.

00:13:37.200 --> 00:13:38.320
Yeah.

00:13:38.400 --> 00:13:40.280
It's all about
living to fight another day.

00:13:40.360 --> 00:13:42.120
Sean, would you like to go next?

00:13:42.200 --> 00:13:43.680
Yeah, why not? [chuckles]

00:13:43.760 --> 00:13:47.480
Yeah, I'm from South Korea.

00:13:47.560 --> 00:13:50.720
-Yeah.
-I was born in Pohang,

00:13:50.800 --> 00:13:55.600
which is a, like, southeastern coast city.

00:13:55.680 --> 00:13:57.040
I was born there,

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:01.800
from, you know...
from parents who are working

00:14:01.880 --> 00:14:05.960
for one of the largest tech companies
in the world.

00:14:06.040 --> 00:14:09.160
So I'm from a middle-class family.

00:14:09.240 --> 00:14:10.560
Yeah, that's my... [chuckles]

00:14:10.640 --> 00:14:15.280
I'm guessing South Korean middle-class is
much more rich than Indian middle-class.

00:14:15.360 --> 00:14:17.480
What is GDP per capita in South Korea?

00:14:17.560 --> 00:14:20.960
-$50,000?
-33,000 now, I guess.

00:14:21.040 --> 00:14:24.160
Middle-class would be like
$70,000-$80,000 a year?

00:14:24.240 --> 00:14:26.760
Yeah, household income might be like that.

00:14:26.840 --> 00:14:32.720
But then you have to understand
that Korea grows-- grew quite fast.

00:14:32.800 --> 00:14:38.160
So when I was, like,
you know, 10, 15, it was--

00:14:38.240 --> 00:14:40.320
I cannot say that it was similar

00:14:40.400 --> 00:14:45.480
to what India's economy
is now currently positioned,

00:14:45.560 --> 00:14:50.760
but South Korea's GDP,
when there was the Olympics in 1988,

00:14:50.840 --> 00:14:57.200
it was 2,500 or 2,700,
which is pretty similar to where India is.

00:14:57.280 --> 00:15:02.840
So, as a South Korean,
we started from, like--

00:15:02.920 --> 00:15:07.840
in the '60s, '70s, before I was born,
it was a developing country

00:15:07.920 --> 00:15:11.680
in the lower side among global peers.

00:15:11.760 --> 00:15:14.080
And then it grew into
a developed country in the--

00:15:14.160 --> 00:15:16.360
What era are you talking about?
Which year?

00:15:16.440 --> 00:15:20.080
From '70s till, maybe, 2000.

00:15:20.160 --> 00:15:26.520
These 30 years, Korea maybe started
from, maybe, 300, 400 GDP per capita,

00:15:26.600 --> 00:15:30.360
and has become, now, like,
you know, 15,000,

00:15:30.440 --> 00:15:33.880
maybe 15,000 around, like, early 2000.

00:15:33.960 --> 00:15:35.880
So that was the journey,

00:15:35.960 --> 00:15:37.760
Korean economy grew quite fast.

00:15:37.840 --> 00:15:40.720
Do you have any North Korean friends
or did you ever?

00:15:40.800 --> 00:15:42.080
Not really.

00:15:42.160 --> 00:15:46.200
Like, it has been separated,
like, more than 70 years now.

00:15:46.280 --> 00:15:50.280
And we are not allowed
to visit North Korea, legally.

00:15:51.360 --> 00:15:54.000
Or if you enter, then you cannot come--
Sorry?

00:15:54.080 --> 00:15:56.000
Are there any North Koreans
in South Korea?

00:15:56.080 --> 00:16:00.360
Yeah, yeah. I mean,
there are quite sizeable defectors.

00:16:00.440 --> 00:16:03.880
Like, they are, uh...

00:16:03.960 --> 00:16:07.440
they are defecting from North Korea

00:16:07.520 --> 00:16:12.440
through third-party countries like China,

00:16:12.520 --> 00:16:15.480
Vietnam, Mongolia, Thailand.

00:16:15.560 --> 00:16:18.840
So I believe-- I don't really remember
the exact number,

00:16:18.920 --> 00:16:23.080
but, I think, at the peak,
there was 10,000 or 20,000 per year,

00:16:23.160 --> 00:16:26.680
the North Koreans defecting North Korea
to enter Chi-- enter South Korea.

00:16:26.760 --> 00:16:29.960
What's Korean society like today?
I have never been.

00:16:30.040 --> 00:16:31.960
-I would love to go.
-Yeah, you should. You should.

00:16:32.040 --> 00:16:35.840
So, you've been in India a while now.
You live in Bangalore, where I also live.

00:16:35.920 --> 00:16:37.120
[Sean] Yeah.

00:16:37.200 --> 00:16:42.120
If you had to draw parallels
between society in Bangalore

00:16:42.200 --> 00:16:44.640
and society in North-- in South Korea.

00:16:44.720 --> 00:16:48.280
-Sorry [laughs awkwardly]
-That mistake happens.

00:16:48.360 --> 00:16:51.800
What is similar, and what is dissimilar?

00:16:53.520 --> 00:16:59.920
Like Korea, South Korea is very--
quite a homogeneous society.

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:02.600
It's getting more cosmopolitan.

00:17:02.680 --> 00:17:07.560
There are more immigrants,
especially from Southeast Asia.

00:17:08.760 --> 00:17:15.760
But I think, overall, 97%, 98%
are all Korean, in terms of population.

00:17:15.840 --> 00:17:19.280
And also, it's a small country.

00:17:19.360 --> 00:17:25.680
I think the land mass is around
100,000 square kilometres,

00:17:25.760 --> 00:17:29.960
which might be, I don't know,
20 times or 40 times smaller than India.

00:17:31.160 --> 00:17:33.040
Old people speak only Korean.

00:17:33.720 --> 00:17:35.400
There are no Hindi-speaking people.

00:17:35.480 --> 00:17:37.160
-English-speaking?
-English...

00:17:37.240 --> 00:17:41.040
I mean, because of education,
it has taken some time,

00:17:41.120 --> 00:17:43.880
but I think young Koreans
speak fairly good English.

00:17:43.960 --> 00:17:46.400
But it's still very much
like the second language, is it?

00:17:46.480 --> 00:17:49.480
Yeah, of course, of course.
So, in school, we...

00:17:49.560 --> 00:17:52.960
I mean, most public schools

00:17:53.040 --> 00:17:57.040
do not use English
as a medium for teaching classes.

00:17:57.120 --> 00:18:00.440
So, English has separate,
sort of, you know, classes,

00:18:00.520 --> 00:18:05.360
which-- maybe three hours a week
or something like that. So, English--

00:18:05.440 --> 00:18:09.560
But we spend a lot of money
to learn English outside the class,

00:18:09.640 --> 00:18:11.440
outside the classroom. So...

00:18:13.040 --> 00:18:16.400
I mean, I also studied a lot of English
outside the school,

00:18:17.240 --> 00:18:19.640
which is still the case.

00:18:19.720 --> 00:18:21.600
Do you live in Bangalore by yourself?

00:18:22.360 --> 00:18:26.720
Yeah. I mean, half voluntarily
and half involuntarily.

00:18:28.600 --> 00:18:32.240
It's kind of a long story,
but to make it short,

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:37.760
when I was working in HQ in Seoul,

00:18:38.560 --> 00:18:42.080
we started to get a sense

00:18:42.160 --> 00:18:47.120
of how India is developing
as a gaming country.

00:18:48.520 --> 00:18:52.840
I think it was in 2019,
I visited the Nazara office.

00:18:52.920 --> 00:18:57.320
Also, I visited some other companies
and VC firms' offices back then.

00:18:59.040 --> 00:19:05.600
And we slowly thought about--
we need to properly spend time in India

00:19:05.680 --> 00:19:09.440
and invest in Indian companies
and work with Indian companies.

00:19:09.520 --> 00:19:11.720
But that was starting from 2019.

00:19:11.800 --> 00:19:16.760
But the chairman, chairman of Krafton,
he travelled to India

00:19:17.800 --> 00:19:20.680
way earlier than me, maybe 2017 or '18.

00:19:20.760 --> 00:19:24.360
And after he came back from there,
from India,

00:19:24.440 --> 00:19:27.880
he told us, like,
the key executives in the company,

00:19:27.960 --> 00:19:29.960
that we should do something in India.

00:19:31.080 --> 00:19:32.720
He didn't tell us how.

00:19:32.800 --> 00:19:35.680
He wanted us to find a way.

00:19:36.960 --> 00:19:39.600
And then we started investments,

00:19:39.680 --> 00:19:42.200
and the first investment
was NODWIN Gaming,

00:19:42.280 --> 00:19:44.800
-which is a subsidiary of...
-Akshat.

00:19:44.880 --> 00:19:47.360
-Yeah, yeah, Akshat. Yeah.
-What do you think of Akshat?

00:19:48.320 --> 00:19:50.480
-Yeah, I mean, like, no-one--
-[Animesh chuckles]

00:19:50.560 --> 00:19:52.880
Why is Animesh laughing?
What do you think of Akshat?

00:19:52.960 --> 00:19:54.200
[Sean] Maybe he doesn't like him.

00:19:54.280 --> 00:19:56.600
He calls himself the Professor,
and I think he's actually the Professor.

00:19:56.680 --> 00:19:58.640
He is the professor of the industry.

00:19:58.720 --> 00:20:01.120
So I have been following Akshat
for, like, a good ten years,

00:20:01.200 --> 00:20:03.400
even before
I got into gaming professionally.

00:20:03.480 --> 00:20:05.120
You know, when NODWIN used to--

00:20:05.200 --> 00:20:07.600
When Akshat himself was a caster,
he used to cast in their own events.

00:20:07.680 --> 00:20:08.920
-Ah, I didn't know it.
-He was, and Gautam.

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:11.040
Both of them,
they used to cast their own events.

00:20:11.760 --> 00:20:16.200
I believe that he has changed the face
of esports in India, specifically.

00:20:16.280 --> 00:20:21.160
To be that consistent with the efforts
when gaming was nothing in India,

00:20:21.240 --> 00:20:25.440
way back in 2014 is, I think,
when he established NODWIN.

00:20:25.520 --> 00:20:27.680
And then, to take some massive steps
like, you know,

00:20:27.760 --> 00:20:30.440
selling his majority to Nazara
way back in the day,

00:20:30.520 --> 00:20:33.320
and then still having that same gist
to build the company.

00:20:33.400 --> 00:20:36.240
And what NODWIN has been doing
over the last one and a half years,

00:20:36.320 --> 00:20:39.440
specifically, I think,
he's a person to look up to.

00:20:39.520 --> 00:20:42.520
And, you know, like, I was smiling
because he's the only person,

00:20:42.600 --> 00:20:44.800
at some point in my career,
I would want to, you know,

00:20:44.880 --> 00:20:48.040
stand shoulder-to-shoulder in the sense
of the enterprise that I built.

00:20:48.120 --> 00:20:50.040
-Mm.
-He's a one-of-a-kind person.

00:20:50.120 --> 00:20:52.120
What are esports, Animesh, if I may ask?

00:20:52.200 --> 00:20:55.240
Esports, it's gaming
in a competitive format

00:20:55.320 --> 00:20:57.560
wherein there are wins and losses.

00:20:57.640 --> 00:20:59.840
It's not about playing inside the game

00:20:59.920 --> 00:21:02.080
and winning and losing,
but there are teams,

00:21:02.160 --> 00:21:05.400
just like how we have in cricket,
and there are a fixed set of players,

00:21:05.480 --> 00:21:07.920
there's a roster, there are teams,
and they are playing with high stakes,

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:09.040
with a big prize, full tournament.

00:21:09.120 --> 00:21:11.920
-And what kind of games, typically?
-It could be anything.

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:14.240
It could be FPS,
which is like CS that you were--

00:21:14.320 --> 00:21:17.120
-that you used to play back in your day.
-Just say full forms. FPS is what?

00:21:17.200 --> 00:21:21.280
FPS is first-person shooter, wherein,
you know, the view format of the game is,

00:21:21.360 --> 00:21:24.200
you have a gun in your hand,
and you can see a first-person view.

00:21:24.280 --> 00:21:27.120
Is that the most popular
kind of game in India, shooting?

00:21:27.200 --> 00:21:28.680
India? Yeah, shooting is very popular.

00:21:28.760 --> 00:21:32.480
But third-person shooting,
TPS, like, you know the game--

00:21:32.560 --> 00:21:35.120
Like, you can see the character fully,
and you're moving.

00:21:35.200 --> 00:21:39.200
So, Krafton, we know now,
Krafton was a $20 billion company.

00:21:39.280 --> 00:21:41.840
Now, it's a $10 billion company,
roundabout.

00:21:43.800 --> 00:21:48.320
How did you get into this industry?
How are you Krafton's CEO now?

00:21:48.400 --> 00:21:50.440
-How did you come to India?
-Krafton India CEO.

00:21:50.520 --> 00:21:52.400
I really like to play games.

00:21:52.480 --> 00:21:55.720
I liked playing games maybe since I was...

00:21:56.720 --> 00:21:58.560
not seven, maybe eight, nine, ten.

00:21:59.760 --> 00:22:02.360
So, I-- Maybe after grade two
or grade three. My father--

00:22:02.440 --> 00:22:03.520
How old are you now, Sean?

00:22:03.600 --> 00:22:06.120
-45. 45.
-Mm-hmm.

00:22:06.200 --> 00:22:08.480
-Nitish also?
-I think we are in the same age.

00:22:08.560 --> 00:22:10.840
-45?
-Yeah. Born in '78, right?

00:22:10.920 --> 00:22:13.360
-'79. '79.
-'79, okay.

00:22:13.440 --> 00:22:18.000
My father could afford, you know, buying,

00:22:18.080 --> 00:22:22.040
back then it was Apple-compatible,
like, 8-bit computers.

00:22:22.120 --> 00:22:24.240
So, my father could afford it.

00:22:25.480 --> 00:22:27.720
And, honestly, back then, you said,

00:22:27.800 --> 00:22:30.360
"I want to learn how to programme",
and things like that,

00:22:30.440 --> 00:22:33.520
but I didn't code too much,
I just played games all the time.

00:22:33.600 --> 00:22:40.200
So that was the beginning of my passion
on gaming as a hobby, mostly.

00:22:40.280 --> 00:22:42.600
And then it grew quite a bit.

00:22:42.680 --> 00:22:46.200
So I played a lot
even in high school and college,

00:22:46.280 --> 00:22:51.360
and back then, like Taiwan,
like Israel, Korean--

00:22:51.440 --> 00:22:53.960
South Korean men should go to the army.

00:22:54.040 --> 00:22:55.560
-But I, back then--
-Conscription.

00:22:55.640 --> 00:22:57.800
Conscription, yeah, it's compulsory,

00:22:57.880 --> 00:23:02.440
but we could choose to work for
high-tech companies, IT companies,

00:23:02.520 --> 00:23:04.560
including gaming companies,

00:23:04.640 --> 00:23:08.000
if you have a certain
engineering certificate...

00:23:09.920 --> 00:23:12.000
after, like, a college degree.

00:23:12.080 --> 00:23:16.720
So I tried that direction
so I could get in--

00:23:16.800 --> 00:23:22.000
get a job as a game developer,
which still exists.

00:23:22.080 --> 00:23:25.960
I could get a job there
as a game designer.

00:23:26.040 --> 00:23:29.880
So, that was my beginning
of a career in gaming.

00:23:29.960 --> 00:23:33.240
But I found that I'm not that good
at game designing or coding,

00:23:33.320 --> 00:23:37.600
so I switched my role
to the marketing and sales side,

00:23:37.680 --> 00:23:41.440
and then, you know, and I--

00:23:41.520 --> 00:23:44.760
That was how I got into the gaming side.

00:23:45.640 --> 00:23:48.600
But I actually didn't like
working for a gaming company.

00:23:48.680 --> 00:23:50.360
I found that it's something different.

00:23:50.440 --> 00:23:53.360
You like playing games, but you don't
really like to work for a gaming company.

00:23:53.440 --> 00:23:57.280
It was-- To be a little casual,

00:23:57.360 --> 00:24:03.080
it was shitty to work for a gaming company
from young, ambitious men perspectives.

00:24:03.160 --> 00:24:06.520
I wanted to work for big companies,
so I switched to banking.

00:24:07.760 --> 00:24:09.120
How old were you then?

00:24:09.200 --> 00:24:12.920
Around ten years after I had an MBA.

00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:14.480
[Sean chuckles]

00:24:15.440 --> 00:24:18.320
So I started my career in gaming in 2000.

00:24:18.400 --> 00:24:20.600
I got an MBA in 2008,

00:24:21.360 --> 00:24:25.480
and I started my career in banking
from 2008 till 2017,

00:24:25.560 --> 00:24:30.880
in which year I joined Krafton
as a CFO of one of the subsidiaries.

00:24:30.960 --> 00:24:33.680
So that's how I got into Krafton.

00:24:33.760 --> 00:24:40.040
And then, you know, we were
very successful in a game called PUBG.

00:24:42.320 --> 00:24:45.680
Did PUBG get banned in India?
You wanna talk about PUBG?

00:24:45.760 --> 00:24:47.320
Yeah. I mean, like, it was more of a--

00:24:47.400 --> 00:24:49.200
It was huge in India, right?
Everybody was playing it.

00:24:49.280 --> 00:24:51.320
Yeah, it's still big, but now it's BGMI.

00:24:51.400 --> 00:24:54.280
Is it the same thing
with a different name?

00:24:54.360 --> 00:24:58.200
No, it's an India-oriented game
that's made specifically for India,

00:24:58.280 --> 00:24:59.760
and it's a different publisher altogether.

00:24:59.840 --> 00:25:02.360
It has nothing to do with PUBG MOBILE.
That was a Tencent game.

00:25:02.440 --> 00:25:03.720
It was a Chinese company,

00:25:03.800 --> 00:25:05.680
the biggest gaming company,
you can call it.

00:25:05.760 --> 00:25:08.440
Tencent owns everything,
like, majority of the stuff.

00:25:08.520 --> 00:25:11.840
What is the relationship
between Tencent and Krafton?

00:25:13.720 --> 00:25:15.280
Tencent is the investor.

00:25:16.600 --> 00:25:20.160
Tencent is an investor
in Krafton before the IPO,

00:25:20.240 --> 00:25:24.120
and they still maintain some share.

00:25:24.200 --> 00:25:26.560
-So BGMI is also you?
-Yeah.

00:25:27.560 --> 00:25:32.440
So you stopped PUBG to build BGMI,
and now that is popular? Like that?

00:25:33.840 --> 00:25:37.320
PUBG is actually--
The original PUBG PC is a Krafton game,

00:25:37.400 --> 00:25:40.960
and then Tencent had the right
to build the mobile version of it.

00:25:41.040 --> 00:25:43.280
And that's globally available,
PUBG MOBILE.

00:25:43.360 --> 00:25:44.480
When India banned PUBG MOBILE,

00:25:44.560 --> 00:25:46.520
Krafton came with the Indian version
of their thing,

00:25:46.600 --> 00:25:50.000
they made their own thing, BGMI,
which is Battlegrounds Mobile India.

00:25:50.080 --> 00:25:52.800
And what are the differences
between these games?

00:25:52.880 --> 00:25:55.840
-One is more appealing than the other?
-[Animesh] Technically, nothing.

00:25:55.920 --> 00:25:58.520
But then, it's more about the origin
and everything else

00:25:58.600 --> 00:26:01.640
that they had to address
to launch the game in India.

00:26:02.400 --> 00:26:04.000
But China does that to everybody, right?

00:26:04.080 --> 00:26:06.680
They don't even allow Facebook
and Google in China, no?

00:26:06.760 --> 00:26:08.280
-That's right.
-[Sean] Yeah.

00:26:08.360 --> 00:26:12.920
And for gaming apps,
or even before the mobile era,

00:26:13.000 --> 00:26:18.800
they allow publishing of games
on an approval basis,

00:26:18.880 --> 00:26:22.720
which is maybe only
China and Vietnam in the world.

00:26:22.800 --> 00:26:27.960
Do you feel like the world is becoming
a more fragmented place?

00:26:28.040 --> 00:26:34.000
Taking inspiration from China,
a country which does not allow

00:26:34.080 --> 00:26:37.720
foreign apps, and replicates it
with their own versions,

00:26:38.760 --> 00:26:44.360
will all IP that touches the citizens
of a certain country,

00:26:44.440 --> 00:26:46.560
in the future, be built in the country

00:26:46.640 --> 00:26:49.640
or at least be owned
or hosted in that country?

00:26:49.720 --> 00:26:51.280
It's a really interesting question

00:26:51.360 --> 00:26:54.720
because I think that
that was the direction we were going,

00:26:54.800 --> 00:26:57.400
and we may go back to that again.

00:26:57.480 --> 00:26:58.960
It was being called splinternet.

00:26:59.040 --> 00:27:04.560
Basically, like, the idea that, because
China has its own internal policies

00:27:04.640 --> 00:27:07.920
where you need a licence,
you also need a local partner,

00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:10.480
they were banning a lot of apps
from the US.

00:27:10.560 --> 00:27:12.600
The current situation now,

00:27:12.680 --> 00:27:16.480
and there was a time
when Trump was president of the US,

00:27:16.560 --> 00:27:17.840
and he was gonna ban TikTok,

00:27:17.920 --> 00:27:20.160
it seemed like we were gonna be
moving more in that direction.

00:27:20.240 --> 00:27:24.360
We might again,
but I do think that that's a danger.

00:27:24.440 --> 00:27:26.760
And actually, though,

00:27:26.840 --> 00:27:30.040
when it came to me starting a company
here in India,

00:27:30.840 --> 00:27:33.960
that was a consideration
because we felt that

00:27:34.040 --> 00:27:36.400
if the world does move towards
a splinternet,

00:27:37.280 --> 00:27:40.280
and if China and Russia are on one side,
I wanna be on the other side.

00:27:40.880 --> 00:27:45.440
And if India is split from China--

00:27:46.080 --> 00:27:49.480
Currently, one thing
that's not well understood

00:27:49.560 --> 00:27:53.560
is that almost all of the top
mobile shooter games

00:27:53.640 --> 00:27:56.200
are all developed
by Chinese companies, effectively.

00:27:56.280 --> 00:27:58.320
Right? And so, like, it's--

00:27:58.400 --> 00:27:59.840
Why is that?

00:28:01.040 --> 00:28:06.760
It's because they have developed
deep expertise in shooters.

00:28:06.840 --> 00:28:08.720
And they also--

00:28:08.800 --> 00:28:13.320
There's been, like, a phenomenon
in which, like, the Tencent teams

00:28:13.400 --> 00:28:17.360
and the Chinese teams have...

00:28:17.440 --> 00:28:21.840
They're just--
The work ethic, the culture,

00:28:21.920 --> 00:28:24.600
they're just kind of crazy
compared to the West. Right?

00:28:24.680 --> 00:28:26.760
Like, the West, right now,
if I'm just being honest...

00:28:26.840 --> 00:28:28.600
We're gonna be honest here, right?

00:28:29.640 --> 00:28:34.160
...is kind of in decline,
where you don't have the same work ethic,

00:28:34.240 --> 00:28:35.920
the same kind of drive.

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:38.960
And I think,
when you look at budgets today,

00:28:39.040 --> 00:28:41.200
in the US, budgets are, like--

00:28:41.280 --> 00:28:43.960
To make a game now
is like $100 million, $300 million

00:28:44.040 --> 00:28:46.680
for, like, an HD, a PC, or console game.

00:28:46.760 --> 00:28:49.000
But, in China, they're working 996.

00:28:49.080 --> 00:28:53.840
They've identified specific strategic
areas that are important to them,

00:28:53.920 --> 00:28:56.120
and then they just go all in
in those areas.

00:28:56.200 --> 00:28:59.000
Mobile, for shooters,
has been one of those areas.

00:28:59.080 --> 00:29:02.960
And so, when you look at every game
that they work on,

00:29:03.040 --> 00:29:06.360
Call of Duty: Mobile
is actually developed by Tencent,

00:29:06.440 --> 00:29:10.280
although they're using the IP
of Activision, for example, right?

00:29:10.360 --> 00:29:12.040
And most of the--

00:29:12.120 --> 00:29:16.400
I would say that the skill, the technical
expertise, currently exists in China.

00:29:17.800 --> 00:29:20.440
One of the objectives of the company
that I started

00:29:20.520 --> 00:29:24.560
was to hopefully do that
here in India as well.

00:29:26.440 --> 00:29:28.400
-But it's been tough.
-Why is that?

00:29:28.480 --> 00:29:29.680
[chuckles awkwardly]

00:29:29.760 --> 00:29:31.200
I think that...

00:29:32.440 --> 00:29:35.640
So, the Indian game development
ecosystem is still early.

00:29:35.720 --> 00:29:40.640
And if you look at the historical context
of the Indian game development ecosystem,

00:29:41.480 --> 00:29:43.320
it's been one that's more--

00:29:44.120 --> 00:29:46.360
that has been more of
a services orientation, right?

00:29:46.440 --> 00:29:51.080
And so, the model in India, in terms
of the historical context,

00:29:51.160 --> 00:29:53.520
has been taking games from the West,

00:29:53.600 --> 00:29:57.200
at least for mobile, that are in decline,

00:29:57.280 --> 00:30:02.600
and then getting a team in India
to live operate it for... greater margins,

00:30:02.680 --> 00:30:04.400
right, for lower costs.

00:30:04.480 --> 00:30:07.600
And so, because of
that historical context,

00:30:07.680 --> 00:30:10.040
there hasn't been, like...

00:30:10.960 --> 00:30:13.320
a culture, a knowledge,

00:30:13.400 --> 00:30:16.360
a skill set of new game development
in India yet.

00:30:16.440 --> 00:30:17.680
I'm sure it's burgeoning,

00:30:17.760 --> 00:30:22.360
and there's certainly a lot of, you know,
successful local game companies, but--

00:30:22.440 --> 00:30:24.320
Has there been a single game in India,

00:30:24.400 --> 00:30:30.080
built in India, that has reached scale
in a true sense?

00:30:30.160 --> 00:30:34.080
So, I believe the game
at the highest scale

00:30:34.160 --> 00:30:37.880
from a downloads perspective
is Gametion's Ludo King,

00:30:37.960 --> 00:30:40.880
-but, really, it's--
-Gametion.

00:30:40.960 --> 00:30:42.320
-Gametion.
-Yeah.

00:30:42.400 --> 00:30:44.760
-Gametion. That's an Indian company?
-Yes, yes.

00:30:44.840 --> 00:30:48.720
When I look at the charts,
that's the only game that I see come,

00:30:48.800 --> 00:30:52.960
you know, on the top charts... globally.

00:30:53.720 --> 00:30:55.960
But still,
it's largely an Indian audience,

00:30:56.040 --> 00:30:58.600
because there's so many Indians
that love ludo.

00:30:58.680 --> 00:31:00.640
In what scale are we talking?

00:31:00.720 --> 00:31:02.480
In terms of revenue
coming out of the game?

00:31:02.560 --> 00:31:05.560
I think that it has almost
very little revenue, right? [chuckles]

00:31:05.640 --> 00:31:08.800
But from a downloads perspective,
it's very active.

00:31:08.880 --> 00:31:11.360
They've recently crossed
a billion downloads, I think.

00:31:11.440 --> 00:31:13.200
-[Sean] Yeah.
-[Nitish] In India.

00:31:13.280 --> 00:31:17.440
-But, yeah, monetisation is a challenge.
-Right.

00:31:17.520 --> 00:31:20.360
And I think that's the opportunity
for India, though, right?

00:31:20.440 --> 00:31:26.720
Which is, like, if India can develop
a similar kind of work ethic,

00:31:26.800 --> 00:31:32.360
skill set, and knowledge of monetisation,
and how to monetise more strongly,

00:31:32.440 --> 00:31:34.360
then, I think
India has a great opportunity.

00:31:34.440 --> 00:31:39.040
You know, just to add to that, Nikhil,
we've been around for so long, right,

00:31:39.120 --> 00:31:42.800
so we've really seen the whole evolution
of the Indian gaming industry,

00:31:42.880 --> 00:31:47.480
right from late '90s
to where we are today in '24.

00:31:47.560 --> 00:31:49.960
I think one more reason is that,
unlike China, et cetera,

00:31:50.040 --> 00:31:52.640
which had a large PC gaming culture,

00:31:52.720 --> 00:31:55.320
gaming cafes, et cetera,

00:31:55.400 --> 00:31:56.880
for a very long period of time,

00:31:57.880 --> 00:32:01.240
India has really been
a mobile-gaming-first nation.

00:32:01.320 --> 00:32:02.680
So, most people playing games,

00:32:02.760 --> 00:32:06.320
the first experience
has been the mobile phone,

00:32:06.400 --> 00:32:07.640
very casual gaming.

00:32:07.720 --> 00:32:11.280
So just that culture
takes time to develop.

00:32:11.360 --> 00:32:13.320
Even when you're thinking
as a game designer,

00:32:13.400 --> 00:32:15.680
as a game developer, there's an evolution.

00:32:15.760 --> 00:32:18.160
Up to 2010, you would not see that at all.

00:32:18.240 --> 00:32:19.440
Then, you had Zyngas of the world

00:32:19.520 --> 00:32:21.720
and Electronic Arts of the world
set up shop,

00:32:21.800 --> 00:32:26.560
back offices in Bangalore
and Hyderabad, et cetera,

00:32:26.640 --> 00:32:29.440
and you've started seeing
some of those come out,

00:32:29.520 --> 00:32:31.680
set up some companies
which are now becoming successful.

00:32:31.760 --> 00:32:33.400
So I think we're going up that curve,

00:32:33.480 --> 00:32:35.840
hopefully, we will accelerate
up that curve.

00:32:35.920 --> 00:32:38.680
But I think he was making a good point.

00:32:38.760 --> 00:32:41.840
Joseph is saying there is--

00:32:41.920 --> 00:32:46.920
the ecosystem in India is not capable
of producing a game...

00:32:48.640 --> 00:32:51.440
which can really compete
on the world stage.

00:32:51.520 --> 00:32:54.200
What do you think India has to change
to change that?

00:32:54.280 --> 00:32:57.680
I think there has to be
a few things that change.

00:32:57.760 --> 00:33:00.600
I would say, probably,
the most important thing...

00:33:01.760 --> 00:33:02.760
is talent.

00:33:02.840 --> 00:33:06.040
So, look, I live in Silicon Valley, okay?

00:33:06.120 --> 00:33:10.600
The smartest guys in Silicon Valley
are all Indian.

00:33:10.680 --> 00:33:14.000
-[all chuckling]
-And so, they certainly have--

00:33:14.080 --> 00:33:16.800
Like, Indians can be
the smartest anywhere.

00:33:16.880 --> 00:33:21.080
They're-- You know, all the tech CEOs
are all Indian in Silicon Valley.

00:33:21.160 --> 00:33:22.720
[Nikhil] Do you think that's the problem?

00:33:22.800 --> 00:33:24.320
The smart ones are going
out of the country?

00:33:24.400 --> 00:33:25.560
That's one of the problems.

00:33:25.640 --> 00:33:29.320
But I think that gaming in India
has a double problem.

00:33:29.400 --> 00:33:31.680
So, first, yes,

00:33:32.640 --> 00:33:37.480
there are a lot of people in India,
when they get an opportunity to,

00:33:37.560 --> 00:33:40.720
like, 7x, 10x their salary
by going abroad,

00:33:40.800 --> 00:33:42.920
and they have that opportunity

00:33:43.000 --> 00:33:47.400
because they've developed
a skill set here, then they'll jump.

00:33:47.480 --> 00:33:50.040
I think the other thing
is more of a cultural issue

00:33:50.120 --> 00:33:53.960
that I have discovered over the past
few years that I've been here in India,

00:33:54.040 --> 00:33:58.760
which is that gaming, at least--
And you guys, please disagree with me.

00:33:58.840 --> 00:34:03.520
But, in my experience, it seems like
gaming is not looked upon favourably

00:34:03.600 --> 00:34:05.520
-by a lot of Indian parents.
-[Sean] Mm.

00:34:05.600 --> 00:34:08.320
And so, when somebody
wants to go into gaming,

00:34:08.400 --> 00:34:10.960
they really have to
want to go into gaming.

00:34:11.680 --> 00:34:14.760
But, otherwise,
I think a lot of the parents,

00:34:14.840 --> 00:34:19.320
they, typically, would want to go
to join some high-tech firm,

00:34:19.400 --> 00:34:22.680
an Amazon, a Google, a Facebook,
a company like that,

00:34:23.600 --> 00:34:25.320
rather than join a gaming company.

00:34:25.400 --> 00:34:29.040
And so, the image of a gaming company--
Unlike in the West, right?

00:34:29.120 --> 00:34:32.920
Like, in the West, joining a game company
is looked upon very favourably

00:34:33.000 --> 00:34:34.880
for a number of reasons, right?

00:34:34.960 --> 00:34:39.840
It generally, like,
leads in terms of innovation.

00:34:39.920 --> 00:34:42.600
A lot of the people that go,
that are in gaming,

00:34:42.680 --> 00:34:47.280
actually are highly coveted by Facebook,
Google, and the high-tech companies.

00:34:48.280 --> 00:34:52.920
But that kind of feeling
and that kind of...

00:34:53.000 --> 00:34:59.080
that kind of orientation towards gaming
in the US versus India is so different.

00:34:59.160 --> 00:35:01.800
So, then, you not only
lose talent overseas,

00:35:01.880 --> 00:35:05.120
but you also lose talent
to other local Indian industries.

00:35:05.200 --> 00:35:06.200
Yeah.

00:35:06.280 --> 00:35:07.720
And what do you think...

00:35:08.880 --> 00:35:12.600
should change in India to culturally...

00:35:13.520 --> 00:35:16.560
make gaming,
a career in gaming, look cool?

00:35:16.640 --> 00:35:19.160
I think it's more of an education, right?

00:35:19.240 --> 00:35:24.400
So I can name so many of my friends
that went from gaming

00:35:24.480 --> 00:35:28.360
to join Facebook or Amazon or Netflix.

00:35:28.440 --> 00:35:33.400
And I think
if some of the Indian employees here

00:35:33.480 --> 00:35:36.680
or people who are considering
going into gaming understood,

00:35:36.760 --> 00:35:41.800
"Wow, I didn't know that those companies
really sought people from gaming,

00:35:41.880 --> 00:35:45.840
because gaming is so innovative
and it is so cross-disciplinary,

00:35:45.920 --> 00:35:49.320
and you have to learn a lot of
complex skills when you're in gaming."

00:35:49.400 --> 00:35:52.600
So that is not well understood here.

00:35:52.680 --> 00:35:57.600
And I think that the other thing, also,
that hasn't happened is that,

00:35:57.680 --> 00:36:04.360
because, again, the historical context
of a lot of the Indian gaming companies

00:36:04.440 --> 00:36:09.080
has been more on the live ops
and services orientation,

00:36:09.160 --> 00:36:13.200
that there hasn't been
the level of poaching

00:36:13.280 --> 00:36:15.760
or of the high-tech companies

00:36:15.840 --> 00:36:18.920
trying to hire people
out of Indian gaming companies yet.

00:36:19.880 --> 00:36:23.640
And I think, when that happens--
And I think that happens from people

00:36:23.720 --> 00:36:28.240
who have learned from a company building
new games that are very successful, right?

00:36:28.320 --> 00:36:33.080
Then they'll be poached
fairly regularly or sought after.

00:36:33.160 --> 00:36:35.080
I think that's when it becomes
more popular.

00:36:35.160 --> 00:36:36.640
Can you tell me a way?

00:36:36.720 --> 00:36:41.840
Assume I'm a young,
20-year-old Indian boy/girl,

00:36:41.920 --> 00:36:44.760
and I want to get a job
at Lila Games, your company,

00:36:44.840 --> 00:36:46.160
what should I learn?

00:36:47.360 --> 00:36:52.280
Well, I think it would depend on
the specific role that you're looking for.

00:36:52.360 --> 00:36:55.520
So, if it's product management,
I would be looking for one thing.

00:36:55.600 --> 00:36:57.800
If it's engineering,
it'd be completely different.

00:36:57.880 --> 00:37:02.000
But I would say, like, a general bit
of advice for anyone that's new,

00:37:02.080 --> 00:37:04.200
looking to join a gaming company, is to...

00:37:04.800 --> 00:37:08.640
essentially, think outside of the resume
and to build...

00:37:08.720 --> 00:37:10.480
I call it a digital footprint.

00:37:10.560 --> 00:37:12.280
But, basically, like,

00:37:12.360 --> 00:37:16.080
show me what you know,
show me what you can do

00:37:16.160 --> 00:37:18.320
that's just not, like,
lines on your resume.

00:37:18.400 --> 00:37:23.160
So whether it's projects
or whether it's, like, blog posts

00:37:23.240 --> 00:37:27.720
where I can see how you think,
because I will say, you know,

00:37:27.800 --> 00:37:31.000
having been recruiting here
for the last three and a half years

00:37:31.080 --> 00:37:36.520
and having interviewed and looked at
thousands and thousands of resumes,

00:37:36.600 --> 00:37:40.320
I would say that most people
generally don't stand out

00:37:40.400 --> 00:37:44.160
because they don't actually show me
anything that they've done

00:37:44.240 --> 00:37:46.600
that really tells me
that they care about gaming,

00:37:46.680 --> 00:37:48.600
that they've thought about gaming.

00:37:48.680 --> 00:37:53.640
So anyone that has a blog post,
a project that they've put onto a website,

00:37:53.720 --> 00:37:57.760
any kind of additional, kind of,
digital footprint outside of their resume

00:37:57.840 --> 00:38:01.480
really shows me that this is somebody
that I need to pay attention to.

00:38:01.560 --> 00:38:07.160
So I'll absolutely look at a resume
with, like, links to projects, blog posts,

00:38:07.240 --> 00:38:12.480
YouTube videos, anything of that nature,
more than just another resume, right?

00:38:12.560 --> 00:38:15.800
Interesting. Would you like to tell us
more about yourself, Joseph?

00:38:15.880 --> 00:38:17.480
Like, generally, life?

00:38:17.560 --> 00:38:21.960
I'm a guy that's trying to do
something meaningful before I die.

00:38:23.280 --> 00:38:25.920
So, you know, I think--

00:38:26.000 --> 00:38:27.800
So, in terms of my career,

00:38:27.880 --> 00:38:33.720
I kind of worked in
software development, initially.

00:38:33.800 --> 00:38:35.840
Then I moved into management consulting.

00:38:35.920 --> 00:38:42.200
Then, around 2010, 2011,
started a gaming company, unsuccessfully.

00:38:43.200 --> 00:38:47.280
Then went into, like, kind of
consulting with big Asian publishers,

00:38:47.360 --> 00:38:52.920
trying to, you know, publish games,
mobile games for the Western market.

00:38:53.000 --> 00:38:54.440
Why do they call them publishers?

00:38:54.520 --> 00:38:59.400
[Joseph] Publishers generally
finance and distribute games.

00:38:59.480 --> 00:39:02.360
So their model is to, like,
not do the development.

00:39:02.440 --> 00:39:05.560
They work with another company
that actually develops the games.

00:39:05.640 --> 00:39:10.680
But then they would help get those games
launched into market and distributed.

00:39:10.760 --> 00:39:12.120
And so there's a financing component,

00:39:12.200 --> 00:39:15.040
but there's also a distribution
and marketing component as well.

00:39:15.120 --> 00:39:18.240
Can you give me the example
of a publisher and a game developer?

00:39:18.320 --> 00:39:20.800
-The distinction?
-Sure.

00:39:20.880 --> 00:39:24.720
So, for example-- I mean,
I think Krafton recently--

00:39:24.800 --> 00:39:29.360
Like, just to kind of give you
a very live example,

00:39:29.440 --> 00:39:32.200
Krafton worked with a company
called ZeptoLab

00:39:32.280 --> 00:39:35.200
that has a game for the global market,

00:39:35.280 --> 00:39:38.560
and they worked with them to make
an Indian-specific version of the game.

00:39:38.640 --> 00:39:40.160
So I don't know
what the exact deal terms were,

00:39:40.240 --> 00:39:42.320
but I assume that they would pay for

00:39:42.400 --> 00:39:45.240
-part or full development cost.
-Revenue share. Yup.

00:39:45.320 --> 00:39:46.680
They would have a revenue share with them,

00:39:46.760 --> 00:39:51.360
may potentially give them a guarantee
of some kind, some initial payment,

00:39:51.440 --> 00:39:56.000
and then it would be up to Krafton to
actually market and distribute the game.

00:39:56.080 --> 00:40:00.080
The developer, after they finished
developing the game, would either--

00:40:00.160 --> 00:40:02.000
For a premium game, they'd be done.

00:40:02.080 --> 00:40:06.800
For a live-operated, free-to-play game,
they would continue to operate the game

00:40:06.880 --> 00:40:09.400
and then share in the success of the game
through a revenue share.

00:40:10.520 --> 00:40:12.000
Interesting.

00:40:12.080 --> 00:40:14.920
And when I read that
you were at SEGA Games,

00:40:15.000 --> 00:40:18.280
by SEGA, do you mean that console
which we used to have back in the year?

00:40:18.360 --> 00:40:21.320
-Yeah, so-- [chuckles]
-I remember playing that.

00:40:21.400 --> 00:40:25.840
So, after I kind of did consulting,

00:40:25.920 --> 00:40:28.480
I joined a company called FunPlus,

00:40:28.560 --> 00:40:31.280
and I actually had a pretty big success.

00:40:31.360 --> 00:40:33.800
And the model that I learned at FunPlus

00:40:33.880 --> 00:40:35.960
is the model that
I'm actually trying to bring to India.

00:40:36.040 --> 00:40:40.960
And so, at FunPlus, we had something
that I call a leads-based model.

00:40:41.040 --> 00:40:46.960
But, essentially, we took, at that time,
a fairly inexperienced team in Beijing.

00:40:47.040 --> 00:40:51.280
And this was during a period--
Like, 2014-15 or so,

00:40:51.360 --> 00:40:54.480
when China was not
as dominant as it is today,

00:40:54.560 --> 00:40:57.360
and we had a team in Beijing,

00:40:57.440 --> 00:41:00.920
we brought experts
from around the world in various areas

00:41:01.000 --> 00:41:02.400
that the team was not strong in.

00:41:03.120 --> 00:41:05.360
We brought them to China,
had them teach the team,

00:41:05.440 --> 00:41:08.840
and then we developed games out of China.

00:41:08.920 --> 00:41:10.760
The game that I developed was called
King of Avalon,

00:41:10.840 --> 00:41:14.080
but that turned out to be
a pretty big success.

00:41:14.160 --> 00:41:17.640
And then, after FunPlus,

00:41:17.720 --> 00:41:22.200
I joined SEGA, basically,
in their mobile games division.

00:41:22.280 --> 00:41:23.440
So, basically--

00:41:23.520 --> 00:41:26.440
Was SEGA the machine on which we used
to play Contra and Mario and all that?

00:41:26.520 --> 00:41:28.560
-SEGA, that's right.
-Yes.

00:41:28.640 --> 00:41:32.840
I've played a lot of that.
Contra, Mario Brothers...

00:41:32.920 --> 00:41:35.960
Yeah, SEGA exited hardware,

00:41:36.040 --> 00:41:38.200
the console business,
a number of years ago,

00:41:38.280 --> 00:41:44.000
but still develops games through
a number of different game studios,

00:41:44.080 --> 00:41:48.440
and is actually diversified in, like,
hotels, pachinko, and things like that.

00:41:48.520 --> 00:41:50.240
Like, a lot of other things as well.

00:41:50.320 --> 00:41:53.800
You know, funnily enough, when you said--
when you mentioned earlier,

00:41:53.880 --> 00:41:55.560
gaming centres.

00:41:55.640 --> 00:42:00.520
When I was a kid growing up,
I'm thinking age six or seven,

00:42:01.600 --> 00:42:04.720
there used to be gaming centres
where there would be SEGA machines,

00:42:04.800 --> 00:42:08.440
and you would pay per hour,
and play Contra for an hour.

00:42:08.520 --> 00:42:11.000
They're more like arcade machines.
Arcade centres, yeah.

00:42:11.080 --> 00:42:14.320
Oh, just to finish the loop,

00:42:14.400 --> 00:42:18.680
after SEGA, I joined NBCUniversal,
which is a big media company,

00:42:18.760 --> 00:42:22.400
and then started this company
about three and a half years ago.

00:42:24.440 --> 00:42:27.160
Okay, moving to the youngest one here.

00:42:27.240 --> 00:42:28.480
[Animesh] Yeah,
that's what I was thinking.

00:42:28.560 --> 00:42:33.560
I've had the shortest professional run
in the gaming industry until now.

00:42:33.640 --> 00:42:37.360
-Your online name is 8bit_thug.
-Yeah.

00:42:37.440 --> 00:42:39.920
Where was that inspired from?

00:42:40.000 --> 00:42:42.200
Do you feel like
you're a thug in real life?

00:42:42.280 --> 00:42:45.800
Not really. People do think
that I'm a little bit of, like,

00:42:45.880 --> 00:42:49.360
have a bully-ish nature in
the gaming industry, but that's not true.

00:42:49.440 --> 00:42:51.320
I think that's just because, you know,

00:42:51.400 --> 00:42:53.280
things that I have luckily
been able to do,

00:42:53.360 --> 00:42:55.800
which I'm very proud of,
across the last six years.

00:42:55.880 --> 00:42:57.400
The name story is very simple.

00:42:57.480 --> 00:43:00.280
8bit was my clan name
in a game called Clash Royale,

00:43:00.360 --> 00:43:03.680
which I was heavily invested into
as a casual gamer, not professionally.

00:43:03.760 --> 00:43:07.680
I was pursuing my CA Inters,
and I had something to do,

00:43:07.760 --> 00:43:10.600
because I didn't want to step out,
spend a lot of time studying.

00:43:10.680 --> 00:43:13.000
So that was a game
I was heavily invested into.

00:43:13.080 --> 00:43:14.600
I made a clan, 8bit.

00:43:14.680 --> 00:43:17.160
-That's how the prefix of my name came in.
-[Nikhil] Mm-hmm.

00:43:17.240 --> 00:43:21.240
And Thug is actually a short form
of Thug Life,

00:43:21.320 --> 00:43:24.480
which is also from a song
from a movie called Dictator.

00:43:24.560 --> 00:43:25.920
College days, nothing to do.

00:43:26.000 --> 00:43:29.960
I said, it's a good name, you know,
getting fascinated by movies.

00:43:30.040 --> 00:43:33.160
And then, actually,
when I used to play PUBG MOBILE,

00:43:33.240 --> 00:43:35.960
it did not take "8bit Thug Life"
as my full name.

00:43:36.040 --> 00:43:38.440
So I left out "Life"
and it's 8bit_thug, and rest is history.

00:43:39.120 --> 00:43:40.360
Why 8bit?

00:43:40.440 --> 00:43:41.920
8bit, my team name.

00:43:42.000 --> 00:43:44.720
Then why did you pick 8bit for your team?

00:43:44.800 --> 00:43:46.160
Okay, so, interesting question.

00:43:46.240 --> 00:43:48.640
When I was playing Clash Royale,
there were eight people

00:43:48.720 --> 00:43:53.240
from across the world, who met
in the game, who founded 8bit.

00:43:53.320 --> 00:43:57.960
So, there was one guy from Austria,
couple from US, one from Australia.

00:43:58.040 --> 00:44:01.760
So we used to call ourselves eight bits
of the entire clan system.

00:44:01.840 --> 00:44:04.240
And then, we all just fell off.

00:44:04.320 --> 00:44:07.280
They fell off, and I just continued
the name and established--

00:44:07.360 --> 00:44:08.680
I thought that-- Thank you.

00:44:08.760 --> 00:44:12.760
I thought that you are, like, you know,
a fan of classic... classic games.

00:44:12.840 --> 00:44:14.000
Oh, no, not really.

00:44:14.080 --> 00:44:17.840
-[Sean] From 8-bit eras.
-High graphic-intensive games, yeah.

00:44:17.920 --> 00:44:23.480
So, I'm gonna ask you most questions
'cause you're the protagonist

00:44:23.560 --> 00:44:27.000
of the Indian gaming story in a way,
or the career in gaming.

00:44:27.080 --> 00:44:28.320
Right.

00:44:28.400 --> 00:44:30.360
You came from a non-gaming background,

00:44:30.440 --> 00:44:32.440
and today,
you're a professional gamer in India.

00:44:32.520 --> 00:44:34.960
So, tell us the story from the beginning,

00:44:36.280 --> 00:44:39.760
and then I'll ask you things like
money, opportunity, all of that.

00:44:39.840 --> 00:44:41.520
So, how did you enter gaming?

00:44:41.600 --> 00:44:44.360
Right, so I'll go back to the beginning.

00:44:44.440 --> 00:44:45.600
Actually, I was--

00:44:45.680 --> 00:44:48.360
I come from a middle-class family.
My father is a chartered accountant.

00:44:48.440 --> 00:44:50.360
My sister is a chartered accountant.
I was pursuing--

00:44:50.440 --> 00:44:53.320
You're gonna get trolled for calling
chartered accountant middle class,

00:44:53.400 --> 00:44:54.440
but continue.

00:44:54.520 --> 00:44:56.360
-[laughter]
-Uh, no.

00:44:56.440 --> 00:44:57.840
Yeah, but it is a story.

00:44:57.920 --> 00:45:01.880
Even I realised right now that how--
how I was in a middle-class segment

00:45:01.960 --> 00:45:05.360
when my father was a CA,
but, all right, that's a different story.

00:45:05.440 --> 00:45:09.280
And I was pursuing CA. My life goal
was inspired from Hrithik Roshan, ZNMD.

00:45:10.760 --> 00:45:14.040
Goldman Sachs. I was doing CFA.
I cleared CFA Level I.

00:45:14.120 --> 00:45:16.800
I pursued FRM. I cleared its Level 1.

00:45:16.880 --> 00:45:21.000
But I did all of this when
I was shy of 24, like, six years back.

00:45:21.080 --> 00:45:23.880
So I realised--
And I used to play a lot of games,

00:45:23.960 --> 00:45:25.560
but not professionally, just play games,

00:45:25.640 --> 00:45:29.640
watch some of the biggest streamers
at that point, like Ninja, Shroud,

00:45:29.720 --> 00:45:31.360
and a game called Fortnite,

00:45:31.440 --> 00:45:34.280
which is still one of the very popular
titles, caught my attention.

00:45:34.360 --> 00:45:35.920
I don't know why.

00:45:36.000 --> 00:45:38.160
Like, today, I have an answer
why people watch games,

00:45:38.240 --> 00:45:39.640
but, then, I did not have an answer,

00:45:39.720 --> 00:45:42.120
and I used to wake up
at 6:30 a.m., Indian time,

00:45:42.200 --> 00:45:45.160
in Bangalore, just to watch Ninja
or these guys go live.

00:45:45.240 --> 00:45:47.400
Because of the time zone difference--
They used to--

00:45:47.480 --> 00:45:49.800
Why? I still don't get it.
When I can play...

00:45:51.200 --> 00:45:54.880
-I guess one can say the same about sport.
-That's the answer.

00:45:54.960 --> 00:45:56.720
The question itself is the answer.

00:45:56.800 --> 00:45:58.440
I have never watched anybody's stream,

00:45:59.400 --> 00:46:01.040
but I'm trying to wrap my head around

00:46:01.120 --> 00:46:04.440
why is it so much fun
to watch someone play a video game.

00:46:04.520 --> 00:46:07.920
I think the nature of video games
that's being played,

00:46:08.000 --> 00:46:10.920
the competitiveness that it brings,
the storyline that it brings,

00:46:11.000 --> 00:46:14.000
I think a lot of great-- greatest content
creators are great storytellers.

00:46:14.080 --> 00:46:15.720
So they bring a different angle, too,

00:46:15.800 --> 00:46:18.160
apart from the story
that is within the game.

00:46:18.240 --> 00:46:21.120
So those are a few things
that really holds the audience together.

00:46:21.200 --> 00:46:23.640
Also, the competitive side
is the biggest part of it.

00:46:23.720 --> 00:46:25.480
-So, wait, somebody is watching a game...
-[Animesh] Right.

00:46:25.560 --> 00:46:28.800
...there is a content creator, on top
of the game, who's giving commentary,

00:46:28.880 --> 00:46:30.800
-and you're watching the commentary?
-Right.

00:46:30.880 --> 00:46:35.280
Because, you know, the way--
I think when you play story-mode games--

00:46:35.360 --> 00:46:37.800
Story-mode games are games
which have, you know, a particular story,

00:46:37.880 --> 00:46:39.760
and once you finish the story,
the game is done.

00:46:39.840 --> 00:46:41.240
You don't need to play it again.

00:46:41.320 --> 00:46:43.360
I think a lot of the greatest
content creators

00:46:43.440 --> 00:46:44.960
that I've seen are big gamers,

00:46:45.040 --> 00:46:47.240
they are excellent storytellers.

00:46:47.320 --> 00:46:49.200
Give me some examples.

00:46:49.280 --> 00:46:52.680
I think if you look at a story-mode game,
something like God of War,

00:46:52.760 --> 00:46:55.880
very popular game way back
in my school days as well,

00:46:55.960 --> 00:46:57.120
I used to play it on the PS2.

00:46:57.200 --> 00:47:00.320
-So, once the story is over, it's done.
-It's done, the game is done.

00:47:00.400 --> 00:47:02.600
And then you move on
to the next one. Yeah.

00:47:02.680 --> 00:47:05.120
And then there are games
like GTA that go on forever.

00:47:05.200 --> 00:47:08.240
Then there have been games
like Grand Theft Auto that go on forever.

00:47:08.320 --> 00:47:11.560
So that's one part of watching streams
or content.

00:47:11.640 --> 00:47:14.800
The second part is, obviously,
when you play games like BGMI or Valorant,

00:47:14.880 --> 00:47:18.480
which have a competitive angle to it,
which have a win condition to it.

00:47:18.560 --> 00:47:22.640
So, you know, when some of the famous
names who have represented India,

00:47:22.720 --> 00:47:25.880
who have played tournaments,
won in those tournaments,

00:47:25.960 --> 00:47:28.480
and when they go out and show it
to the public how it's done,

00:47:28.560 --> 00:47:31.560
I think that really catches
the attention of a lot of people.

00:47:31.640 --> 00:47:33.880
I think it has evolved
over the last three, four years.

00:47:33.960 --> 00:47:35.960
We have a lot of fun elements
because it's a very--

00:47:36.040 --> 00:47:38.920
You know, these games like BGMI, Valorant,
where you're playing as a squad,

00:47:39.000 --> 00:47:40.400
it has a lot of fun elements to it

00:47:40.480 --> 00:47:42.840
because you are connecting socially
to each other, you are talking.

00:47:42.920 --> 00:47:44.400
So those conversations become fun.

00:47:44.480 --> 00:47:46.440
I mean, like, why did we use--

00:47:46.520 --> 00:47:49.360
Even I have watched Kyunki Saas Bhi
Kabhi Bahu Thi. What was it?

00:47:49.440 --> 00:47:50.720
It was just those conversations--

00:47:50.800 --> 00:47:52.360
-How old are you? 28, no?
-28.

00:47:53.800 --> 00:47:55.480
That was my era,
Kyunki Saas Bhi Kabhi Bahu Thi.

00:47:55.560 --> 00:47:57.920
No, but my era also.
But I was in class one.

00:47:58.000 --> 00:48:01.120
You must have seen the later Tulsis
and Mihirs, not the original ones.

00:48:01.200 --> 00:48:03.320
[Animesh] Yeah, possibly,
but I have seen all their deaths.

00:48:03.400 --> 00:48:05.600
-I have seen five Mihirs, I guess.
-Not Smriti Irani.

00:48:05.680 --> 00:48:07.240
No, I have seen Smriti Irani. Yeah.

00:48:07.880 --> 00:48:11.120
-She was so good, right?
-Yeah, she was good. Definitely.

00:48:11.200 --> 00:48:13.920
So I believe that that's the reason
why people watch games.

00:48:14.000 --> 00:48:18.040
It's just about-- they play the game,
now they relate to it. It's like cricket.

00:48:18.120 --> 00:48:19.920
You have played cricket,
everyone has played

00:48:20.000 --> 00:48:22.600
or at least heard a lot about cricket,
now you're getting to--

00:48:22.680 --> 00:48:25.320
When you see IPL, you get to see
a different angle of cricket.

00:48:25.400 --> 00:48:28.040
Believe me, T20 World Cup
is never the same as IPL.

00:48:28.120 --> 00:48:30.440
The masala that comes with IPL
is the reason why

00:48:30.520 --> 00:48:32.120
so many people are glued to it.

00:48:32.200 --> 00:48:33.720
Like, you know,
it becomes a festival in India.

00:48:33.800 --> 00:48:37.280
I think that's the case with people
watching gaming streamers.

00:48:37.360 --> 00:48:40.520
You know, it becomes a different version
of that game for them.

00:48:40.600 --> 00:48:43.880
And while you're watching a stream,
are you all talking to each other?

00:48:43.960 --> 00:48:47.560
While I'm watching, if I'm a viewer,
I'll be chatting with other people

00:48:47.640 --> 00:48:48.640
who are watching my stream.

00:48:48.720 --> 00:48:52.400
That's what happens on YouTube
and Twitch or Loco, as a matter of fact.

00:48:52.480 --> 00:48:56.040
But, as a player, if I'm playing
a solo-person story-mode game,

00:48:56.120 --> 00:48:58.320
then I might not be chatting
with anyone else,

00:48:58.400 --> 00:49:00.800
but I'm playing squad games,
I'll be chatting with my teammates.

00:49:00.880 --> 00:49:02.600
-I'm gonna blatantly ask a question.
-[Animesh] Right.

00:49:02.680 --> 00:49:05.440
As an Indian full-time gamer,

00:49:06.560 --> 00:49:12.440
how much do successful streamers,
gamers make in India?

00:49:12.520 --> 00:49:15.280
How viable is it
as a "profession" profession?

00:49:15.360 --> 00:49:17.880
I think it's very skewed,
to be very honest.

00:49:17.960 --> 00:49:21.360
The top gamers and top streamers
make a lot of money, and they are--

00:49:21.440 --> 00:49:23.040
Like, if you go
to the bottom of the chart,

00:49:23.120 --> 00:49:24.720
people are not making money at all.

00:49:24.800 --> 00:49:26.920
Describe "lot."
Who's the number one gamer?

00:49:27.000 --> 00:49:29.720
$1 million comfortably in a year.

00:49:29.800 --> 00:49:32.440
-This is a gamer.
-This is a gaming content creator.

00:49:32.520 --> 00:49:34.960
-It has to be a streamer at the other end.
-Who's the top in India?

00:49:35.040 --> 00:49:38.760
I think it could be MortaL,
sc0ut, Mythpat,

00:49:38.840 --> 00:49:40.400
-and Payal--
-[Sean] Like, a few million subscribers

00:49:40.480 --> 00:49:41.840
-on YouTube.
-Yeah, million subscribers.

00:49:41.920 --> 00:49:43.800
Then we have techno gamers.

00:49:43.880 --> 00:49:47.280
They are comfortably making,
you know, money around that number.

00:49:47.360 --> 00:49:50.800
-And this money comes from?
-Brand endorsements plus content.

00:49:50.880 --> 00:49:53.040
Brand endorsements
really form a big chunk.

00:49:53.120 --> 00:49:54.360
-YouTube content?
-Yeah, YouTube content.

00:49:54.440 --> 00:49:57.160
-YouTube or Instagram.
-Is it like PewDiePie?

00:49:57.240 --> 00:50:00.080
I remember looking at YouTube
for a long time.

00:50:00.160 --> 00:50:02.160
PewDiePie had the largest subscribers.

00:50:02.240 --> 00:50:04.120
-This is like that?
-Sort of, yes.

00:50:04.200 --> 00:50:06.200
He has been an inherent gamer.

00:50:06.280 --> 00:50:08.960
Like, he has played games
for quite a bit on his channel.

00:50:09.040 --> 00:50:10.320
So something of that kind.

00:50:10.400 --> 00:50:12.920
Okay, remove content creators.
[clears throat]

00:50:13.760 --> 00:50:16.000
-"Gamer" gamer.
-A "gamer" gamer,

00:50:16.080 --> 00:50:22.000
I would say, people who have played
at the highest level of esports,

00:50:22.080 --> 00:50:25.520
that is playing official tournaments
for a franchise or--

00:50:25.600 --> 00:50:26.840
Not a franchise, we don't have franchises,

00:50:26.920 --> 00:50:29.640
but for a registered esports team,

00:50:29.720 --> 00:50:34.200
I think they could be doing
close to 30, 35 lakhs a year

00:50:34.840 --> 00:50:36.800
by just playing games professionally.

00:50:36.880 --> 00:50:38.320
And how many of these people are there?

00:50:39.160 --> 00:50:41.400
-Thousands.
-Uh, not really.

00:50:41.480 --> 00:50:43.560
I don't think at 35 lakhs, it's 1,000.

00:50:43.640 --> 00:50:47.000
It could be the top 150. Right.

00:50:47.080 --> 00:50:48.960
Because it's very limited.

00:50:50.240 --> 00:50:53.480
Where else in this domain
can young people make money in India?

00:50:53.560 --> 00:50:55.200
Streamer, gamer, then?

00:50:55.280 --> 00:50:57.600
Okay, so, now this is where I wanted
to come to the conversation that,

00:50:57.680 --> 00:50:59.960
you know, you were having with Joseph.

00:51:00.040 --> 00:51:03.040
What I feel is that
India does not really--

00:51:03.120 --> 00:51:06.440
So, if you look at the Indian market,
gaming boomed in India, mid-2019.

00:51:06.520 --> 00:51:09.720
It's exactly when it started booming,
and COVID happened,

00:51:09.800 --> 00:51:12.200
and the gaming industry
just blew off the lids.

00:51:12.280 --> 00:51:15.440
I believe, if you compare
the Indian gaming trajectory

00:51:15.520 --> 00:51:18.160
to Western and European markets--
like European and American markets,

00:51:18.240 --> 00:51:23.440
you realise we paced in--
the graph was very steep.

00:51:23.520 --> 00:51:26.240
We moved at a very fast pace.
We're paced really well.

00:51:26.320 --> 00:51:28.280
Gaming in India grew by leaps and bounds

00:51:28.360 --> 00:51:31.160
compared to the pace
at which other countries were coming in.

00:51:31.240 --> 00:51:34.280
But that is the consumption part of it.

00:51:34.360 --> 00:51:38.720
India surpassed US and Brazil
in terms of mobile game downloads.

00:51:38.800 --> 00:51:41.280
India has 568 million online gamers.

00:51:41.360 --> 00:51:42.800
So numbers are great.

00:51:42.880 --> 00:51:45.320
But there was a big void in the system,
which was this,

00:51:45.400 --> 00:51:49.160
that we did not have the proper...
correct roles defined.

00:51:49.240 --> 00:51:51.280
People did not know
what jobs are available,

00:51:51.360 --> 00:51:55.800
but people did not know, apart from being
a MortaL or a sc0ut or becoming a gamer,

00:51:55.880 --> 00:51:58.480
there are other hundred domains
where you can enter the gaming industry.

00:51:59.160 --> 00:52:01.080
So I believe that
we are too young for that.

00:52:01.160 --> 00:52:02.520
The industry is too young for that.

00:52:02.600 --> 00:52:05.840
India will produce the best of games
in the coming years,

00:52:05.920 --> 00:52:08.280
but it's not gonna happen
at least for the next five years.

00:52:08.360 --> 00:52:09.600
Why?

00:52:09.680 --> 00:52:11.760
I believe that building games
are super expensive.

00:52:12.600 --> 00:52:16.400
From what I have studied-- I might
be wrong, and someone can correct me.

00:52:16.480 --> 00:52:18.560
I don't believe
there were enough funds in India

00:52:18.640 --> 00:52:23.200
funding game development in India,
just, like, all the gaming funds,

00:52:23.280 --> 00:52:25.720
even Krafton's incubator
was announced early this year.

00:52:25.800 --> 00:52:28.920
And then there's Lumikai, and then,
I think even MPL is building a game.

00:52:29.000 --> 00:52:31.400
But all of this happened
in the last three, four years.

00:52:31.480 --> 00:52:32.840
So, if there were dreams,

00:52:32.920 --> 00:52:35.840
you know, when we talk about exodus,
talent exodus from India,

00:52:35.920 --> 00:52:37.480
if there were dreams eight years back

00:52:37.560 --> 00:52:39.240
about building a game in India,
who would fund it?

00:52:39.320 --> 00:52:40.760
That's the point.

00:52:40.840 --> 00:52:43.680
You know, I was just speaking
to one of your teammates--

00:52:43.760 --> 00:52:46.800
I feel like money always follows talent.

00:52:48.560 --> 00:52:49.560
It does.

00:52:49.640 --> 00:52:52.920
But then, I believe that there needs to be
a base for that ecosystem.

00:52:53.000 --> 00:52:56.320
I mean, like, eight years ago,
if someone would have gone and said,

00:52:56.400 --> 00:52:59.680
I need $2 million or $3 million
to build a game,

00:52:59.760 --> 00:53:01.960
no-one would have given
that person that money.

00:53:02.040 --> 00:53:04.520
I believe that. I could be wrong here,
but that's what I feel,

00:53:04.600 --> 00:53:06.600
because I watched the industry
only for the last seven, eight years,

00:53:06.680 --> 00:53:07.840
so I think that is the problem.

00:53:07.920 --> 00:53:10.520
So I think, right now, it's doing good.

00:53:10.600 --> 00:53:12.160
The money has just started to come in.

00:53:12.240 --> 00:53:14.600
There are small studios
that are trying to work really hard,

00:53:14.680 --> 00:53:15.720
and we'll have a good game,

00:53:15.800 --> 00:53:18.400
and we'll have that point
where we hold India's talent to India

00:53:18.480 --> 00:53:19.480
and build good games.

00:53:19.560 --> 00:53:22.040
And also, if you look at it,
even he was mentioning it,

00:53:22.120 --> 00:53:23.960
China has a stronghold.

00:53:24.040 --> 00:53:26.360
Tencent makes games that no-one else can.

00:53:26.440 --> 00:53:29.720
That is one problem
that the entire world is facing.

00:53:29.800 --> 00:53:31.520
So I believe that
India will make its mark,

00:53:31.600 --> 00:53:34.120
but we need to give it time to breathe.
Like, let it breathe.

00:53:34.200 --> 00:53:36.040
Let this industry breathe.
We have talents.

00:53:36.120 --> 00:53:38.000
We have people who are now keen on
developing games.

00:53:38.080 --> 00:53:40.360
Because now they see the money coming in.

00:53:40.440 --> 00:53:42.520
I believe-- You said,
"Money follows talent."

00:53:42.600 --> 00:53:45.560
I believe, in India,
talent goes where the money lies.

00:53:46.280 --> 00:53:48.480
-Both ways.
-Both ways. It is actually both ways.

00:53:48.560 --> 00:53:50.280
-[Nikhil] Yeah.
-But I would say that,

00:53:50.360 --> 00:53:52.640
if you look at Turkey, for example, right,

00:53:52.720 --> 00:53:56.000
you had a few studios
that had pretty big success there.

00:53:56.080 --> 00:53:57.800
Peak Games and now Dream Games.

00:53:57.880 --> 00:54:01.280
And then, now there's a flood of money
rushing to Turkey, right?

00:54:01.360 --> 00:54:07.840
And so, similarly, if India had just
a few successes on a global stage,

00:54:07.920 --> 00:54:12.000
I'm sure there would be a rush of money
that would come here as well.

00:54:12.080 --> 00:54:14.240
There's already
a number of global funds, right?

00:54:14.320 --> 00:54:17.280
There hasn't even been one
outside of Ludo?

00:54:17.360 --> 00:54:19.400
There's been Raji, which did pretty well.

00:54:19.480 --> 00:54:20.920
-Which one?
-Raji. It's a game

00:54:21.000 --> 00:54:22.960
-that was launched on Steam.
-[Sean] Ah, Raji. Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:54:23.040 --> 00:54:24.520
But then, it's an indie-ish--

00:54:24.600 --> 00:54:26.720
It's an indie game, but it did okay-ish.

00:54:26.800 --> 00:54:29.400
And I believe that what, now, Indus--

00:54:29.480 --> 00:54:30.960
-SuperGaming is building Indus.
-[Sean] Mm.

00:54:31.040 --> 00:54:32.800
It's a very promising title.

00:54:32.880 --> 00:54:35.360
Even MPL is doing UGW,
Underworld Gang Wars.

00:54:35.440 --> 00:54:38.160
So, let's see.
I think there are games coming out,

00:54:39.160 --> 00:54:42.200
and I believe that India will have
great games come out

00:54:42.280 --> 00:54:45.480
because, you know, I have seen
Indian gamers are built different.

00:54:45.560 --> 00:54:48.680
We haven't had, you know,
the cricket moment of '83 yet

00:54:48.760 --> 00:54:50.000
-for Indian esports.
-[Sean] Mm.

00:54:50.080 --> 00:54:52.280
But once that happens,
the boom should come in.

00:54:52.360 --> 00:54:55.160
Are the incumbent Indian market leaders
helping out?

00:54:55.240 --> 00:54:56.440
Like Nitish, on your right?

00:54:57.000 --> 00:54:59.480
-[laughter]
-We are very focused on our ROI.

00:54:59.560 --> 00:55:00.840
[Animesh] Definitely.

00:55:00.920 --> 00:55:04.720
I got great help from NODWIN,
and I'm shooting for Krafton tomorrow.

00:55:04.800 --> 00:55:06.240
I have a shoot at 6:00 a.m.

00:55:06.320 --> 00:55:07.440
Okay.

00:55:07.520 --> 00:55:12.320
So if I were a 20-year-old...
young guy or girl,

00:55:13.360 --> 00:55:14.720
how do I make money in gaming?

00:55:14.800 --> 00:55:17.280
I love gaming. I play it in my free time.

00:55:17.360 --> 00:55:21.160
My parents and my peers
are giving me a hard time,

00:55:21.240 --> 00:55:25.720
saying that I'm wasting time and money
and resources gaming.

00:55:25.800 --> 00:55:29.400
What is the path
to build a successful career,

00:55:29.480 --> 00:55:32.160
path of least resistance in gaming?

00:55:32.240 --> 00:55:35.400
So, I'll talk about the path
to becoming a gamer.

00:55:35.480 --> 00:55:36.920
Very hard truth.

00:55:37.000 --> 00:55:41.120
If you're a 20-year-old, I have said it
on record, and I always say it,

00:55:41.200 --> 00:55:44.600
gaming cannot be the only thing
that you are pursuing, in India right now.

00:55:44.680 --> 00:55:47.720
You need to have a back-up.
You need to have a back-up plan.

00:55:47.800 --> 00:55:49.920
If you come from a business family,

00:55:50.000 --> 00:55:52.360
you are pursuing your studies,
you need to continue doing that.

00:55:52.440 --> 00:55:54.480
Continue gaming as a passion

00:55:54.560 --> 00:55:57.560
until you are at the right place,

00:55:57.640 --> 00:56:00.440
in front of the right person,
and at the right stage

00:56:00.520 --> 00:56:02.120
where you get to show your gaming talent.

00:56:02.200 --> 00:56:06.760
When I talk about India's top gamers,
professional gamers or content creators,

00:56:06.840 --> 00:56:09.000
I believe they are nothing.

00:56:09.080 --> 00:56:12.440
There could be hundreds, thousands,
lakhs of more skilled gamers

00:56:12.520 --> 00:56:14.040
and better content creators
sitting at home.

00:56:14.680 --> 00:56:16.560
But it's so much about luck

00:56:16.640 --> 00:56:19.160
that they were at the right place
at the right time.

00:56:19.240 --> 00:56:20.680
The timing matters so much.

00:56:20.760 --> 00:56:23.560
I wouldn't have been sitting here
if I wouldn't have taken that break

00:56:23.640 --> 00:56:24.840
for a year from my academic career.

00:56:25.680 --> 00:56:28.280
Plus, the game--
I started streaming on 20th July--

00:56:28.360 --> 00:56:29.520
But if you don't do it full-time,

00:56:29.600 --> 00:56:32.080
how do you compete with
the international ones doing it full-time?

00:56:33.280 --> 00:56:35.720
Coming to the international stage
is a very, very long story.

00:56:35.800 --> 00:56:37.480
If you are actually
getting a chance to compete,

00:56:37.560 --> 00:56:39.520
that means you have made it nationally.

00:56:39.600 --> 00:56:42.280
I am also saying, to make it nationally,
it's a very big luck factor.

00:56:42.360 --> 00:56:45.440
-Because-- To explain--
-What is... what is talent?

00:56:46.080 --> 00:56:49.760
I know, in cricket, talent is timing...

00:56:50.920 --> 00:56:54.760
time, maybe you have more time
before you hit a ball,

00:56:54.840 --> 00:56:58.520
body, physical strength, all of that.

00:56:58.600 --> 00:57:02.880
What distinguishes one gamer
from another in terms of talent?

00:57:02.960 --> 00:57:05.120
Understanding of the game,
the biggest thing.

00:57:05.200 --> 00:57:07.800
I think, every game
which is competitive in nature

00:57:07.880 --> 00:57:10.680
has so many strategical aspects to it,

00:57:10.760 --> 00:57:14.080
yet you need to give it real time
to understand it.

00:57:14.160 --> 00:57:17.520
And, believe me,
a person who gives lot of time--

00:57:17.600 --> 00:57:19.080
So, there's a thing called meta.

00:57:19.160 --> 00:57:21.760
Meta is like, what is something
that is dominating the--

00:57:21.840 --> 00:57:23.840
Which strategy is dominating
the game right now?

00:57:23.920 --> 00:57:26.480
So how does a meta change?

00:57:26.560 --> 00:57:27.800
What is that strategy that changes?

00:57:27.880 --> 00:57:30.080
There is someone spending
so much time on the game

00:57:30.160 --> 00:57:32.600
to bring out something different

00:57:32.680 --> 00:57:34.160
that gets him a win condition.

00:57:34.240 --> 00:57:36.720
Like, you know, he starts winning games,
and that's when everyone else adopts it.

00:57:36.800 --> 00:57:40.880
So I think talent is about
that strategical input

00:57:40.960 --> 00:57:42.320
that you are bringing to a game.

00:57:42.400 --> 00:57:45.600
Apart from that, if you are playing
a first-person shooter or shooting game,

00:57:45.680 --> 00:57:48.280
the reflexes matter a lot,
how fast you react to situations.

00:57:48.360 --> 00:57:52.280
So, I had another agenda today,
like, an ulterior motive, almost.

00:57:53.400 --> 00:57:59.320
Our audience who we speak to
are upcoming entrepreneurs in India

00:57:59.400 --> 00:58:01.960
who are trying to build a business.

00:58:02.040 --> 00:58:05.440
We try and give them information
about different industries.

00:58:05.520 --> 00:58:08.920
We have a grant programme
where we try and give them some funding,

00:58:09.000 --> 00:58:13.000
somebody really young who wants
to build something with promise.

00:58:13.680 --> 00:58:18.320
And we also try and connect them
from a community standpoint.

00:58:18.400 --> 00:58:22.840
So we will put you guys in front
of a bunch of really inquisitive people

00:58:22.920 --> 00:58:25.400
who want to be in gaming
and make it a career.

00:58:26.600 --> 00:58:31.800
So the first thing I wanted to know is,
where is young India spending time?

00:58:32.840 --> 00:58:34.560
You guys have the gaming lens.

00:58:35.600 --> 00:58:37.640
If I were to make the assumption...

00:58:39.200 --> 00:58:41.720
Not assumption,
I think there is data for this.

00:58:41.800 --> 00:58:44.520
People under the age of 30 in India

00:58:44.600 --> 00:58:47.840
are spending a lot more time
on social media.

00:58:47.920 --> 00:58:50.600
They are spending a lot
more time on gaming.

00:58:50.680 --> 00:58:52.960
They are spending less time watching TV.

00:58:53.840 --> 00:58:57.080
They are spending, strangely,
less time watching sport.

00:58:57.600 --> 00:59:02.360
So the amount of time somebody
really young is spending on cricket

00:59:02.440 --> 00:59:05.200
is lesser than it was 10 years ago,
15 years ago.

00:59:06.760 --> 00:59:11.600
They're spending lesser time playing
physical sports or physical activities.

00:59:11.680 --> 00:59:14.080
Print media is going down.

00:59:14.160 --> 00:59:16.120
Online media is going up,

00:59:16.200 --> 00:59:21.160
but not enough to totally compensate
for print media going down.

00:59:21.240 --> 00:59:24.000
So if I'm a young 16-year-old boy,

00:59:24.840 --> 00:59:30.440
I have 8, 10, 12 free hours in a day.
Let's say eight.

00:59:31.760 --> 00:59:36.400
How much time of that eight
is going where... today?

00:59:36.480 --> 00:59:37.800
Where was it yesterday?

00:59:37.880 --> 00:59:40.120
And where will it be at tomorrow?

00:59:40.200 --> 00:59:45.000
This is essential for anybody looking
to build any kind of company in India

00:59:45.080 --> 00:59:48.520
because we need to know where the youth
are going to be spending time tomorrow.

00:59:48.600 --> 00:59:51.440
So I'll go to each one of you,
and we don't have to, like,

00:59:51.520 --> 00:59:53.640
narrow our lens down to India.

00:59:53.720 --> 00:59:58.080
You could talk about America,
you could talk about Southeast Asia...

00:59:58.160 --> 00:59:59.720
Who would like to go first? Nitish?

00:59:59.800 --> 01:00:02.000
No, sure, I can go first.

01:00:02.080 --> 01:00:08.520
So, I think, if you go back...
if I go back to my own generation, right,

01:00:08.600 --> 01:00:14.080
and if I go back to my school days
or when I was 15 or 16 or even younger,

01:00:15.440 --> 01:00:19.280
cricket was where our life
would revolve around, right?

01:00:19.360 --> 01:00:23.120
You would play cricket all the time
with your building friends.

01:00:23.200 --> 01:00:24.760
You would watch cricket.

01:00:24.840 --> 01:00:27.600
I remember, in school, I would
even wake up at 5:00 in the morning

01:00:27.680 --> 01:00:30.960
to watch a test match happening
in South Africa or Australia

01:00:31.040 --> 01:00:32.240
before going to school, right?

01:00:32.320 --> 01:00:35.040
Your whole life revolved around
this thing called cricket.

01:00:36.120 --> 01:00:38.280
I especially think,
the younger you're getting--

01:00:38.360 --> 01:00:40.000
Your question was, "Below 30," right?

01:00:40.080 --> 01:00:43.920
But I have a thesis here
that the younger you get,

01:00:44.000 --> 01:00:49.480
the velocity or the amount of time being
spent on gaming is increasing.

01:00:49.560 --> 01:00:52.200
Right? So, a 15, 16-year-old today

01:00:52.280 --> 01:00:55.320
is probably spending
maximum time on social media,

01:00:56.640 --> 01:00:59.400
some on sports,
and a decent amount of time on gaming.

01:00:59.480 --> 01:01:04.760
The stats say 40% of their time
on social media and maybe 30% on gaming.

01:01:04.840 --> 01:01:10.360
But the rate of change in time spent
is going up in social media

01:01:10.440 --> 01:01:11.920
even faster than gaming.

01:01:12.000 --> 01:01:14.600
No, but if you go even a little younger,

01:01:14.680 --> 01:01:17.400
I'm saying from experience,
I've got two young kids

01:01:17.480 --> 01:01:18.680
who are below 12,

01:01:19.760 --> 01:01:23.040
social media, they are not even allowed,
to be honest, a lot.

01:01:23.120 --> 01:01:24.640
But the rest of the time is only gaming.

01:01:25.280 --> 01:01:27.960
-And what games have they played?
-They've evolved.

01:01:28.040 --> 01:01:31.880
First, they used to play my games,
which was Kiddopia, which is very popular.

01:01:31.960 --> 01:01:33.680
So I'll do a shameless plug.

01:01:33.760 --> 01:01:36.240
I like how he plugged himself.
Listed company--

01:01:36.320 --> 01:01:39.160
[Nitish] I'm trained.
Three years trained now. [chuckles]

01:01:40.240 --> 01:01:44.240
But now they've moved to Minecraft. Right?

01:01:44.320 --> 01:01:46.880
So both the kids
are playing Minecraft. Okay?

01:01:46.960 --> 01:01:49.200
-Sitting next to each other.
-They wake up at 6:00 in the morning.

01:01:49.280 --> 01:01:51.120
I wake them up sharp at 6:00
in the morning

01:01:51.200 --> 01:01:53.040
'cause they have to leave
for school at 7:00.

01:01:53.120 --> 01:01:55.520
The first thing they will do
is pick up their respective iPads

01:01:55.600 --> 01:01:56.680
and start Minecraft.

01:01:56.760 --> 01:01:59.320
So, 6:00 to 6:30 is their gaming time,

01:01:59.400 --> 01:02:01.800
their wake-up alarm, you can say.

01:02:02.960 --> 01:02:05.840
So they'll do Minecraft,
but the more important thing is,

01:02:05.920 --> 01:02:08.000
on YouTube or on the TV,

01:02:08.080 --> 01:02:11.160
they're on YouTube
and watching Minecraft videos.

01:02:11.240 --> 01:02:13.400
They're watching Minecraft streamers.

01:02:13.480 --> 01:02:15.480
Then my daughter recently
had a birthday, so I asked her,

01:02:15.560 --> 01:02:17.040
"What birthday theme do you want?"

01:02:18.080 --> 01:02:20.400
-And she wanted to do--
-How old is your daughter?

01:02:20.480 --> 01:02:22.600
She's just turned seven.
She wanted a theme--

01:02:22.680 --> 01:02:24.040
She said Aphmau.

01:02:24.120 --> 01:02:26.600
I didn't even know what Aphmau is,
so I googled it.

01:02:26.680 --> 01:02:29.320
It's supposedly a girl
called Jessica in the US,

01:02:29.400 --> 01:02:31.120
who's a popular Minecraft streamer.

01:02:32.040 --> 01:02:34.240
And she wanted a whole birthday theme
around that...

01:02:35.040 --> 01:02:36.400
streamer, right?

01:02:36.480 --> 01:02:38.520
And you have merchandise
around that streamer now,

01:02:38.600 --> 01:02:39.960
so she wants me to buy that for her.

01:02:40.040 --> 01:02:42.880
So what I realised is,
for these younger kids,

01:02:42.960 --> 01:02:46.560
what cricket was for us
has been replaced by gaming.

01:02:47.320 --> 01:02:49.640
With their friends,
the topic of discussion is gaming.

01:02:49.720 --> 01:02:52.000
What are you doing? Which game?
Et cetera, right?

01:02:52.080 --> 01:02:53.680
So it's all revolving around gaming.

01:02:53.760 --> 01:02:59.000
And therefore, I'm betting that
as this generation grows up,

01:02:59.640 --> 01:03:03.000
which is your today's five-year-old,
ten-year-old,

01:03:03.720 --> 01:03:05.560
into the next four, five years

01:03:05.640 --> 01:03:10.400
where gaming will be, by far,
the primary source of entertainment.

01:03:10.480 --> 01:03:11.840
But why not social media?

01:03:11.920 --> 01:03:13.960
'Cause when they grow to be 16,

01:03:14.040 --> 01:03:16.400
you'll allow them
and they'll graduate to that, right?

01:03:16.480 --> 01:03:20.080
Probably, they will, but I think
they will still be far more ingrained

01:03:20.160 --> 01:03:22.400
because they've done this gaming
from the age of two.

01:03:22.480 --> 01:03:24.080
My daughter started gaming
at one and a half.

01:03:24.920 --> 01:03:26.840
So I think it comes
very naturally to them,

01:03:26.920 --> 01:03:30.440
rather than adopting to it
as a lot of the current generation has.

01:03:30.520 --> 01:03:35.640
So if I am 20 and I want to sell something
when I'm 25, I'm building a business,

01:03:35.720 --> 01:03:37.840
I'm an entrepreneur, wannabe entrepreneur,

01:03:38.800 --> 01:03:40.920
do you think I should focus on gaming,

01:03:41.000 --> 01:03:42.240
social media,

01:03:42.960 --> 01:03:46.680
sport, movies, TV?

01:03:46.760 --> 01:03:50.240
What audience should I be building for--
towards?

01:03:50.320 --> 01:03:52.920
-If you want to sell to the audience?
-Yeah.

01:03:53.000 --> 01:03:54.720
-I think gaming--
-Continue.

01:03:54.800 --> 01:03:57.080
I think gaming is a great place
because of the kind of engagement

01:03:57.160 --> 01:03:59.600
you have on gaming, right.

01:03:59.680 --> 01:04:01.480
When you're playing a game,
you're very focused

01:04:01.560 --> 01:04:05.680
and interacting with the game
versus watching it passively.

01:04:06.680 --> 01:04:10.080
Let's say watching... content passively.

01:04:10.160 --> 01:04:12.520
-[Nikhil] Right.
-So if you're selling to a gamer...

01:04:13.680 --> 01:04:15.360
it's a big potential,

01:04:15.440 --> 01:04:17.480
which is why
something we've been looking at is,

01:04:17.560 --> 01:04:20.440
this new word coming up,
g-commerce, right,

01:04:20.520 --> 01:04:23.400
which is selling via games.

01:04:24.640 --> 01:04:29.040
It's a new trend which is starting
to pick up, and we'll see where it goes.

01:04:29.120 --> 01:04:31.720
-But, yeah, I think--
-And how do I sell to a gamer?

01:04:31.800 --> 01:04:35.400
Say I'm starting a chocolate company,
and I want to sell--

01:04:36.280 --> 01:04:38.920
I think the gaming crowd
will be three times as big

01:04:39.000 --> 01:04:41.880
as they are today, in ten years.
How do you start selling to them?

01:04:41.960 --> 01:04:46.880
Do you go to Discord, Twitch,
streaming platforms, chat boxes?

01:04:47.760 --> 01:04:50.440
I think the best way
is in-game monetisation.

01:04:50.520 --> 01:04:53.400
You know, I think that if the crowd
is shifting, the trend is shifting

01:04:53.480 --> 01:04:55.160
towards spending more time on games,

01:04:55.240 --> 01:04:58.160
then I would want to market it
inside the game.

01:04:58.240 --> 01:04:59.680
I mean, like, if you look at Hero,

01:04:59.760 --> 01:05:02.560
your recent partnership
that you announced yesterday,

01:05:02.640 --> 01:05:05.960
now, I'm guessing Hero will bring
their bike skins within the game.

01:05:06.040 --> 01:05:09.800
And if they are targeting it
for the Gen-Z, the 125R model,

01:05:09.880 --> 01:05:11.120
I think they've hit the right chord.

01:05:11.200 --> 01:05:14.440
Because, like we see,
people are not spending time on TV.

01:05:14.520 --> 01:05:16.080
If people are not watching cricket,

01:05:16.160 --> 01:05:18.880
and if they're spending time
on social media and gaming,

01:05:18.960 --> 01:05:22.880
then you just split your spends
into the two things.

01:05:22.960 --> 01:05:24.760
You have your ads running,
and then you have things

01:05:24.840 --> 01:05:26.520
that they're spending time on
integrated into it.

01:05:26.600 --> 01:05:28.920
So I believe,
that is the best way to go about it,

01:05:29.000 --> 01:05:30.040
but you will have more insight.

01:05:30.120 --> 01:05:32.320
Yeah, I have a very good example.

01:05:32.400 --> 01:05:36.120
Like, my kids love to watch MrBeast,

01:05:36.200 --> 01:05:39.160
the YouTube...
Crazy-- Kids are getting crazy.

01:05:39.240 --> 01:05:43.760
And then, I think he has built
some brands. Chocolate.

01:05:43.840 --> 01:05:45.360
-Yeah, yeah.
-[Sean] Er, Feastables?

01:05:45.440 --> 01:05:46.760
Feastables chocolate.

01:05:46.840 --> 01:05:52.520
They-- My kids don't really remember
Hershey's, but kids remember Feastables.

01:05:52.600 --> 01:05:56.560
So when I went to GDC
just a few weeks back,

01:05:56.640 --> 01:05:58.320
their request was just-- only one thing,

01:05:58.400 --> 01:06:00.720
-buy lots of Feastables chocolate.
-[Nitish] Feastables. [chuckling]

01:06:00.800 --> 01:06:03.160
So that they can have it,

01:06:03.240 --> 01:06:05.160
-also they can give out to friends.
-[Nitish] Yeah, yeah.

01:06:05.240 --> 01:06:08.480
So it's also kind of like
showing, kind of, status.

01:06:08.560 --> 01:06:12.360
Like, I have Feastables
which can be bought from the US

01:06:12.440 --> 01:06:13.720
and then give it to friends.

01:06:13.800 --> 01:06:15.360
It's big.

01:06:16.040 --> 01:06:19.440
I paid, like, 1,000 bucks
for a Feastable which tastes the same

01:06:19.520 --> 01:06:22.560
like Amul chocolate. [chuckles]
-They're the same, they're the same,

01:06:22.640 --> 01:06:24.960
but different labels.

01:06:25.040 --> 01:06:27.440
Nikhil, I've got a very
different perspective.

01:06:27.520 --> 01:06:32.680
Nikhil, I think one other way to think
about opportunity for a young person is--

01:06:32.760 --> 01:06:37.000
And certainly, I think, one way to think
about it is current, kind of, demand side.

01:06:37.080 --> 01:06:40.200
But the other way to think about it
is more on the supply side,

01:06:40.280 --> 01:06:41.960
and also, in terms of new demand.

01:06:42.800 --> 01:06:46.800
I think the one thing that cannot
be ignored, in my opinion,

01:06:46.880 --> 01:06:52.000
and I believe we're living in a very
unprecedented time, is, essentially, AI.

01:06:52.080 --> 01:06:57.280
And if you see the growth of AI today,
and we were at GDC,

01:06:57.360 --> 01:07:01.720
the number of people building tools
and capabilities with AI is incredible.

01:07:01.800 --> 01:07:03.880
It's moving so fast.

01:07:03.960 --> 01:07:10.000
So if I were to advise somebody younger,
I would say that, in my opinion,

01:07:10.080 --> 01:07:13.240
I think AI is going to be
as big as the Internet,

01:07:13.320 --> 01:07:16.400
potentially bigger
in terms of impact to society.

01:07:16.480 --> 01:07:19.960
And so, from that lens,
I think that you wanna be thinking

01:07:20.040 --> 01:07:21.800
about a cross-strategy,

01:07:21.880 --> 01:07:24.640
meaning you wanna learn AI as a base,

01:07:24.720 --> 01:07:26.640
but then cross it with something else.

01:07:27.440 --> 01:07:29.360
Explain. What does that mean?

01:07:29.440 --> 01:07:31.320
For example, AI-cross-gaming.

01:07:31.400 --> 01:07:34.960
So you're gonna learn AI, but then
you're also gonna develop depth

01:07:35.040 --> 01:07:37.240
in a different industry or sector

01:07:37.320 --> 01:07:41.360
so that you can take the AI capabilities
and bring that to that sector.

01:07:41.440 --> 01:07:46.360
So whether it's AI-cross-gaming
or banking or pharmaceuticals or whatever.

01:07:46.440 --> 01:07:50.640
Right? So, then,
I would recommend for younger people

01:07:50.720 --> 01:07:54.000
to find an area of interest,

01:07:54.080 --> 01:07:58.560
but then, also develop their expertise
and knowledge in AI

01:07:58.640 --> 01:08:01.280
so that they can take those capabilities
into that space.

01:08:02.120 --> 01:08:04.880
And then, I think, besides that,
the one other thing that we're seeing

01:08:04.960 --> 01:08:06.880
is a fundamental shift.

01:08:06.960 --> 01:08:10.200
And so, for people who are watching
that are interested in gaming,

01:08:10.280 --> 01:08:14.440
I think the big shift that is happening
is from a development perspective.

01:08:14.520 --> 01:08:16.240
-And it's something that--
-Before you go there,

01:08:16.320 --> 01:08:21.520
if I were to try and incorporate AI
into my vocabulary

01:08:21.600 --> 01:08:25.520
as a gamer, as a young gamer,
what tools should I get familiar with?

01:08:25.600 --> 01:08:26.600
What should I learn?

01:08:27.280 --> 01:08:30.680
Well, I would say, like,
in the current state,

01:08:30.760 --> 01:08:33.160
I would probably learn all of the tools.

01:08:33.240 --> 01:08:34.600
For example?

01:08:34.680 --> 01:08:38.000
So, whether it's ChatGPT or Claude 3

01:08:38.080 --> 01:08:42.920
or, you know, some of the newer tools
that are being developed using those,

01:08:43.000 --> 01:08:45.160
there's a lot of applications in gaming

01:08:45.240 --> 01:08:47.560
in terms of, like, conversational AI
and things of that nature.

01:08:47.640 --> 01:08:49.320
So there's a lot of services
being developed.

01:08:49.400 --> 01:08:52.440
So, becoming familiar with
the services and the capabilities

01:08:52.520 --> 01:08:53.880
that are being developed,

01:08:53.960 --> 01:08:57.560
but, on top of that,
to then learn AI in more depth.

01:08:57.640 --> 01:08:59.600
So, what is a large language model?

01:08:59.680 --> 01:09:01.960
What are the kind of models
that are out there today?

01:09:02.040 --> 01:09:05.640
Whether it's LlaMA or other open-source
models and things of that nature.

01:09:05.720 --> 01:09:11.400
So, what I would recommend for AI
is, basically, extreme depth.

01:09:11.480 --> 01:09:16.000
Learn as much as you can
at a foundational, fundamental level,

01:09:16.080 --> 01:09:19.440
and then... and then,
again, that other industry.

01:09:19.520 --> 01:09:21.440
And if you had to...

01:09:22.840 --> 01:09:25.520
name two subsets of AI

01:09:25.600 --> 01:09:28.920
that I should begin focusing on,
specifically for gaming,

01:09:29.000 --> 01:09:30.720
what would they be?

01:09:30.800 --> 01:09:34.680
Well, I mean, I think the biggest push
right now is conversational AI, which is--

01:09:34.760 --> 01:09:37.680
You wouldn't say something
like Unreal Engine or--

01:09:37.760 --> 01:09:43.400
Oh, well, I mean, I think Unreal and Unity
are game development engines, right?

01:09:43.480 --> 01:09:46.320
And so, I don't think those--

01:09:46.400 --> 01:09:49.840
They're trying to build
some AI capabilities there,

01:09:49.920 --> 01:09:53.040
for example, to potentially
write code or to automate things,

01:09:53.120 --> 01:09:57.280
but I don't think AI has as big
of an impact on the game engines

01:09:57.360 --> 01:10:00.400
as they would...
Probably, more on a UGC platform.

01:10:00.480 --> 01:10:02.280
-So I think you'll start--
-What is UGC?

01:10:02.360 --> 01:10:03.880
User-generated content.

01:10:03.960 --> 01:10:07.760
And so, if you were to look
at some of the UGC platforms,

01:10:07.840 --> 01:10:11.240
the user-generated content platforms
like Roblox or UEFN,

01:10:11.320 --> 01:10:13.800
which is Epic's version of Roblox.

01:10:14.880 --> 01:10:18.720
Can you just explain?
Like, think I'm a layman, proper idiot.

01:10:18.800 --> 01:10:19.920
What is...

01:10:20.000 --> 01:10:24.680
So, Roblox is the world's biggest
user-generated content platform.

01:10:24.760 --> 01:10:29.000
Basically, what Roblox is,
is a platform on which...

01:10:29.080 --> 01:10:33.160
you know, actually, many kids go,
and they build game experiences

01:10:33.240 --> 01:10:38.080
based upon a set of tools that Roblox
provides, into the Roblox game world.

01:10:38.160 --> 01:10:39.760
And so, you can go to Roblox,

01:10:39.840 --> 01:10:43.280
and there's a bunch of different games
that the creators have made.

01:10:43.360 --> 01:10:47.720
So, in Roblox,
creators that are often very young

01:10:47.800 --> 01:10:51.640
will create these games using the tools
that have been provided by Roblox.

01:10:52.360 --> 01:10:55.760
And Epic, now, has something similar
called UEFN,

01:10:55.840 --> 01:11:00.640
Unreal Engine for Fortnite, which kind of
builds these experiences within Fortnite.

01:11:00.720 --> 01:11:03.920
And I don't need any prior knowledge
to be able to utilise these?

01:11:04.000 --> 01:11:07.760
You need some depth of understanding.

01:11:07.840 --> 01:11:11.560
So, like, Roblox, for example,
uses a scripting language called Luau.

01:11:11.640 --> 01:11:14.720
So there is some knowledge required.

01:11:14.800 --> 01:11:16.160
But, you know, I would say

01:11:16.240 --> 01:11:20.520
the user-generated content platforms
are also a way in which

01:11:20.600 --> 01:11:23.800
someone from India could make,
potentially, millions of dollars. Right?

01:11:23.880 --> 01:11:25.520
-I think, like, the top creator--
-Explain.

01:11:25.600 --> 01:11:27.400
[Nitish] I just wanna add there

01:11:27.480 --> 01:11:30.400
because I've been very actively involved
in that whole thing right now,

01:11:30.480 --> 01:11:31.680
what he's just referring to.

01:11:32.480 --> 01:11:34.600
I just did a Zoom call recently

01:11:34.680 --> 01:11:39.800
with a 19-year-old kid
who has a game called Blox Fruits,

01:11:40.600 --> 01:11:44.400
and it makes something like
$60 million a year, or something,

01:11:44.480 --> 01:11:45.760
in revenue.

01:11:45.840 --> 01:11:50.360
After that, I've been trying to migrate
my kid from Minecraft to Roblox.

01:11:50.440 --> 01:11:53.520
-[laughter]
-Every day, I try that, right?

01:11:53.600 --> 01:11:55.720
So, it's... it's absolutely crazy,

01:11:55.800 --> 01:11:57.480
and he's absolutely right in terms--

01:11:57.560 --> 01:11:59.840
-Okay, tell me, that kid, 19-year-old...
-Yeah.

01:12:00.600 --> 01:12:03.560
...me, idiot,
don't know anything about gaming,

01:12:03.640 --> 01:12:07.200
know little bit about computers,
can't code, nothing. Okay?

01:12:07.280 --> 01:12:10.840
Step one, step two, step three, step four,
that kid making $60 million,

01:12:10.920 --> 01:12:12.080
name those four steps.

01:12:12.880 --> 01:12:16.240
No, I mean... coding is one thing, right,

01:12:16.320 --> 01:12:17.480
understanding some of these rules.

01:12:17.560 --> 01:12:20.080
But these kids are kind of hackers, right?

01:12:20.160 --> 01:12:23.080
-They've done it hands-on--
-But I am not. How do I do it?

01:12:23.160 --> 01:12:26.760
So, I would say, like, first,
you need to learn the platform

01:12:26.840 --> 01:12:31.480
and then learn the kinds of things
that the Roblox players are looking for.

01:12:31.560 --> 01:12:34.400
And so, the experience on Roblox
is different from a mobile game,

01:12:34.480 --> 01:12:37.640
is different from other kinds of games
because it's very social in nature.

01:12:37.720 --> 01:12:40.840
And people are in Roblox to not just play

01:12:40.920 --> 01:12:43.320
but to meet and interact
with other players.

01:12:43.400 --> 01:12:46.720
And so, step one would be learning Roblox,

01:12:46.800 --> 01:12:49.120
understanding the kinds of games
that are popular,

01:12:49.200 --> 01:12:52.320
and forming a hypothesis
on why they are popular.

01:12:52.400 --> 01:12:54.840
And this is not complicated?
I can spend X amount of time--

01:12:54.920 --> 01:12:57.640
There are 13-year-old kids
making games on Roblox.

01:12:57.720 --> 01:12:59.240
-It's not that complicated.
-[Nitish] Yeah.

01:12:59.320 --> 01:13:02.360
And the second thing
would be to learn the tools,

01:13:02.440 --> 01:13:06.080
Luau and the Roblox creator platform.

01:13:06.160 --> 01:13:09.160
And I think the third thing
would just be to just go,

01:13:09.240 --> 01:13:11.280
just build as many games as you can,

01:13:11.360 --> 01:13:14.800
and to then get those repetitions in
as far as, like,

01:13:14.880 --> 01:13:17.200
building and learning your craft,

01:13:17.280 --> 01:13:20.600
and experimenting to see what works
and what doesn't work.

01:13:21.240 --> 01:13:23.200
-I mean, if I may add--
-[Nitish] Yeah, yeah.

01:13:23.280 --> 01:13:27.760
Erm, my kids are actually trying
to make a game on Roblox.

01:13:28.440 --> 01:13:32.160
So the first, you-- I mean,
if I may answer your question,

01:13:32.840 --> 01:13:38.240
you have to love playing games on Roblox
or any other platform first.

01:13:38.320 --> 01:13:41.120
So you play maybe
100 different kinds of games first.

01:13:41.200 --> 01:13:44.240
You like it, you like this,
you don't like that.

01:13:44.320 --> 01:13:46.320
And then, it's a very human nature,

01:13:46.400 --> 01:13:51.960
like, if you like certain board games
or certain games outside your home,

01:13:52.040 --> 01:13:56.040
you want to change a little bit
and make it more fun with your friends.

01:13:56.120 --> 01:14:00.240
That is very-- You know, the same thing
is happening in Roblox and Minecraft.

01:14:00.320 --> 01:14:02.000
There are some games that you like,

01:14:02.080 --> 01:14:06.040
then you want to create something similar,
but in your own way.

01:14:06.120 --> 01:14:08.560
That's how, actually,
I think things are starting.

01:14:08.640 --> 01:14:09.640
Yeah, no, it's great.

01:14:09.720 --> 01:14:16.080
And just-- I wanted to also highlight that
the AI he spoke about on UGC, right?

01:14:16.160 --> 01:14:20.040
And I was just hearing the podcast
of the founder of Roblox,

01:14:20.120 --> 01:14:22.920
and they're talking about now introducing,
or they've introduced,

01:14:23.000 --> 01:14:28.120
or they're talking about launching soon,
is real-time translation.

01:14:28.200 --> 01:14:30.120
So, when the kids are talking
to each other,

01:14:30.200 --> 01:14:32.600
let's say I'm an Indian
and there's another Japanese kid,

01:14:32.680 --> 01:14:35.480
and I'm talking in Hindi
to you, Japanese kid,

01:14:35.560 --> 01:14:38.080
it's gonna translate in real-time.

01:14:38.160 --> 01:14:43.280
So kids can actually talk in
their own language and communicate...

01:14:43.360 --> 01:14:46.680
It translates Hindi into Japanese,
and it's fantastic.

01:14:46.760 --> 01:14:50.000
So, the way AI is being used
in such applications

01:14:50.080 --> 01:14:53.680
-to actually bridge and connect--
-I have one confusion here.

01:14:53.760 --> 01:14:55.960
You were not talking about...

01:14:57.520 --> 01:15:00.280
creating content around the game,
because you said UGC.

01:15:00.360 --> 01:15:02.600
You're talking about
actually building the game.

01:15:02.680 --> 01:15:05.560
Yeah, I think there's a couple
of different opportunities, right?

01:15:05.640 --> 01:15:08.520
So there is an opportunity
that we haven't talked about,

01:15:08.600 --> 01:15:11.480
which is building games for UGC platforms.

01:15:12.160 --> 01:15:13.600
Name a UGC platform.

01:15:13.680 --> 01:15:16.920
Roblox and UEFN.
Those are the two biggest right now.

01:15:17.000 --> 01:15:19.480
When you say UGC,
my head is going to YouTube.

01:15:19.560 --> 01:15:21.520
-[laughter]
-User-generated content.

01:15:21.600 --> 01:15:23.200
-Yeah.
-It could be anything.

01:15:23.280 --> 01:15:30.120
Yeah, and I think, you know, we see plenty
of examples of games built by kids

01:15:30.200 --> 01:15:31.760
that are making tens
of millions of dollars,

01:15:31.840 --> 01:15:35.320
like, Adopt Me! probably makes
like $70 million to that team.

01:15:36.200 --> 01:15:37.920
Erm, so that's certainly an opportunity.

01:15:39.760 --> 01:15:42.760
And then there's the opportunity
that I think is more general

01:15:42.840 --> 01:15:44.600
outside of UGC platforms,

01:15:44.680 --> 01:15:48.920
which is, just by understanding
AI and gaming,

01:15:49.000 --> 01:15:54.000
to then find a specific opportunity
to apply AI to gaming.

01:15:54.080 --> 01:15:55.880
And I think, certainly,
what we're gonna see is,

01:15:55.960 --> 01:16:00.280
we're gonna see a massive shift
in how development occurs.

01:16:00.360 --> 01:16:03.360
It's gonna change
dramatically and radically.

01:16:03.440 --> 01:16:07.600
And as I mentioned, this kind of depends
on your perspective of the world.

01:16:07.680 --> 01:16:14.480
But I actually think that this is gonna be
an incredibly rare moment in time

01:16:14.560 --> 01:16:19.800
and probably, you know, and I believe,
unprecedented in history,

01:16:19.880 --> 01:16:23.360
where you're gonna have the opportunity
for some kid in India

01:16:24.200 --> 01:16:28.320
to become, like, a billionaire
as a single-person company, right?

01:16:28.400 --> 01:16:32.160
Because one of the things
that we're seeing is

01:16:32.240 --> 01:16:37.000
this shift from what I call
long vector development.

01:16:37.080 --> 01:16:41.520
By vector, I mean, time, cost,
resources, things like that,

01:16:41.600 --> 01:16:43.200
to small vector development.

01:16:43.280 --> 01:16:47.080
And so, today, you've got a lot of games
that have huge budgets,

01:16:47.160 --> 01:16:50.600
100, 200, 300 million with huge teams.

01:16:50.680 --> 01:16:53.560
But the promise of AI,
and it's hard to see right now

01:16:53.640 --> 01:16:56.120
because it's hard for people
to think exponentially.

01:16:56.760 --> 01:17:00.160
But when you see the numbers, this is like
when Jeff Bezos started Amazon.

01:17:00.240 --> 01:17:03.920
He saw the dramatic growth
in adoption of the Internet.

01:17:04.000 --> 01:17:06.120
When you see that kind of--

01:17:06.200 --> 01:17:07.440
What we're currently seeing is,

01:17:07.520 --> 01:17:10.880
we're seeing that growth start to happen
and that investment starting to happen.

01:17:10.960 --> 01:17:16.360
But as that happens, you're gonna be able
to then have very small teams

01:17:16.440 --> 01:17:20.320
build incredible games that have
massive reach, massive distribution.

01:17:20.400 --> 01:17:25.960
The mobile platforms, iOS and Google Play,
they have billions of people.

01:17:26.040 --> 01:17:27.960
Right? They're billion-person platforms.

01:17:28.920 --> 01:17:32.320
We've also had an example where,
talking about UGC,

01:17:32.400 --> 01:17:36.600
there was a creator
that learned their skills on Roblox,

01:17:36.680 --> 01:17:41.320
but then, created a mobile--
Sorry, a PC game called Lethal Company

01:17:41.400 --> 01:17:43.360
that became a number one game on Steam.

01:17:44.000 --> 01:17:48.280
So, similarly, erm, I do think that

01:17:48.360 --> 01:17:50.160
this is a new era,

01:17:50.240 --> 01:17:52.240
and this is the time where I hope...

01:17:53.320 --> 01:17:56.680
that the young Indian people out there
listening to this podcast

01:17:56.760 --> 01:18:03.080
will kind of wake up and realise that this
moment in time in history is very rare.

01:18:03.880 --> 01:18:09.600
This is the time for them
to really, like, focus, learn,

01:18:09.680 --> 01:18:11.200
and to make something great.

01:18:12.200 --> 01:18:15.000
Because I don't think there's gonna be
that many more opportunities

01:18:15.080 --> 01:18:16.920
in the world after this.

01:18:17.000 --> 01:18:21.240
After this is done, can we all,
in consultation,

01:18:21.320 --> 01:18:27.920
put out a process doc of recommendations
of what a young person needs to learn?

01:18:28.000 --> 01:18:29.600
-Yeah.
-[Nikhil] Yeah?

01:18:29.680 --> 01:18:33.480
They say mid-core and core is 0.4 billion,

01:18:33.560 --> 01:18:36.240
casual and hyper-casual is 0.7 billion.

01:18:36.320 --> 01:18:38.600
Can you explain what that means?

01:18:38.680 --> 01:18:40.800
Anyone? Sean?

01:18:41.880 --> 01:18:43.640
Mm, yeah, I mean, mid-core-ish.

01:18:43.720 --> 01:18:49.120
Mid-core, like, hardcore games
include BGMI,

01:18:49.200 --> 01:18:52.760
and maybe other shooter games
and some of, er, maybe sports games,

01:18:52.840 --> 01:18:53.920
simulation games.

01:18:54.560 --> 01:18:57.800
So how do you...
how do you justify this mid--

01:18:57.880 --> 01:19:01.560
How do you categorise mid-core,
this 0.4 billion?

01:19:01.640 --> 01:19:06.920
Mid-core games require
quite focused attention--

01:19:07.000 --> 01:19:09.760
-And a lot of investment?
-To make the game?

01:19:09.840 --> 01:19:11.480
-Yeah?
-Yeah, generally, yes.

01:19:12.840 --> 01:19:15.560
-But there is also, like, a big range.
-Mm-hmm.

01:19:15.640 --> 01:19:19.960
But compared to typical hyper-casual
or hybrid-casual games,

01:19:20.040 --> 01:19:22.040
it requires more resources,
that's for sure.

01:19:22.120 --> 01:19:23.560
You guys wanna comment?

01:19:23.640 --> 01:19:25.640
My only understanding of the Indian market

01:19:25.720 --> 01:19:29.240
is that it does seem that
it's highly skewed to shooters.

01:19:29.320 --> 01:19:32.280
It does seem like shooters are making
the majority of the money in India.

01:19:33.000 --> 01:19:35.560
-A lot of the--
-They fall in mid-core? In that bucket?

01:19:35.640 --> 01:19:37.560
Mid-core, yeah, yeah.

01:19:37.640 --> 01:19:41.200
And then it seems like the rest
of the money is being made

01:19:41.280 --> 01:19:45.320
from, like, ludo as well as, like,
cricket and things like that.

01:19:45.400 --> 01:19:49.240
And, actually, it's a surprising number
for me that mid-core and core market

01:19:49.320 --> 01:19:51.480
-is so big, because hyper-casual is--
-Not so big.

01:19:51.560 --> 01:19:53.880
0.4 billion, 400 million for India.

01:19:53.960 --> 01:19:58.480
400 million for India is still-- I feel
that it's pretty big that, you know--

01:19:58.560 --> 01:20:00.400
-Most of it, he takes home.
-Yeah.

01:20:00.480 --> 01:20:02.720
-[laughter]
-[Nikhil] Yeah?

01:20:02.800 --> 01:20:04.880
What's your market share for BGMI?

01:20:05.760 --> 01:20:08.000
BGMI, I would say...

01:20:08.080 --> 01:20:09.440
[chuckling]

01:20:10.480 --> 01:20:12.840
-5-10%.
-That's all?

01:20:12.920 --> 01:20:14.240
[Nitish] He's being modest.

01:20:14.320 --> 01:20:15.840
-[Animesh] Modest.
-[laughter]

01:20:15.920 --> 01:20:17.280
I don't know about that. [chuckles]

01:20:18.520 --> 01:20:20.200
Is the money going back to South Korea?

01:20:21.200 --> 01:20:23.280
-Some of it, yes.
-[laughter]

01:20:23.360 --> 01:20:27.400
But we invest in Indian tech startups.

01:20:27.480 --> 01:20:29.440
He invested in companies like Nazara.

01:20:29.520 --> 01:20:31.280
-He can always invest more.
-[Nikhil] Right.

01:20:31.360 --> 01:20:35.120
Okay, so I got an understanding
of what is mid-core.

01:20:35.200 --> 01:20:38.960
What is casual and hyper-casual,
which is growing the fastest, apparently?

01:20:40.040 --> 01:20:43.520
Well, I think hyper-casual is dying down,
but it's really, like--

01:20:43.600 --> 01:20:46.680
the level of complexity
is another way to think about it.

01:20:46.760 --> 01:20:50.000
Are you saying casual and hyper-casual
need lesser money?

01:20:50.080 --> 01:20:52.120
-Yeah.
-Generally to build,

01:20:52.200 --> 01:20:55.320
because they're simpler games,
less complexity.

01:20:55.400 --> 01:20:59.000
I would say that the other kind of nuance
behind those games

01:20:59.080 --> 01:21:02.520
is they typically have lower,
what's called retention days.

01:21:02.600 --> 01:21:07.760
So, like, a hyper-casual game often might
retain a user for like five days or...

01:21:07.840 --> 01:21:11.280
But I think
hyper-casual's starting to die.

01:21:11.360 --> 01:21:12.560
Give me some examples.

01:21:12.640 --> 01:21:13.840
I think Candy Crush and Counter-Strike.

01:21:13.920 --> 01:21:17.720
"Hyper-casual" casual is Candy Crush
and "mid-core" core is--

01:21:17.800 --> 01:21:20.080
Well, I would say Candy Crush
is more casual.

01:21:20.160 --> 01:21:21.160
-[Nitish] Casual, yeah.
-Yeah.

01:21:21.240 --> 01:21:22.760
-Hyper-casual is more like--
-Voodoo.

01:21:22.840 --> 01:21:25.200
-Yeah, the Voodoo games, right?
-Voodoo games.

01:21:25.280 --> 01:21:26.560
[indistinct]

01:21:26.640 --> 01:21:29.480
Well, I would say even Ludo
is more casual rather than hyper-casual.

01:21:29.560 --> 01:21:32.800
Hyper-casual, typically, has a bunch
of forced ads and things like that.

01:21:32.880 --> 01:21:34.240
-[Sean] Mm.
-Example?

01:21:35.280 --> 01:21:39.520
Well, it's like... The old, old examples
were, like, Snake.io

01:21:39.600 --> 01:21:41.760
-and all the other dot-io games.
-[Nikhil] On the old Nokia phones.

01:21:41.840 --> 01:21:43.600
Something like a Pac-Man?

01:21:43.680 --> 01:21:46.080
-Pac-Man is also still...
-[Nitish and Joseph] Casual.

01:21:46.160 --> 01:21:47.480
But why is that dying?

01:21:47.560 --> 01:21:49.320
That seems like the simplest thing
for people to--

01:21:49.400 --> 01:21:50.400
[Joseph] It's, uh-- Okay, I mean,

01:21:50.480 --> 01:21:53.760
I don't know how deep you wanna go
because we can go very deep here,

01:21:53.840 --> 01:21:57.200
but it has to do with, mainly, Apple,

01:21:57.280 --> 01:22:00.680
and, basically, this thing called IDFA--

01:22:00.760 --> 01:22:04.560
-We're really gonna go into--
-Give us the summary.

01:22:04.640 --> 01:22:07.560
The summary is you can't do
targeting anymore

01:22:07.640 --> 01:22:10.480
-because of Apple's privacy policies.
-[Nitish] Privacy.

01:22:10.560 --> 01:22:12.960
And so, the ability for
the hyper-casual games

01:22:13.040 --> 01:22:15.840
that are largely driven off
of an ad-driven model

01:22:15.920 --> 01:22:20.240
to then make money off of those ads
through targeting is going away.

01:22:20.320 --> 01:22:23.760
And Apple just doesn't like
hyper-casual games.

01:22:23.840 --> 01:22:30.080
But I'll tell you this, when I used to
play Snake on my old Nokia 3310 phone,

01:22:30.160 --> 01:22:31.440
there was no advertising.

01:22:31.520 --> 01:22:33.480
-It came bundled with the phone.
-It was offline.

01:22:33.560 --> 01:22:39.040
Right, and it, kind of, in mobile,
it kind of morphed into a model

01:22:39.120 --> 01:22:41.840
where you have a super casual
gameplay experience.

01:22:41.920 --> 01:22:47.320
But throwing in a bunch of ads
has been the current,

01:22:47.400 --> 01:22:51.760
like, you know, the manifestation
of how hyper-casual evolved into.

01:22:51.840 --> 01:22:57.360
So, is that ad model moving
from ad to in-app purchases?

01:22:57.440 --> 01:23:00.880
Yes. So, now, it's moving more
to what's being called "hybrid-casual",

01:23:00.960 --> 01:23:02.200
-where--
-Can you explain?

01:23:02.280 --> 01:23:04.840
A hybrid-casual is
more of a hybrid between

01:23:04.920 --> 01:23:08.760
more of a casual or mid-core game
and a hyper-casual game

01:23:08.840 --> 01:23:11.040
with less reliance on advertising,

01:23:11.120 --> 01:23:14.480
because of things like
the lack of targeting,

01:23:14.560 --> 01:23:16.440
because of privacy and things like that.

01:23:16.520 --> 01:23:18.480
Say, if I were building a game today,

01:23:19.240 --> 01:23:22.920
let's say I followed the three steps
that we would put out from the--

01:23:23.000 --> 01:23:25.400
I would ignore hyper-casual.
I would not look at it.

01:23:25.480 --> 01:23:28.320
So, say a young guy has done
the Nvidia free course,

01:23:28.400 --> 01:23:30.480
the Michigan University free course,

01:23:30.560 --> 01:23:33.560
he's on Roblox,
he has learnt how to create a game.

01:23:33.640 --> 01:23:36.000
Now, when I start building the game,

01:23:37.000 --> 01:23:40.960
should I plan to monetise my game

01:23:41.040 --> 01:23:45.200
via in-app purchases versus pay-to-play?

01:23:45.280 --> 01:23:47.200
So, it depends on the game, right?

01:23:47.280 --> 01:23:50.120
So I would say if you're making
more of a mid-core or hardcore game,

01:23:50.200 --> 01:23:52.920
it's generally a heavier IAPCU.

01:23:53.000 --> 01:23:54.200
What is IAPCU?

01:23:54.280 --> 01:23:56.200
-IAP is just in-app purchase.
-[Nikhil] Right.

01:23:56.280 --> 01:23:58.280
Right. So, not advertising-based.

01:23:58.360 --> 01:24:00.560
And then, the more casual
to hyper-casual it is,

01:24:00.640 --> 01:24:03.320
the more advertising
you would integrate into the game.

01:24:04.000 --> 01:24:08.280
But I think, to the point on,
like, if you were learning AI

01:24:08.360 --> 01:24:12.360
and trying to figure out how to apply it,
you could apply it to making a game,

01:24:12.440 --> 01:24:13.880
you could apply it to figuring out

01:24:13.960 --> 01:24:16.640
a completely new kind of game to make
using AI.

01:24:16.720 --> 01:24:18.440
For example, like, were the AI--

01:24:18.520 --> 01:24:22.080
Like Dungeons &amp; Dragons where the AI
is suddenly the Dungeon Master.

01:24:22.160 --> 01:24:24.400
Now, it can do
all the campaigns for you, right?

01:24:24.480 --> 01:24:27.320
There's gonna be new capabilities
and new games

01:24:27.400 --> 01:24:29.640
that are enabled because of AI.

01:24:30.760 --> 01:24:34.200
And the third area of opportunity
would be looking at AI

01:24:34.280 --> 01:24:39.040
and trying to pick a specific segment
in the game development process

01:24:39.120 --> 01:24:43.320
that you can help reduce the cost of
or automate through AI.

01:24:43.400 --> 01:24:44.720
Explain.

01:24:44.800 --> 01:24:46.400
So, for example, like,

01:24:47.240 --> 01:24:50.680
in game development,
there's a lot of different teams

01:24:50.760 --> 01:24:51.800
that do different things, right?

01:24:51.880 --> 01:24:56.760
So, there's engineering, there's art,
there's product management.

01:24:56.840 --> 01:25:01.920
But if you could use AI
to provide a better tool

01:25:02.000 --> 01:25:05.000
or to automate
one of the workflows there--

01:25:05.080 --> 01:25:09.840
Like, so, for example,
right now, coders can use AI tools

01:25:09.920 --> 01:25:12.680
-to help write code for them.
-Like Copilot.

01:25:12.760 --> 01:25:14.040
Yes.

01:25:14.120 --> 01:25:17.440
Also, AI is being used
to generate manuals.

01:25:17.520 --> 01:25:20.480
Product managers can use AI
to do data analysis

01:25:20.560 --> 01:25:22.560
by just dumping in spreadsheets

01:25:22.640 --> 01:25:25.600
and saying, you know,
"Visualise some stuff for me."

01:25:26.920 --> 01:25:31.040
And, so there's a lot of different things
that AI can be applied to.

01:25:31.120 --> 01:25:32.720
And so, then it would just be
figuring out,

01:25:32.800 --> 01:25:37.280
"Okay, what is a big problem
that I can apply AI against?"

01:25:37.360 --> 01:25:38.640
Right?

01:25:38.720 --> 01:25:42.760
Can you give me, like, a low-hanging fruit
that you think is an opportunity today?

01:25:42.840 --> 01:25:44.720
Well, I mean, I can give you
specific examples

01:25:44.800 --> 01:25:46.040
of what people are doing right now, right?

01:25:46.120 --> 01:25:47.920
So, the big thing right now,

01:25:48.000 --> 01:25:50.960
there's two companies, Inworld and Convai,

01:25:51.040 --> 01:25:52.840
that have been funded
for conversational AI.

01:25:52.920 --> 01:25:57.640
Meaning, right now, NPCs in games,
the non-player characters--

01:25:57.720 --> 01:26:00.480
So, like, in an MMO, you can go to a shop

01:26:00.560 --> 01:26:02.840
and then there's a shopkeeper
that talks to you.

01:26:02.920 --> 01:26:06.880
Well, the dialogue
that happens often with,

01:26:06.960 --> 01:26:11.040
whether it's an in-story character
or with a shopkeeper

01:26:11.120 --> 01:26:13.680
that has a very limited amount
of dialogue,

01:26:13.760 --> 01:26:16.360
is through, like, a dialogue tree.

01:26:16.440 --> 01:26:21.160
So, you can use these behaviour trees
to, like, code what is said and not said.

01:26:21.240 --> 01:26:23.160
Or you could use a large language model

01:26:23.920 --> 01:26:26.920
and give the background behind a character

01:26:27.000 --> 01:26:30.560
in a large language model,
understanding the context of the game

01:26:30.640 --> 01:26:33.240
and that character
that they're supposed to personify,

01:26:33.320 --> 01:26:36.920
can then just naturally respond to people
in real-time.

01:26:37.000 --> 01:26:38.680
So that's, like, one application.

01:26:38.760 --> 01:26:41.200
There's other applications,
where there's a company

01:26:41.280 --> 01:26:44.560
that's trying to automate
the art process, right?

01:26:44.640 --> 01:26:50.280
So, like, where you, like, think of

01:26:50.360 --> 01:26:52.880
a character or a building,

01:26:52.960 --> 01:26:56.520
you create the model for it, you put it
in the game, and things like that.

01:26:56.600 --> 01:26:59.360
There are some companies
that are just trying to make it

01:26:59.440 --> 01:27:03.240
so that you do sketches and then
it just automatically goes into the game

01:27:03.320 --> 01:27:04.640
and completes the whole workflow, right?

01:27:05.480 --> 01:27:10.760
So there's a lot of different areas
that you can potentially apply AI to.

01:27:10.840 --> 01:27:14.560
And again, this is why
it's like the cross-something.

01:27:14.640 --> 01:27:18.960
So I wanna learn product management
in gaming super well

01:27:19.040 --> 01:27:20.960
and then try to figure out
areas to attack.

01:27:21.040 --> 01:27:25.480
Or I wanna learn art super well
and figure out areas to attack.

01:27:25.560 --> 01:27:27.520
That's the way
I would be thinking about it.

01:27:27.600 --> 01:27:29.240
Animesh, after listening to this,

01:27:29.320 --> 01:27:31.640
where do you think the opportunity is
for someone young?

01:27:32.560 --> 01:27:36.000
I still feel, obviously,
this is a very big opportunity.

01:27:36.080 --> 01:27:39.040
It's futuristic from all I have read,
all I have seen.

01:27:39.120 --> 01:27:43.400
But I believe that if someone wants
to start building a game tomorrow

01:27:43.480 --> 01:27:48.400
and actually go out in the market
in the next three, four years,

01:27:48.480 --> 01:27:52.160
that data where you mentioned
that 40% of time is going to social media,

01:27:52.240 --> 01:27:55.880
I think that is very key to India
sticking to mobile gaming,

01:27:55.960 --> 01:27:58.400
and my generation people,
the younger generation,

01:27:58.480 --> 01:28:01.000
sticking to mobile phones.

01:28:01.080 --> 01:28:03.440
So, I think, even if I look
at my gaming journey

01:28:03.520 --> 01:28:04.960
and how I got into games...

01:28:05.040 --> 01:28:08.280
After a break from gaming
for a good seven, eight years...

01:28:08.360 --> 01:28:10.920
I think after class eight,
I haven't played too many games

01:28:11.000 --> 01:28:13.840
until I got into college and had some
free time and I was away from home.

01:28:13.920 --> 01:28:15.800
So it all started with Facebook.

01:28:15.880 --> 01:28:19.200
And then I started playing maybe
a Zynga game inside Facebook.

01:28:19.280 --> 01:28:22.360
And then, on Facebook, I got maybe
a recommendation of a Supercell game

01:28:22.440 --> 01:28:24.040
which was Boom Beach.

01:28:24.120 --> 01:28:25.560
And then I went into Boom Beach,

01:28:25.640 --> 01:28:28.960
but the reason why I continued
to play in Boom Beach

01:28:29.040 --> 01:28:32.000
was there's a big social element
attached to that game,

01:28:32.080 --> 01:28:35.240
where I could chat with different people,
make a clan, we could strategise,

01:28:35.320 --> 01:28:36.560
although it was within the game.

01:28:37.200 --> 01:28:40.520
However, what happened next is that
I took that entire set of audience,

01:28:40.600 --> 01:28:44.000
we exchanged our numbers within the game
or we went to a Discord server.

01:28:44.080 --> 01:28:45.880
But then, we were always
socially connected.

01:28:45.960 --> 01:28:47.320
We were chatting, we were conversational.

01:28:48.480 --> 01:28:49.920
If I also look at-- So--

01:28:50.000 --> 01:28:52.920
And that's been the trend in India,
at least, which I can say very confidently

01:28:53.000 --> 01:28:56.760
that people love playing games
which have an element

01:28:56.840 --> 01:29:00.360
where they can connect
with existing friends or meet new people.

01:29:00.440 --> 01:29:02.840
So you're saying
not so much mid-core games,

01:29:02.920 --> 01:29:05.400
but more casual with mobile-first?

01:29:05.480 --> 01:29:09.840
Casual, mobile-first, and needs
to have a social meeting element to it.

01:29:09.920 --> 01:29:12.440
And how easy or hard is it to build that?

01:29:12.520 --> 01:29:17.320
I think it's difficult, not easy to hit
the right chords with Indian audience,

01:29:17.400 --> 01:29:19.240
especially with their culture, also.

01:29:19.320 --> 01:29:20.640
Like, you know, I believe

01:29:20.720 --> 01:29:23.680
that there are a lot of nuances
that they need to be careful about

01:29:23.760 --> 01:29:26.920
when you bring the social element
of being connected online.

01:29:27.000 --> 01:29:30.880
And I think there is going to be
a lot of scrutiny, lot of tapings,

01:29:30.960 --> 01:29:33.080
when they go to build that game.

01:29:33.160 --> 01:29:34.520
What is a "taping"?

01:29:34.600 --> 01:29:35.920
-Sorry?
-What is a "taping"?

01:29:36.000 --> 01:29:38.000
I meant that, you know,
there is going to be a lot of problems

01:29:38.080 --> 01:29:41.720
when they try to have two random people
connect online.

01:29:41.800 --> 01:29:44.400
Because I believe a lot of games
are facing this trouble even today,

01:29:44.480 --> 01:29:48.400
with respect to bullying happening online
or cases that we have had,

01:29:48.480 --> 01:29:51.840
because of people not knowing each other
but connecting within games.

01:29:51.920 --> 01:29:54.800
So I believe that those are the key things
that need to be sorted,

01:29:54.880 --> 01:29:57.600
and because Indian gaming development
market is still evolving,

01:29:57.680 --> 01:29:59.640
so these are a few things
that they wouldn't be able to solve

01:29:59.720 --> 01:30:01.400
when they are building
in India, for India.

01:30:01.480 --> 01:30:05.000
So you are saying young people in India
want to solve

01:30:05.080 --> 01:30:06.480
for both community...

01:30:06.560 --> 01:30:08.120
-[Animesh] And...
-...and timepass.

01:30:08.200 --> 01:30:10.800
Correct. That should be the key factor.

01:30:10.880 --> 01:30:13.120
And that is where I believe
that Sean can answer

01:30:13.200 --> 01:30:14.400
why BGMI is so successful.

01:30:14.480 --> 01:30:16.280
Like, what are those key aspects?

01:30:17.160 --> 01:30:18.840
Hmm... Yeah, my understanding--

01:30:18.920 --> 01:30:21.280
I mean, people, different people
might have different opinions,

01:30:21.360 --> 01:30:26.440
I think, about BGMI
or, like, similar games.

01:30:26.520 --> 01:30:28.520
I think it has very good...

01:30:29.120 --> 01:30:32.480
Largely speaking, there are two elements
for the success, I believe.

01:30:32.560 --> 01:30:33.840
Maybe you guys can add.

01:30:33.920 --> 01:30:36.160
So one thing is social aspects,
definitely.

01:30:36.240 --> 01:30:39.760
Like, it is most fun when you are playing

01:30:39.840 --> 01:30:42.840
with the other squad members,
other three members, as a team,

01:30:42.920 --> 01:30:46.520
which you can keep talking
through the voice chat

01:30:46.600 --> 01:30:49.520
over the 30-minute or 40-minute sessions,

01:30:49.600 --> 01:30:54.640
which gives a good reason for playing
another session, another session,

01:30:54.720 --> 01:30:57.120
maybe tomorrow, or next week,
next weekend.

01:30:57.200 --> 01:30:58.920
That is one factor.

01:30:59.000 --> 01:31:01.880
And the second factor is unpredictability.

01:31:03.080 --> 01:31:08.480
It is mostly like the similar elements
in many multiplayer games.

01:31:08.560 --> 01:31:10.760
But I think,
the battle royale genre itself,

01:31:10.840 --> 01:31:14.960
it has large open-- not really fully open,
but a large map,

01:31:15.040 --> 01:31:19.080
like 8x8, 8 km by 8 km.

01:31:19.160 --> 01:31:23.160
So there are a lot of elements
of unpredictability

01:31:23.240 --> 01:31:25.680
and less repeatability.

01:31:25.760 --> 01:31:28.440
So every gameplay feels different.

01:31:28.520 --> 01:31:31.400
You cannot really make it
if it is a story-based game, right?

01:31:31.480 --> 01:31:35.160
If you play ten hours, 20 hours,
then it's finished.

01:31:35.240 --> 01:31:38.000
I've got a slightly different perspective.

01:31:38.080 --> 01:31:40.240
I'd love to hear your take on this, Sean.

01:31:40.320 --> 01:31:43.360
I don't know if I've ever talked to you
about this before,

01:31:43.440 --> 01:31:50.120
but I believe that games are actually
a manifestation of a latent human desire.

01:31:50.200 --> 01:31:55.440
So I think that people generally have,
in their psychology,

01:31:55.520 --> 01:31:57.040
a need for something.

01:31:57.120 --> 01:31:58.240
[Sean] Mm.

01:31:58.320 --> 01:32:01.920
And so, I believe that games allow people

01:32:02.000 --> 01:32:05.360
to manifest those desires in some way.

01:32:05.440 --> 01:32:07.600
Which psychological desire, though?

01:32:07.680 --> 01:32:09.240
So, let me give you a few examples.

01:32:09.320 --> 01:32:15.000
So, the 35-year-old soccer mom in the US

01:32:15.080 --> 01:32:17.520
who's driving her kids to school all day,

01:32:17.600 --> 01:32:20.680
going home, washing the dishes,
doing the laundry,

01:32:20.760 --> 01:32:23.800
but doesn't feel like there's
much progress happening in her life.

01:32:24.640 --> 01:32:28.640
But then, when she plays Candy Crush Saga,

01:32:28.720 --> 01:32:32.320
she makes progress,
she can see development.

01:32:32.400 --> 01:32:36.320
She can see all these bright lights
and positive reinforcement.

01:32:37.120 --> 01:32:41.320
And I also think that
for some guys, you know,

01:32:41.400 --> 01:32:46.720
it's like, there's a latent
human desire for war,

01:32:46.800 --> 01:32:49.320
-to show that I'm special.
-Yeah.

01:32:49.400 --> 01:32:51.120
In battle royale, in particular--

01:32:51.200 --> 01:32:52.720
And I agree with you. Right?

01:32:52.800 --> 01:32:55.360
And, in terms of, like,
the variability, right?

01:32:55.440 --> 01:32:57.360
And there's been studies...

01:32:57.440 --> 01:32:59.920
I don't know if you guys are familiar
with the Skinner box, but...

01:33:00.000 --> 01:33:02.640
-What is the Skinner box?
-A Skinner box, um...

01:33:02.720 --> 01:33:07.960
So, there was a research scientist
named B.F. Skinner who did a study on rats

01:33:08.040 --> 01:33:12.880
that showed, like, "How can I get a rat
to press this button more often,

01:33:12.960 --> 01:33:14.600
even though there's an electric shock?"

01:33:14.680 --> 01:33:18.120
And then they tried
different kinds of ways

01:33:18.200 --> 01:33:20.040
to incentivise that rat
to push the button.

01:33:20.120 --> 01:33:23.800
And what they found is that
if you provided variable rewards,

01:33:24.520 --> 01:33:26.840
then the rat will keep pushing
that button forever.

01:33:26.920 --> 01:33:29.040
-Yeah. That's why slot machines work.
-And so--

01:33:29.120 --> 01:33:33.960
And the way that battle royale
is structured, it's variable.

01:33:34.040 --> 01:33:35.520
And there's two other aspects.

01:33:35.600 --> 01:33:38.600
So, one, I remember hearing
an interview with Ninja

01:33:38.680 --> 01:33:41.480
who said that the special thing
about battle royale

01:33:41.560 --> 01:33:44.720
is that every battle royale
is like a new story

01:33:44.800 --> 01:33:46.560
because of that variability aspect.

01:33:47.160 --> 01:33:52.000
But the one other thing
I would say is that, on top of that,

01:33:52.080 --> 01:33:55.000
plus I think that
it speaks to Indian culture.

01:33:55.080 --> 01:33:59.760
Like, I think that Indians have
a latent desire to feel special,

01:33:59.840 --> 01:34:05.200
to feel like, "Yes, I won battle royale.
I was the best out of 100 people."

01:34:05.280 --> 01:34:07.000
Is that a cultural thing

01:34:07.080 --> 01:34:09.920
where Indians feel differently
from Americans?

01:34:10.000 --> 01:34:11.080
-I think--
-[Nikhil] The psychology?

01:34:11.160 --> 01:34:13.520
Actually, the psychology
is the same for Americans, right?

01:34:13.600 --> 01:34:15.560
Because, in America,
shooters are number one.

01:34:15.640 --> 01:34:18.040
Battle royale is number one
in the States as well.

01:34:18.120 --> 01:34:22.000
-Mm-hmm.
-It's not true for Japan.

01:34:22.080 --> 01:34:25.600
In Japan, RPGs are number one,
for whatever reason.

01:34:25.680 --> 01:34:28.080
-What are RPGs?
-Role-playing games.

01:34:28.160 --> 01:34:31.640
So, they really love role-playing games,
more than shooters.

01:34:31.720 --> 01:34:35.080
But, you know, in India and the US,
I think it's a similar psychology.

01:34:36.120 --> 01:34:39.240
Battle royale and PUBG
in particular has, though,

01:34:39.320 --> 01:34:41.760
is what I call a high climax moment.

01:34:42.720 --> 01:34:43.720
-Meaning...
-Did you try?

01:34:44.680 --> 01:34:48.240
So, there's, like, one definition of art,

01:34:48.320 --> 01:34:51.560
and the definition of art
that I ascribe to

01:34:51.640 --> 01:34:56.960
is that, for me, art is something
that makes the user feel something.

01:34:58.280 --> 01:35:01.120
So, from that perspective,

01:35:02.640 --> 01:35:04.560
that's what
battle royale does really well.

01:35:04.640 --> 01:35:07.360
What I believe inherently

01:35:07.440 --> 01:35:11.840
is all humans
are permanently chasing status,

01:35:11.920 --> 01:35:13.600
status in any way.

01:35:13.680 --> 01:35:17.920
I can be really moralistic
about something, really altruistic.

01:35:18.000 --> 01:35:21.440
I can vie for sympathy with everything.

01:35:21.520 --> 01:35:24.080
I can chase some kind of status.

01:35:24.160 --> 01:35:27.320
So when we are talking
about status in gaming,

01:35:27.400 --> 01:35:31.160
do you think it's my skill being
better than Sean's, for example,

01:35:31.240 --> 01:35:32.680
which is giving me status?

01:35:32.760 --> 01:35:36.080
Or is it something more ulterior,
something below that?

01:35:36.160 --> 01:35:38.480
I mean, I think status can be gained
in many ways.

01:35:38.560 --> 01:35:44.160
So, for the kind of game,
if it's a shooter game, if it's like PUBG,

01:35:44.240 --> 01:35:45.720
then it will be skill.

01:35:45.800 --> 01:35:47.800
So skill will differentiate you.

01:35:47.880 --> 01:35:50.960
Now, I mentioned that I used to work
at a company called FunPlus,

01:35:51.040 --> 01:35:52.760
and we worked on a 4X game,

01:35:53.440 --> 01:35:55.520
which is more of a...

01:35:55.600 --> 01:35:57.840
It's, you march, you build up armies,

01:35:57.920 --> 01:36:00.600
you work with other people
to defeat other people.

01:36:01.480 --> 01:36:03.760
Like Age of Empires, back in the day.

01:36:03.840 --> 01:36:05.880
That's more of a PC 4X game.

01:36:05.960 --> 01:36:08.600
I think the most famous 4X game
for mobile is called

01:36:08.680 --> 01:36:10.240
-Game of War.
-[Nikhil] Mm-hmm.

01:36:10.320 --> 01:36:13.880
And one of the things that
we say in the 4X industry is like...

01:36:14.640 --> 01:36:15.760
What does 4X stand for?

01:36:15.840 --> 01:36:18.400
Uh, explore, ex--

01:36:18.480 --> 01:36:20.000
I don't know.
I don't even remember anymore.

01:36:20.080 --> 01:36:21.360
[mouths indistinctly]

01:36:21.440 --> 01:36:23.000
-[Sean] I don't remember, either.
-[laughs]

01:36:23.080 --> 01:36:24.600
Exterminate... something.

01:36:24.680 --> 01:36:26.640
Anyway, there's four X's,

01:36:27.280 --> 01:36:29.520
but one of the things
that we just talked about is, like,

01:36:30.240 --> 01:36:34.640
you know, what would somebody pay
to become famous?

01:36:34.720 --> 01:36:37.640
Like, if you could be known
by 30,000 people,

01:36:37.720 --> 01:36:41.000
how valuable would that be to you?
What would you pay for that?

01:36:41.080 --> 01:36:44.120
Well, guess what?
In 4X games, people do pay it

01:36:44.200 --> 01:36:45.440
so that they can be famous.

01:36:46.280 --> 01:36:48.640
Famous in the social circle,
inside the game.

01:36:48.720 --> 01:36:53.200
Yeah. So you might be,
you know, lok'tar59, but...

01:36:53.280 --> 01:36:55.200
And nobody in the real world
knows who you are,

01:36:55.280 --> 01:36:57.400
but, in a specific game,
they might be like,

01:36:57.480 --> 01:37:00.960
"Oh, my God, that's lok'tar59!"
You know what I'm saying?

01:37:01.040 --> 01:37:03.600
So, what you're saying is,
like everything else in the world,

01:37:04.760 --> 01:37:08.280
people inside games, that are working,
are chasing status.

01:37:09.240 --> 01:37:10.400
That could be one thing.

01:37:10.480 --> 01:37:13.080
They could be chasing emotion.
They could be chasing status.

01:37:13.160 --> 01:37:15.080
They could be chasing
a feeling of progress.

01:37:15.880 --> 01:37:18.640
And I think that different types of games

01:37:18.720 --> 01:37:23.680
help people cope with
their latent human desires for something.

01:37:24.680 --> 01:37:28.240
And is it very hard
because of the opportunity cost?

01:37:28.320 --> 01:37:32.520
If I have spent X amount of time
on a particular game,

01:37:33.360 --> 01:37:35.640
derived Y amount of status,

01:37:36.400 --> 01:37:38.120
is there a big moat because of that?

01:37:38.200 --> 01:37:40.040
I will not switch
from that game to another...

01:37:40.120 --> 01:37:41.840
-[Joseph] Yes.
-...'cause I will have to rebuild status.

01:37:41.920 --> 01:37:45.120
Is there a way to transition status
from one game to another?

01:37:45.200 --> 01:37:48.080
Not as-- As far as I know, not right now.

01:37:48.160 --> 01:37:49.960
I mean, that was the...

01:37:50.040 --> 01:37:52.080
I'm not sure how familiar you are
with crypto games...

01:37:52.160 --> 01:37:53.600
-Mm-hmm.
-...but that was like, what?

01:37:53.680 --> 01:37:57.080
One of the things they were trying to do
is to help transfer assets between games,

01:37:57.160 --> 01:37:58.680
-but that never really worked out.
-[Nikhil] Yeah.

01:37:58.760 --> 01:37:59.840
[Joseph] Yet.

01:38:00.600 --> 01:38:02.680
As a gamer, it did work out for me.

01:38:02.760 --> 01:38:06.120
I mean, like, if I look at it,
I had a very good following,

01:38:06.200 --> 01:38:08.520
and people knew me,
8bit_thug in Clash Royale,

01:38:08.600 --> 01:38:11.680
and it really helped me transition,
as a gamer, purely as a gamer...

01:38:11.760 --> 01:38:14.600
transition well into PUBG MOBILE in India,

01:38:14.680 --> 01:38:17.720
and people still knew me
and people would still want to join 8bit

01:38:17.800 --> 01:38:19.560
because they knew me from that
and I had a status.

01:38:19.640 --> 01:38:22.360
But are you talking about your status
in-game or out of the game?

01:38:22.440 --> 01:38:24.200
In-game. In-game. Purely in-game.

01:38:24.280 --> 01:38:26.800
Because, that time, it was--
All my friends within the game

01:38:26.880 --> 01:38:28.560
were people I have never met.

01:38:28.640 --> 01:38:31.600
So I believe that it really helps,
but that's a gamer perspective.

01:38:31.680 --> 01:38:34.720
It could be a unique case as well,
but it helped.

01:38:34.800 --> 01:38:38.320
So while I was researching today,
for today,

01:38:39.200 --> 01:38:42.800
the one thing that seemed to permeate
every domain is

01:38:43.600 --> 01:38:46.760
games saw this crazy spike in COVID,

01:38:46.840 --> 01:38:49.880
but, right now,
the industry is completely screwed.

01:38:50.760 --> 01:38:52.240
People are getting fired.

01:38:52.320 --> 01:38:55.480
In most large companies,
from Microsoft to Sony,

01:38:56.360 --> 01:38:57.960
games are getting dropped.

01:38:59.640 --> 01:39:04.920
And it seems like a fairly tumultuous time
for the industry today.

01:39:05.560 --> 01:39:07.800
How far is that true?

01:39:08.840 --> 01:39:11.000
I actually don't think it's true.

01:39:11.080 --> 01:39:12.320
I don't know if you wanna--

01:39:12.400 --> 01:39:15.560
So, like, yes, because of COVID,
there was a huge spike.

01:39:15.640 --> 01:39:19.800
But if you look at the overall trajectory,
at least, on the mobile side,

01:39:20.600 --> 01:39:22.120
the growth...

01:39:22.200 --> 01:39:24.320
Like, if you smooth out COVID,

01:39:24.400 --> 01:39:27.160
then there was an over-investment
because of COVID,

01:39:27.240 --> 01:39:30.040
and everyone was extrapolating linearly,

01:39:30.120 --> 01:39:33.680
and a lot of additional people
were hired and things like that.

01:39:33.760 --> 01:39:36.080
And now, we're kind of correcting
on the downside.

01:39:36.160 --> 01:39:38.440
But, I mean,
that's a typical business cycle, right?

01:39:38.520 --> 01:39:41.200
Yeah. That is happening
in every industry, right?

01:39:42.040 --> 01:39:43.920
I know Nitish can't say anything
about this,

01:39:44.000 --> 01:39:46.360
-'cause he's in a publicly listed company.
-No, no.

01:39:46.440 --> 01:39:48.000
-[overlapping conversations]
-[laughter]

01:39:48.080 --> 01:39:49.280
At least, honestly.

01:39:49.360 --> 01:39:51.400
[Nitish] I actually answer
this question every quarter, so...

01:39:51.480 --> 01:39:52.560
-Yeah.
-[laughter]

01:39:52.640 --> 01:39:54.600
But, actually, this happened
with India as well.

01:39:54.680 --> 01:39:56.760
But, tell me this, the money, as a gamer,

01:39:57.400 --> 01:39:58.920
that you made two years ago...

01:39:59.000 --> 01:40:00.760
-Yeah.
-...has it gone down today?

01:40:00.840 --> 01:40:02.160
Of course it has. That's what I'm saying.

01:40:02.240 --> 01:40:04.080
But it's a correction.
It's best for the industry.

01:40:04.160 --> 01:40:05.920
If this correction wouldn't
have happened today--

01:40:06.000 --> 01:40:08.680
So, a year earlier, around 2020,
everyone was saying

01:40:08.760 --> 01:40:11.280
this is a bubble that's ready
to burst in India first.

01:40:11.360 --> 01:40:13.040
But, luckily, it was not a bubble burst,

01:40:13.120 --> 01:40:16.880
it was just a slight correction
after all the global crisis that'd hit in.

01:40:16.960 --> 01:40:18.600
And it's a correction,
a correction for the good.

01:40:18.680 --> 01:40:21.320
Because now, if I look
at my side of the industry,

01:40:21.400 --> 01:40:23.640
esports teams, owners,
all those people entering the industry

01:40:23.720 --> 01:40:26.240
with the mindset of making quick money,

01:40:26.320 --> 01:40:28.360
you cannot make quick money anymore.

01:40:28.440 --> 01:40:30.720
So if you look at my company,

01:40:30.800 --> 01:40:34.040
when people were over-investing
into their business,

01:40:34.120 --> 01:40:37.440
when their P&amp;Ls were in red, deep red,

01:40:37.520 --> 01:40:40.480
I was spending the least.

01:40:40.560 --> 01:40:44.320
And today, when the market is bad,
you know, "bad"-- in the bad shape

01:40:44.400 --> 01:40:47.160
where there's not enough money flowing in,
there's no streaming platform money,

01:40:47.240 --> 01:40:48.880
there is no direct money from the brands,

01:40:48.960 --> 01:40:51.760
everyone has tightened their grip,
I'm spending the most.

01:40:51.840 --> 01:40:53.600
And I have been able to sustain and grow.

01:40:53.680 --> 01:40:55.320
So I am growing at a point--

01:40:55.400 --> 01:40:57.680
So I think it all comes
from the understanding

01:40:57.760 --> 01:40:58.880
of how people perceived...

01:40:59.640 --> 01:41:02.240
perceived about Indian gaming
when they entered the market.

01:41:04.320 --> 01:41:06.480
Quick buck because of the COVID ride?

01:41:06.560 --> 01:41:09.400
Or they wanted to build something
for the next ten, 15, 20 years.

01:41:09.480 --> 01:41:12.200
Like, if they had some inspiration
taken from somewhere,

01:41:12.280 --> 01:41:14.440
from a team in America
or a team in Europe.

01:41:14.520 --> 01:41:18.320
If a gamer entered the YouTube space
to build something for the next 15 years,

01:41:18.400 --> 01:41:20.040
or someone was looking
for an overnight success

01:41:20.120 --> 01:41:23.720
because there were a lot of users flocking
into YouTube to watch gaming.

01:41:23.800 --> 01:41:26.720
So I think that changed everything,
and the correction is for the best.

01:41:26.800 --> 01:41:30.240
One thing I didn't ask you is,
your personal journey.

01:41:30.320 --> 01:41:31.840
Where do you make the most money from?

01:41:31.920 --> 01:41:34.400
Is it your content?

01:41:34.480 --> 01:41:36.800
Is it the people you manage?

01:41:36.880 --> 01:41:38.480
I make the most money
from people I manage.

01:41:38.560 --> 01:41:39.600
The talent management business.

01:41:39.680 --> 01:41:43.840
Okay, when I look at establishing
market size in India,

01:41:43.920 --> 01:41:49.560
the numbers state that gamers
were 400 million in '21.

01:41:49.640 --> 01:41:54.520
In '23, they are 560 million,
going up every year.

01:41:54.600 --> 01:41:56.880
This doesn't sound reasonable to me.

01:41:56.960 --> 01:42:02.440
Like, India is a country where 2%
of our population pays tax, right?

01:42:02.520 --> 01:42:06.280
-[chuckles]
-Like, 25-30 million people, tops.

01:42:06.360 --> 01:42:09.800
How are there 560 million gamers in India?

01:42:09.880 --> 01:42:12.480
I think this is RMG
and skill-based, combined.

01:42:12.560 --> 01:42:15.200
And I'm not sure,
because they would have more data.

01:42:15.280 --> 01:42:16.960
-RMG? Real-money gaming?
-Yeah.

01:42:17.040 --> 01:42:19.200
I think it's combined, this data.

01:42:19.280 --> 01:42:21.280
Because we are talking about
55 crore gamers, I guess.

01:42:21.360 --> 01:42:23.200
-568 million. Impossible.
-Yeah.

01:42:23.280 --> 01:42:24.720
But...

01:42:24.800 --> 01:42:27.320
But I think everybody's a gamer, right?

01:42:27.400 --> 01:42:30.480
And one of the things
that we haven't talked about

01:42:30.560 --> 01:42:33.200
is how, because of some
of the stuff that happened

01:42:33.280 --> 01:42:35.920
between the US and China,
going back to that topic,

01:42:36.000 --> 01:42:38.440
a lot of production
is shifting to India, right?

01:42:38.520 --> 01:42:40.120
There's gonna be a Tesla factory in India.

01:42:40.200 --> 01:42:42.720
There's all sorts of stuff
moving to India,

01:42:42.800 --> 01:42:46.560
which should then enable
a bigger middle class in India,

01:42:46.640 --> 01:42:49.960
which should then enable
higher disposable income,

01:42:50.040 --> 01:42:54.280
which should then enable
a lot of people in India to,

01:42:54.360 --> 01:42:57.560
who maybe don't even identify as gamers,

01:42:57.640 --> 01:43:00.640
to then spend in games
because they, actually, are gamers.

01:43:01.240 --> 01:43:04.320
So, what do you think?
Okay, remove real-money gaming.

01:43:04.400 --> 01:43:10.280
How many people in India
are playing games on a PlayStation

01:43:10.360 --> 01:43:11.800
or a computer,

01:43:11.880 --> 01:43:14.400
versus how many people
are playing on a mobile phone?

01:43:14.480 --> 01:43:17.160
And how many people
are doing real-money gaming?

01:43:17.240 --> 01:43:18.360
If you had to break that down.

01:43:18.440 --> 01:43:19.640
It's all mobile, right?

01:43:19.720 --> 01:43:21.440
I think India runs on mobile games.

01:43:21.520 --> 01:43:23.440
-Console would be the least.
-[Sean] I think 95-97%...

01:43:23.520 --> 01:43:25.480
-95...
-[Nikhil] 95% what?

01:43:25.560 --> 01:43:26.720
-[Sean] Mobile.
-[Animesh] Yeah, yeah.

01:43:26.800 --> 01:43:28.040
-[Nikhil] Mobile games?
-[all] Yeah.

01:43:28.120 --> 01:43:29.920
[Nikhil] And BGMI being the largest?

01:43:30.000 --> 01:43:31.920
-[Animesh] Mobile games, could be.
-[Sean] Could be.

01:43:32.000 --> 01:43:34.360
But there could be
a casual game like Ludo taking space.

01:43:34.440 --> 01:43:36.760
From a revenue perspective, yes.

01:43:36.840 --> 01:43:39.880
But I think
the highest-grossing app, uh...

01:43:39.960 --> 01:43:43.480
Wait, 97% of what? Not 550 million.

01:43:43.560 --> 01:43:45.000
95%...

01:43:45.080 --> 01:43:48.720
97% of the whole gaming population.

01:43:48.800 --> 01:43:49.800
Sean can tell us.

01:43:49.880 --> 01:43:51.640
He'll know the numbers
since he's a market leader.

01:43:51.720 --> 01:43:53.600
How many people are playing BGMI in India?

01:43:54.560 --> 01:43:57.360
I believe, uh, like,

01:43:57.440 --> 01:43:59.920
people who are actually regularly playing

01:44:00.000 --> 01:44:04.120
one or two specific games
and, at least, willing to pay--

01:44:04.200 --> 01:44:06.600
Maybe they haven't paid at all.

01:44:06.680 --> 01:44:11.200
Or they might pay once in, like,
maybe three, five, six months.

01:44:11.280 --> 01:44:14.880
Which has capacity to pay,
or willingness to pay altogether,

01:44:14.960 --> 01:44:18.800
might be, I believe,
100 million or 80 million-ish.

01:44:18.880 --> 01:44:20.880
-That's a lot.
-That's still a lot. Uh...

01:44:20.960 --> 01:44:22.360
-Great number.
-[Sean] Maybe...

01:44:24.560 --> 01:44:27.320
the average pay month...
average paying a month,

01:44:27.400 --> 01:44:29.680
might be much lesser than global average,

01:44:29.760 --> 01:44:33.480
but, at least, they are willing
to pay for gaming. I mean, that's...

01:44:33.560 --> 01:44:36.400
The way I look at this space
is for content.

01:44:36.480 --> 01:44:37.520
Hmm, content, yeah.

01:44:37.600 --> 01:44:40.480
Netflix, maybe six, seven million people

01:44:40.560 --> 01:44:42.880
-are willing to pay the $10.
-Hmm.

01:44:42.960 --> 01:44:47.360
It peaks at JioCinema-Hotstar combination.

01:44:47.440 --> 01:44:49.800
Maybe 50 million people are willing to pay

01:44:50.720 --> 01:44:54.240
$10 a year for crazy amount of content.

01:44:55.120 --> 01:44:59.000
So if that is 50 million,
but 100 million are willing to play--

01:44:59.080 --> 01:45:01.320
to pay to play, is a lot.

01:45:01.400 --> 01:45:03.120
And you're talking more
in-app purchases, right?

01:45:03.200 --> 01:45:04.560
-In-app purchases, yes.
-Not pay-to-play.

01:45:04.640 --> 01:45:06.160
Hmm. Yeah.

01:45:07.360 --> 01:45:13.120
I mean, there is no very, like,
good statistics from one source.

01:45:13.200 --> 01:45:17.120
It's more of guesstimation,
but that's my guesstimation.

01:45:17.200 --> 01:45:18.600
And real-money gaming--

01:45:18.680 --> 01:45:19.840
Do you agree with that number?

01:45:19.920 --> 01:45:21.080
Yeah, I think so.

01:45:21.160 --> 01:45:23.120
I think the important point
to also understand

01:45:23.200 --> 01:45:25.360
is there's a perception
that games in India

01:45:25.440 --> 01:45:27.520
are being played by kids or youngsters.

01:45:27.600 --> 01:45:31.640
But I think that's not true at all, now,
and especially after COVID, right?

01:45:31.720 --> 01:45:34.840
It's cutting across demographics,

01:45:34.920 --> 01:45:36.560
-ages, genders...
-I read a stat

01:45:36.640 --> 01:45:38.960
that youngsters are spending
12 hours a day--

01:45:39.040 --> 01:45:40.440
12 hours a week on gaming.

01:45:40.520 --> 01:45:42.680
But I'm guessing adults
can't be spending that much.

01:45:42.760 --> 01:45:43.800
[Nitish] No, they are.

01:45:43.880 --> 01:45:45.680
And different use cases
for different people.

01:45:45.760 --> 01:45:49.440
You know, my own grandmom just touched 90

01:45:49.520 --> 01:45:51.080
and she plays games on her phone.

01:45:51.160 --> 01:45:55.280
And she likes to play word games
for a variety of entertainment, right?

01:45:55.360 --> 01:45:56.720
When we were going IPO,

01:45:56.800 --> 01:45:59.400
one of the things on my mind
was responsible gaming.

01:45:59.480 --> 01:46:01.280
We have a game called
World Cricket Championship,

01:46:01.360 --> 01:46:03.000
which is a popular cricket game.

01:46:04.120 --> 01:46:06.040
Don't virtue signal because
you're a listed company

01:46:06.120 --> 01:46:07.920
and talk about responsible gaming.

01:46:08.000 --> 01:46:10.520
You wish your clients were playing
24 hours a day.

01:46:10.600 --> 01:46:11.880
-[Nitish] No, no, but still...
-[laughs]

01:46:11.960 --> 01:46:13.640
I still had to look at it.

01:46:14.520 --> 01:46:16.200
You're selling a game
at the end of the day.

01:46:16.280 --> 01:46:17.720
No, no, but still.

01:46:17.800 --> 01:46:19.720
Another stat I wanted to ask is,

01:46:19.800 --> 01:46:22.320
I read that, in the gaming split,

01:46:22.400 --> 01:46:24.520
while we were establishing market size...

01:46:25.280 --> 01:46:27.760
First thing, uh, Sean said, 100 million.

01:46:27.840 --> 01:46:29.040
Let's go with that number.

01:46:29.120 --> 01:46:32.920
I am assuming, off the balance, 450,

01:46:33.000 --> 01:46:34.760
a lot of it is real-money gaming.

01:46:36.000 --> 01:46:40.200
No, because 100 million--
He said potential payers.

01:46:40.280 --> 01:46:43.040
-There are a lot of casual gamers, right?
-Who are not paying.

01:46:43.120 --> 01:46:45.640
Yeah, a lot of people, and all--
Again, as I said,

01:46:45.720 --> 01:46:48.520
across demographics,

01:46:48.600 --> 01:46:51.480
playing for time pass,
playing to kill time.

01:46:51.560 --> 01:46:53.040
Like word games, cooking games.

01:46:53.120 --> 01:46:54.520
-[Nitish] Yeah, exactly.
-Sports games.

01:46:54.600 --> 01:46:55.640
[Nitish] And they don't pay,

01:46:55.720 --> 01:46:59.360
so they're happy to see some ads
and continue playing.

01:46:59.440 --> 01:47:00.760
And how big is Dream11?

01:47:00.840 --> 01:47:03.760
What is their number of users count?

01:47:03.840 --> 01:47:05.840
I think it's over 200 million.

01:47:05.920 --> 01:47:07.440
Yeah, that's kind of starting
to add up, right?

01:47:07.520 --> 01:47:09.720
200 from there, 100 from here.

01:47:11.360 --> 01:47:14.280
The balance, 115, casual.

01:47:15.080 --> 01:47:18.000
And people say that the split
is 60 men, 40 women.

01:47:18.080 --> 01:47:20.680
Is that right?
I'll talk about my industry.

01:47:20.760 --> 01:47:27.400
In finance, the split is more like 83 men
and 17 women participants.

01:47:27.480 --> 01:47:29.120
Is it really 60-40?

01:47:29.200 --> 01:47:33.320
I think it's 75-25-ish,
is from what I read latest.

01:47:33.400 --> 01:47:36.360
So maybe, mid-core-ish games,

01:47:36.440 --> 01:47:38.600
which is more like, um...

01:47:38.680 --> 01:47:41.440
which needs more time spent
and more focused.

01:47:41.520 --> 01:47:45.800
That would be 75 male and 25 female.

01:47:45.880 --> 01:47:48.960
I think, casual games, it can become,
like, more balanced, yeah.

01:47:49.040 --> 01:47:51.720
Do you guys have an opinion
on real-money gaming?

01:47:52.480 --> 01:47:57.640
I'm sure you heard
about the taxation in India.

01:47:58.320 --> 01:47:59.840
I'll go through each one of you,

01:47:59.920 --> 01:48:01.800
because it's such a big monster
in the room

01:48:01.880 --> 01:48:03.560
that we have to talk about it, right?

01:48:04.560 --> 01:48:05.560
Like, while I say this,

01:48:05.640 --> 01:48:07.520
Harsh is a really good friend of mine,
the Dream11 guy.

01:48:07.600 --> 01:48:09.880
I think he's Nitish's friend as well.

01:48:10.520 --> 01:48:15.400
But how do you think it affects Dream11

01:48:15.480 --> 01:48:17.520
and all of his competitors, this tax?

01:48:17.600 --> 01:48:20.520
Do you think it's fair
that they did what they did?

01:48:21.120 --> 01:48:23.720
Let's start with, uh, Animesh.

01:48:24.520 --> 01:48:27.600
I don't think it's fair.
I think it was too harsh, but then...

01:48:27.680 --> 01:48:29.120
It was too harsh to Harsh.

01:48:29.200 --> 01:48:31.320
-Too harsh to Harsh.
-Yeah.

01:48:31.400 --> 01:48:34.040
But I felt that it was more harsh
on the profitability

01:48:34.120 --> 01:48:35.960
from my layman understanding.

01:48:36.040 --> 01:48:38.120
Because I saw that Dream11

01:48:38.200 --> 01:48:40.720
did put out a coupon code in a way.

01:48:40.800 --> 01:48:43.360
You know, it did not affect
the end user at the end.

01:48:43.440 --> 01:48:46.200
So I think smart plays
always come into play, and...

01:48:46.280 --> 01:48:48.160
But, yeah, I guess it did take a hit.

01:48:48.240 --> 01:48:51.720
I had good friends in MPL and WinZO
who are really affected.

01:48:51.800 --> 01:48:54.240
I met the WinZO cofounders
a couple of times,

01:48:54.320 --> 01:48:57.360
and they've been our very good clients,
so has been MPL.

01:48:57.440 --> 01:49:00.040
People were really hit hard,
so I actually pity the industry,

01:49:00.120 --> 01:49:01.840
Because that was like a one-night thing.

01:49:01.920 --> 01:49:04.760
It just suddenly changed
everything for them.

01:49:04.840 --> 01:49:05.880
So, all right.

01:49:05.960 --> 01:49:09.040
But, yeah, I think the government
has a big team working for them,

01:49:09.120 --> 01:49:11.360
so they always take the best decision.

01:49:11.440 --> 01:49:13.640
I'm all for free-market capitalism.

01:49:13.720 --> 01:49:18.280
I feel like
if somebody is willing to engage

01:49:18.360 --> 01:49:21.160
with a certain platform, consciously,

01:49:21.240 --> 01:49:26.560
somebody able, willing, adult,
spending his own money...

01:49:26.640 --> 01:49:27.680
I feel like

01:49:28.760 --> 01:49:32.040
regulations skew industries in manners

01:49:32.120 --> 01:49:35.840
which is not always conducive
to innovation and evolution

01:49:35.920 --> 01:49:37.280
of whatever industry.

01:49:37.360 --> 01:49:39.800
I feel like there should be
less control and not more.

01:49:40.400 --> 01:49:44.240
Nitish, this is a more
nuanced question for you,

01:49:44.320 --> 01:49:47.720
because I know Nazara
doesn't really do RMG,

01:49:47.800 --> 01:49:51.320
but you have a tiny component
which is, like, 1% or 2%.

01:49:51.400 --> 01:49:52.800
2%, yeah.

01:49:52.880 --> 01:49:54.720
Yeah. What do you think?

01:49:54.800 --> 01:49:57.080
Look, I think over the last few years,

01:49:57.160 --> 01:50:01.440
it's clearly been demonstrated
that the consumer demand is there.

01:50:01.520 --> 01:50:05.680
Consumer interest
in participating and playing

01:50:05.760 --> 01:50:08.640
real-money games
is definitely very high in India.

01:50:08.720 --> 01:50:10.320
It's not new, right?

01:50:10.400 --> 01:50:14.040
People participating in betting in cricket
has forever been there,

01:50:14.120 --> 01:50:16.040
whether-- It's not even allowed.

01:50:16.120 --> 01:50:17.600
It's banned, but it's...

01:50:17.680 --> 01:50:21.040
Would you argue that it formalised
what was otherwise a black market,

01:50:21.120 --> 01:50:25.240
where we, as Indians, were not
benefiting from the tax revenue?

01:50:25.320 --> 01:50:26.840
Yeah, absolutely.

01:50:26.920 --> 01:50:28.320
What do you think about it personally?

01:50:28.400 --> 01:50:30.680
If I were to ask you about...

01:50:32.160 --> 01:50:37.000
fantasy... fantasy cricket, rummy, poker,

01:50:37.080 --> 01:50:39.520
a whole bunch of games like that,

01:50:39.600 --> 01:50:42.320
which game requires
the most skill to least skill,

01:50:42.400 --> 01:50:43.600
in that order?

01:50:43.680 --> 01:50:44.880
I think, uh...

01:50:46.240 --> 01:50:47.720
So it's not necessarily the game,

01:50:47.800 --> 01:50:49.920
but how it is played
and who is playing it,

01:50:50.000 --> 01:50:52.240
whether it is for skill or not, right?

01:50:52.320 --> 01:50:56.840
But my overall thesis here
is that there is consumer demand.

01:50:58.160 --> 01:51:00.280
People are going to play. When you ban--

01:51:00.360 --> 01:51:01.720
You've seen in many states,

01:51:01.800 --> 01:51:04.040
for example, in India,
where games have been banned.

01:51:05.400 --> 01:51:06.640
The online real-money games

01:51:06.720 --> 01:51:08.120
-have been banned.
-[Nikhil] Mm-hmm.

01:51:08.200 --> 01:51:10.680
The business has usually
gone underground...

01:51:11.720 --> 01:51:14.080
-to more irresponsible players...
-[Nikhil] Right.

01:51:14.160 --> 01:51:16.920
-...which completely exposes the users.
-[Nikhil] Right.

01:51:17.000 --> 01:51:20.960
So I think the right balance
with the right...

01:51:21.920 --> 01:51:23.920
amount of regulation and framework...

01:51:25.000 --> 01:51:27.360
for companies to responsibly do it,

01:51:27.440 --> 01:51:30.760
as well as the government
to get its fair share of tax,

01:51:30.840 --> 01:51:34.120
is probably a healthier place to be,

01:51:34.920 --> 01:51:36.800
versus a completely unregulated market,

01:51:36.880 --> 01:51:39.440
which is going underground

01:51:39.520 --> 01:51:41.800
and getting, you know, screwed up.

01:51:41.880 --> 01:51:45.080
Now, in terms of what is the tax,
what is the fair amount of tax,

01:51:45.160 --> 01:51:47.960
I think there is no perfect answer,
obviously...

01:51:48.040 --> 01:51:50.000
Currently, what was the number? 30%?

01:51:50.080 --> 01:51:51.520
-No, no, so...
-[Nikhil] 28.

01:51:51.600 --> 01:51:53.240
...it's 28%.

01:51:53.320 --> 01:51:57.720
Now, the latest tax on the GST
is 28% on deposits,

01:51:58.320 --> 01:52:00.400
which was earlier 20--

01:52:00.480 --> 01:52:04.880
I mean, gaming companies
were paying 18% on their rake, right?

01:52:06.080 --> 01:52:09.120
Now, the spectrum can be very large.
It could be 18% on rake.

01:52:09.200 --> 01:52:11.560
It could be all the way 28% on entry fee.

01:52:11.640 --> 01:52:13.760
Is the tax now on rake or the money?

01:52:13.840 --> 01:52:15.040
[Nitish] It's on the money you deposit.

01:52:15.120 --> 01:52:17.520
So if you put in ₹100
in your online wallet--

01:52:17.600 --> 01:52:19.240
Do you think that is the part
people are contesting?

01:52:19.320 --> 01:52:21.800
That it should be on the rake
and not the money put in?

01:52:22.800 --> 01:52:25.160
Yeah, I mean, the industry is, of course.

01:52:25.240 --> 01:52:27.800
I mean, they would want
the least amount of tax, right?

01:52:27.880 --> 01:52:29.240
So that is the main contention.

01:52:29.320 --> 01:52:34.560
It is okay to charge the revenue
of the company, but...

01:52:34.640 --> 01:52:36.560
Like, in e-commerce terms, not the GMV.

01:52:36.640 --> 01:52:38.120
Yeah.

01:52:38.200 --> 01:52:40.320
So that's where it is right now.

01:52:40.400 --> 01:52:41.760
I think, over the next few months,

01:52:41.840 --> 01:52:45.360
hopefully, there will be more clarity
on how this pans out.

01:53:05.840 --> 01:53:08.000
I want each of you guys
to come up with one thing.

01:53:08.080 --> 01:53:11.040
What is it that will be relevant
five years from now?

01:53:12.040 --> 01:53:13.160
Wager a guess.

01:53:13.240 --> 01:53:14.640
You wanna go first?

01:53:14.720 --> 01:53:17.960
I think that person needs to realise
that attention span has already declined.

01:53:18.040 --> 01:53:19.440
It's gonna decline further.

01:53:19.520 --> 01:53:21.240
So whatever they are making,

01:53:21.320 --> 01:53:24.720
it needs to move
at a very fast speed for the user.

01:53:24.800 --> 01:53:27.320
So, you both are in contradiction there,

01:53:27.400 --> 01:53:30.600
because Joseph thinks
casual and super casual,

01:53:30.680 --> 01:53:34.920
which might require
lesser attention span, is declining.

01:53:35.000 --> 01:53:36.360
Well, hyper-casual is declining.

01:53:36.440 --> 01:53:39.040
I would say casual
is not necessarily declining,

01:53:39.120 --> 01:53:42.280
but hyper-casual,
in terms of these very casual games

01:53:42.360 --> 01:53:44.280
with a bunch of ads, for reasons--

01:53:44.360 --> 01:53:47.120
In my mind,
I think Snake is hyper-casual, right?

01:53:47.200 --> 01:53:50.600
[laughs] Think Snake,
but they load a bunch of ads

01:53:50.680 --> 01:53:52.000
-on top of it.
-Right.

01:53:52.080 --> 01:53:54.160
[Joseph] Yeah, so that stuff
is starting to go away.

01:53:54.240 --> 01:53:59.160
So what do you mean by, uh, your time...

01:54:00.640 --> 01:54:03.080
focused on the game going down?
How much time?

01:54:03.160 --> 01:54:04.960
I think it's not about the time,

01:54:05.040 --> 01:54:06.800
it's about the next event
that's gonna happen

01:54:06.880 --> 01:54:08.160
when I'm playing the game.

01:54:08.240 --> 01:54:09.920
So I think if I--

01:54:10.000 --> 01:54:12.560
For example, if I'm meeting an NPC,
a non-playing character,

01:54:12.640 --> 01:54:15.800
in the game,
and it progresses my storyline.

01:54:15.880 --> 01:54:18.320
Earlier, when I've played games
like Batman, et cetera,

01:54:18.400 --> 01:54:20.520
we used to have long chats, long dialogues

01:54:20.600 --> 01:54:22.960
that they would use to tell,
the story used to be really beautiful.

01:54:23.040 --> 01:54:25.920
I don't think people are gonna be ready
for that in the next five years.

01:54:26.000 --> 01:54:28.360
The first event, the next event needs--

01:54:28.440 --> 01:54:31.000
The rate at which events happen
in the game, or events occur in the game,

01:54:31.080 --> 01:54:32.320
needs to be faster.

01:54:32.400 --> 01:54:34.920
Because I think swipe-up generation
is gonna take up the world,

01:54:35.000 --> 01:54:37.480
and it's just gonna be
swipe, swipe, swipe.

01:54:37.560 --> 01:54:39.000
So we need to have events
that happen faster.

01:54:39.080 --> 01:54:41.760
Attention span-- Games that
are fast-paced, very fast-paced.

01:54:41.840 --> 01:54:44.800
I think that's the reason
maybe battle royale or FPS games

01:54:44.880 --> 01:54:45.920
would live longer,

01:54:46.000 --> 01:54:47.840
because it always involves action.

01:54:47.920 --> 01:54:50.840
Like, you know,
even if you're standing at a position,

01:54:50.920 --> 01:54:55.880
you're still doing something
which will help the next event occur.

01:54:55.960 --> 01:54:58.840
But when you're playing story mode games
or normal casual games,

01:54:58.920 --> 01:55:01.680
you cannot just be moving slowly
and wait for something to happen.

01:55:01.760 --> 01:55:05.160
Give me an example of the kind of game
which will work in five years

01:55:05.240 --> 01:55:06.800
and one which won't.

01:55:06.880 --> 01:55:11.480
I think there's a game called Among Us,

01:55:11.560 --> 01:55:13.080
it should still work in five years.

01:55:13.160 --> 01:55:15.800
And that works in five years, because?
Something is happening?

01:55:15.880 --> 01:55:17.440
Because something is happening
really fast.

01:55:17.520 --> 01:55:19.440
I believe that we cannot have

01:55:19.520 --> 01:55:22.200
those slow story mode games
that we used to play.

01:55:22.280 --> 01:55:24.520
Same thing we established why

01:55:24.600 --> 01:55:27.000
watching movies and sport
is not working anymore.

01:55:27.080 --> 01:55:31.280
Because you're not interacting
with the interface in a manner.

01:55:31.360 --> 01:55:32.840
You're watching,
and it takes a long period of time.

01:55:32.920 --> 01:55:35.720
Also, I think it could be
a major reason why

01:55:35.800 --> 01:55:38.560
TikTok and reels and shorts
are doing really well.

01:55:38.640 --> 01:55:40.160
I mean, like, last night,

01:55:40.240 --> 01:55:42.440
I was actually scrolling
your podcast shorts,

01:55:42.520 --> 01:55:46.040
and it really took me into a loop
of two and a half hours

01:55:46.120 --> 01:55:49.200
where I just got related content,
I got so intrigued.

01:55:49.280 --> 01:55:51.960
Then I was looking at your guest speaking
at some other places.

01:55:52.040 --> 01:55:54.280
Then I dived down
to Ritesh's other interviews.

01:55:54.360 --> 01:55:56.160
So, it's just a loop.

01:55:56.240 --> 01:55:58.560
And I just saw the clock,
it's 03:00 a.m., and I was like,

01:55:58.640 --> 01:56:00.520
"Good two and a half hours,"

01:56:00.600 --> 01:56:02.720
but that is what it is about.

01:56:02.800 --> 01:56:05.760
But I won't watch two and a half hours
of a movie

01:56:05.840 --> 01:56:08.520
of a content of a related topic.

01:56:08.600 --> 01:56:11.280
And one example of a game
which won't work in five years?

01:56:11.360 --> 01:56:12.400
[Animesh] Uh...

01:56:14.640 --> 01:56:17.840
A very beautiful game that I used to play.

01:56:18.960 --> 01:56:20.600
I'm not able to recollect its name.

01:56:21.920 --> 01:56:24.800
But something like, I would say
a Batman: Arkham Knight wouldn't work.

01:56:24.880 --> 01:56:26.160
It's one fantastic game.

01:56:26.240 --> 01:56:28.160
I think it's slow-paced, because,

01:56:28.240 --> 01:56:29.560
you know, you have those dialogues
coming in.

01:56:29.640 --> 01:56:30.680
Territory-based.

01:56:30.760 --> 01:56:33.080
Yeah, you have to go
from one place to another.

01:56:33.160 --> 01:56:34.920
The movements are difficult.

01:56:35.000 --> 01:56:38.000
I think even if you talk about the way
the movements happen in-game,

01:56:38.080 --> 01:56:39.920
people would want
more simplified versions of it.

01:56:40.000 --> 01:56:43.760
Like, you know, just give us two buttons,
two joysticks, allow us to move.

01:56:43.840 --> 01:56:45.520
Like, even me, I've evolved...

01:56:45.600 --> 01:56:48.440
Like, I'm playing less games nowadays
because I have other work to do.

01:56:48.520 --> 01:56:50.280
But when, now, I want to play new games,

01:56:50.360 --> 01:56:51.800
I tend to play simpler games

01:56:51.880 --> 01:56:56.480
which do not have too many abilities,
too many buttons that I need to use.

01:56:56.560 --> 01:56:58.080
So, maybe, I think
there could be a transition.

01:56:58.160 --> 01:56:59.800
I believe that there are
a lot of people like me

01:56:59.880 --> 01:57:01.720
who are transitioning
into such type of games.

01:57:01.800 --> 01:57:04.480
These are a few things
that might change five years later.

01:57:04.560 --> 01:57:07.160
And, Nitish,
one insight five years from now?

01:57:07.240 --> 01:57:10.040
That people should bear in mind
looking to build a career here?

01:57:10.120 --> 01:57:13.920
I think gaming is on the cusp
of many new technologies,

01:57:14.000 --> 01:57:16.800
and, therefore, the experience
of gaming itself is changing.

01:57:17.840 --> 01:57:20.560
We already spoke a lot about AI,
so I won't repeat that.

01:57:20.640 --> 01:57:22.760
But also, for example,

01:57:22.840 --> 01:57:26.040
I'm personally of the opinion that

01:57:26.120 --> 01:57:29.120
virtual reality will become
far more tangible

01:57:29.200 --> 01:57:30.480
in the years to come, right?

01:57:31.080 --> 01:57:34.400
And I've been playing with
the Apple Vision Pro and the Quest Pro.

01:57:34.480 --> 01:57:37.720
And I think, now the experience
we've been looking at for a decade--

01:57:37.800 --> 01:57:40.080
the company, we've been
looking at VR for a decade--

01:57:40.760 --> 01:57:42.080
it was never there.

01:57:42.160 --> 01:57:43.560
I think the experience has got there,

01:57:43.640 --> 01:57:45.680
and I think once it transcends
a little bit more,

01:57:45.760 --> 01:57:47.560
maybe two, three years down.

01:57:47.640 --> 01:57:52.640
Now, you have three big players,
Sony, Meta, and now Apple in their fray.

01:57:52.720 --> 01:57:57.880
I think you will go from potentially
playing a game to being in the game,

01:57:57.960 --> 01:57:59.680
which can be transformative.

01:57:59.760 --> 01:58:01.640
I know that a lot of people
are still very pessimistic

01:58:01.720 --> 01:58:05.440
because I think they're burnt
for very long on VR and stuff like that.

01:58:06.480 --> 01:58:09.040
But, at least, I believe
that's the future of gaming.

01:58:09.120 --> 01:58:14.600
How does somebody
build the proficiency required

01:58:14.680 --> 01:58:17.040
to cater to games on VR and AR?

01:58:17.840 --> 01:58:20.440
I mean, it's the same tools
that you're using largely.

01:58:20.520 --> 01:58:22.720
Is it, like, a completely different thing?

01:58:22.800 --> 01:58:24.080
Building a game for VR?

01:58:25.400 --> 01:58:26.720
You can use some of the same engines.

01:58:26.800 --> 01:58:29.040
[Nitish] Yeah, the engines are similar.

01:58:30.760 --> 01:58:31.760
[Nikhil] Sean?

01:58:32.800 --> 01:58:33.960
Hmm.

01:58:34.960 --> 01:58:38.600
I mean, Nitish mentioned about AR.
Uh, I mean, VR.

01:58:38.680 --> 01:58:40.640
So I would, uh...

01:58:40.720 --> 01:58:45.040
I feel that AR might be closer than VR.

01:58:45.120 --> 01:58:49.400
I mean, I also bought,
like, a different version of Meta Quest,

01:58:50.760 --> 01:58:55.360
which I used maybe for two, three hours,

01:58:55.440 --> 01:58:57.760
maybe one week or two weeks,

01:58:57.840 --> 01:59:00.240
[chuckles] and then I... I gave up.

01:59:00.320 --> 01:59:01.680
[Nikhil] Why?

01:59:01.760 --> 01:59:03.520
Because, uh, like...

01:59:04.480 --> 01:59:07.480
it doesn't feel very comfortable
to play long hours.

01:59:07.560 --> 01:59:10.760
And that uncomfortableness doesn't,

01:59:12.400 --> 01:59:15.520
sort of, allow me to reengage.

01:59:15.600 --> 01:59:19.160
But I think, AR, for example,
like Pokémon GO,

01:59:19.240 --> 01:59:23.600
which blends the reality--

01:59:23.680 --> 01:59:25.800
I mean, the physical space

01:59:25.880 --> 01:59:27.320
with your smartphone,

01:59:27.400 --> 01:59:29.720
actually gives a lot
of different experiences,

01:59:29.800 --> 01:59:32.760
which traditional games didn't offer.

01:59:32.840 --> 01:59:37.280
I think that can be actually invented
in a lot of different ways

01:59:37.360 --> 01:59:38.560
if you...

01:59:38.640 --> 01:59:40.360
If, as a game designer or game producer,

01:59:40.440 --> 01:59:42.080
if you can, you know,

01:59:42.160 --> 01:59:44.560
really become innovative and experimental.

01:59:44.640 --> 01:59:47.880
So that is my, sort of... yeah.

01:59:47.960 --> 01:59:52.920
What is the role of Discord and Twitch
in the gaming world?

01:59:54.920 --> 01:59:56.160
I'll go?

01:59:56.240 --> 02:00:00.680
Yeah, so, Discord was more
of the chat room that used to exist

02:00:00.760 --> 02:00:02.880
when games did not have VoIP.

02:00:02.960 --> 02:00:05.840
Like, you know,
you could not talk within the game.

02:00:05.920 --> 02:00:08.000
There used to be TeamSpeak,
a software called TeamSpeak,

02:00:08.080 --> 02:00:09.440
then Discord took over.

02:00:09.520 --> 02:00:13.680
However, Discord also brought with itself
the community-building angle

02:00:13.760 --> 02:00:15.080
in the form of a server.

02:00:15.160 --> 02:00:16.360
It's called a Discord server.

02:00:16.440 --> 02:00:19.480
So what you could do is,
you could get your friends

02:00:19.560 --> 02:00:23.480
or people only whom you want to join
inside a particular server

02:00:23.560 --> 02:00:27.280
and do a closed chat
and a closed call outside the game.

02:00:27.360 --> 02:00:31.600
So I think Discord really changed
everything for gaming in a lot of ways.

02:00:31.680 --> 02:00:33.800
But now, Discord has gone
into a lot of things,

02:00:33.880 --> 02:00:36.680
like, it's relevant
to a lot of industries,

02:00:36.760 --> 02:00:40.000
relevant to a lot of industries
that are non-gaming that are into...

02:00:40.080 --> 02:00:42.000
It's a big space for Web3 also.

02:00:42.080 --> 02:00:44.200
I think a lot of Web3 games
are being discussed

02:00:44.280 --> 02:00:46.480
and the communities
are being formed within Discord.

02:00:46.560 --> 02:00:48.040
It's great for art as well.

02:00:48.120 --> 02:00:49.360
Like, I have joined some servers

02:00:49.440 --> 02:00:51.040
which used to have artists in it
who used to help me out.

02:00:51.120 --> 02:00:54.160
So it's a good community-building--
It's a social media platform, I would say.

02:00:54.240 --> 02:00:55.400
Is it a good way--

02:00:55.480 --> 02:00:59.520
Somebody said
Discord is democratising game marketing.

02:00:59.600 --> 02:01:02.520
I don't think Discord has too much
of a role to play in that,

02:01:02.600 --> 02:01:04.320
but I would let them take this question.

02:01:04.400 --> 02:01:06.440
Like, if a game is really good,

02:01:06.520 --> 02:01:07.960
people will chat with each other

02:01:08.040 --> 02:01:10.920
in the gaming community,
in Discord, discover it,

02:01:11.000 --> 02:01:15.480
so traditional marketing for games
might be getting disrupted.

02:01:15.560 --> 02:01:18.680
I mean, I would actually think
that it's more, rather than Discord,

02:01:18.760 --> 02:01:22.640
it's more Twitch and YouTube
that are allowing influencers

02:01:22.720 --> 02:01:24.800
to become the new marketing
for games, right?

02:01:24.880 --> 02:01:27.720
And so, today, you know,
you mentioned Among Us,

02:01:27.800 --> 02:01:31.720
but like, some of those games
were going nowhere for, like...

02:01:31.800 --> 02:01:35.080
I think Among Us had, like,
nothing for, like, three or four years,

02:01:35.160 --> 02:01:39.720
and then some influencers picked it up
and talked about it and then it blew up.

02:01:39.800 --> 02:01:45.600
So, I would agree where Discord
is more of like the community tool,

02:01:45.680 --> 02:01:47.680
the ways that you can have

02:01:47.760 --> 02:01:50.520
a one-on-one conversation
with your player,

02:01:50.600 --> 02:01:54.120
with your players and your audience,
to get that direct feedback.

02:01:54.200 --> 02:01:57.240
So I view it more as a feedback
and community-building mechanism.

02:01:57.320 --> 02:01:59.880
-And we think in similar ways on that.
-Right.

02:01:59.960 --> 02:02:03.520
But I think in terms of marketing,
that would be more Twitch and YouTube.

02:02:03.600 --> 02:02:06.560
And certainly, that has been a big shift,

02:02:06.640 --> 02:02:11.400
is that influencers now
are really driving many installs

02:02:11.480 --> 02:02:15.080
and driving a lot of the word of mouth
and awareness for games today.

02:02:15.160 --> 02:02:18.400
If I had a game,
I did all that we discussed.

02:02:20.360 --> 02:02:22.880
-I did Nvidia's free course...
-Yeah.

02:02:22.960 --> 02:02:25.440
I did the University of Michigan
free course.

02:02:26.320 --> 02:02:28.400
I learned whatever Roblox is.

02:02:28.480 --> 02:02:31.080
And then I built...

02:02:32.080 --> 02:02:35.800
not a hyper-casual, but a casual game,

02:02:35.880 --> 02:02:37.360
which is mobile first,

02:02:37.440 --> 02:02:39.880
'cause most people in India
are playing on mobile.

02:02:39.960 --> 02:02:41.040
You said 97%.

02:02:43.160 --> 02:02:46.440
Do I then integrate

02:02:47.240 --> 02:02:49.920
influencers, Discord, and Twitch

02:02:50.000 --> 02:02:51.960
to sell the game and get the word out?

02:02:52.040 --> 02:02:54.240
Is there a particular way to do that?

02:02:54.320 --> 02:02:56.280
How does a game garner virality?

02:02:58.560 --> 02:03:01.040
See, that's a very
typical way of doing it.

02:03:01.120 --> 02:03:02.560
Like, we're launching a product
in the market

02:03:02.640 --> 02:03:04.640
and you have influencers talking about it.

02:03:06.120 --> 02:03:10.800
The other way of how me as a gamer
would want things to happen

02:03:10.880 --> 02:03:15.520
is involve those influencers
or those key stakeholders or those gamers

02:03:15.600 --> 02:03:17.320
that you actually want to target.

02:03:17.400 --> 02:03:21.840
Obviously, it cannot be the entire cohort,
but at your alpha or pre-beta stage

02:03:21.920 --> 02:03:23.600
-or even before alpha.
-[Nikhil] Mm-hmm.

02:03:23.680 --> 02:03:26.840
So this is one thing that Indus did,
the SuperGaming that I'm talking about.

02:03:26.920 --> 02:03:31.040
Indus invited us a year and a half back
to, you know, just show us the game.

02:03:31.120 --> 02:03:33.840
Just take casual feedback
of how it's doing.

02:03:33.920 --> 02:03:35.640
"What do you think about it?"

02:03:35.720 --> 02:03:38.080
I think those are some key things
that are very important,

02:03:38.160 --> 02:03:40.480
and it really helped
strike a chord between...

02:03:40.560 --> 02:03:42.560
So, it was me and MortaL who went there.

02:03:42.640 --> 02:03:45.920
That, you know, if they invited us
at such a stage to take feedback,

02:03:46.000 --> 02:03:49.160
that means it's a, sort of,
a moral responsibility towards us

02:03:49.240 --> 02:03:51.000
that when this game comes out,
we'll talk about it.

02:03:51.080 --> 02:03:52.480
And we actually went ahead
and talked about it.

02:03:52.560 --> 02:03:53.840
Even today, we talk about it.

02:03:53.920 --> 02:03:56.960
That's the reason I'm talking about it,
because I felt really connected to it.

02:03:57.040 --> 02:04:00.080
So I believe that, generally,
the development story also helps.

02:04:00.160 --> 02:04:02.640
That was the case with how Riot does it.

02:04:02.720 --> 02:04:04.560
You know,
they will call the game Project X,

02:04:04.640 --> 02:04:06.720
then they'll talk about it for two years,

02:04:06.800 --> 02:04:08.240
then they will release teasers,

02:04:08.320 --> 02:04:10.920
then there will be leaks
that will come out,

02:04:11.000 --> 02:04:13.520
and then they will release a game
with alpha, beta, pre-beta,

02:04:13.600 --> 02:04:15.240
and an official launch.

02:04:15.320 --> 02:04:17.800
So I think a good way
to go about it is talk about it.

02:04:17.880 --> 02:04:19.440
Start very early.

02:04:19.520 --> 02:04:21.720
If your product is ready
and then you want to launch it,

02:04:21.800 --> 02:04:23.080
it's always very expensive.

02:04:23.160 --> 02:04:26.280
I mean, like, you know,
the marketing starts way early.

02:04:27.400 --> 02:04:28.880
So this is external marketing.

02:04:28.960 --> 02:04:31.920
You can also build virality
into your game.

02:04:32.000 --> 02:04:35.960
So, one is, if you can play the game
with your friends, right?

02:04:36.040 --> 02:04:38.600
For example, in India, Ludo blew up,

02:04:38.680 --> 02:04:40.680
because when I was playing Ludo,

02:04:40.760 --> 02:04:42.280
I wanted to play it with my friends

02:04:42.360 --> 02:04:43.840
and I would automatically,
through the game,

02:04:43.920 --> 02:04:49.000
easily be able to invite my friends
or family to play with me, right?

02:04:49.080 --> 02:04:51.640
Many games incorporate stuff like,

02:04:51.720 --> 02:04:55.800
you can unlock special features
if you refer this game to five friends.

02:04:55.880 --> 02:04:58.360
There are a lot of hacks
that you can build into your game

02:04:58.440 --> 02:05:02.520
also to drive organic virality
from within your game.

02:05:03.800 --> 02:05:06.080
If I know nothing about the gaming world,

02:05:06.960 --> 02:05:09.960
and I wanna go talk to people
who are in the gaming world,

02:05:10.040 --> 02:05:12.520
where is the easiest place
to connect with them?

02:05:13.840 --> 02:05:15.640
I'm starting from scratch.

02:05:15.720 --> 02:05:19.280
In India, probably IGDC,
the game conference.

02:05:19.360 --> 02:05:20.560
[Sean] The developer conference.

02:05:20.640 --> 02:05:22.960
When does it happen? Who organises it?

02:05:23.040 --> 02:05:25.640
-November...
-[Sean] Uh, Hyderabad.

02:05:25.720 --> 02:05:27.680
-Hyderabad.
-[Nikhil] Hmm?

02:05:27.760 --> 02:05:29.600
-Who puts it on?
-Sorry?

02:05:29.680 --> 02:05:30.800
Who organises it?

02:05:31.400 --> 02:05:33.760
-Um...
-It's a volunteer organisation.

02:05:33.840 --> 02:05:36.560
There is a committee or council members

02:05:36.640 --> 02:05:39.920
who have been in the industry
for a long time.

02:05:40.760 --> 02:05:43.800
I think the Indian typical mind
would work differently.

02:05:43.880 --> 02:05:45.280
Like, if I want to know about something,

02:05:45.360 --> 02:05:47.440
I would search
who the most famous person is

02:05:47.520 --> 02:05:50.280
and try to figure out
where that person is doing a dialogue

02:05:50.360 --> 02:05:51.760
and then reach that.

02:05:51.840 --> 02:05:53.960
I think majority of the Indians
would first come to a gamer

02:05:54.040 --> 02:05:56.120
who is streaming on YouTube or Twitch,

02:05:56.200 --> 02:05:59.120
go to his chat, speak, and then start.

02:05:59.200 --> 02:06:03.680
IGDC, believe me, no 19-year-old boy,
who knows nothing about gaming,

02:06:03.760 --> 02:06:05.120
would ever enter IGDC.

02:06:06.560 --> 02:06:08.120
But maybe a good idea for him, too?

02:06:08.200 --> 02:06:10.440
Yeah, if on the other side,
it's a great idea.

02:06:11.320 --> 02:06:13.680
Obviously, IGDC, I think,
is the biggest gaming event,

02:06:13.760 --> 02:06:15.880
gaming industry event that happens.

02:06:16.440 --> 02:06:19.280
What are some other topics
that you guys think are relevant

02:06:19.360 --> 02:06:21.120
that I might not know about?

02:06:21.200 --> 02:06:22.440
Uh, why...

02:06:22.520 --> 02:06:23.600
For me, it's very relevant.

02:06:23.680 --> 02:06:26.040
I actually want Sean and Joseph
to answer about it.

02:06:26.120 --> 02:06:29.720
Why is that only BGMI and Free Fire
were able to do so big?

02:06:29.800 --> 02:06:32.840
COD:M failed,
a lot of other games came to India,

02:06:32.920 --> 02:06:34.640
tried for two, three months and failed.

02:06:34.720 --> 02:06:38.320
And why is it only BGMI and Free Fire
on mobile games?

02:06:38.400 --> 02:06:40.600
The reason why I'm asking is
because I don't have an answer for this.

02:06:40.680 --> 02:06:43.520
Except for the fact
that I praise you guys a lot,

02:06:43.600 --> 02:06:45.720
that the publisher took keen interest
in the country.

02:06:45.800 --> 02:06:49.040
You guys did set up the esports ecosystem
and everything else.

02:06:49.120 --> 02:06:50.880
This is one thing everyone
would want to know.

02:06:51.640 --> 02:06:55.320
I think Joseph might be the best person
to answer this question

02:06:55.400 --> 02:06:56.720
from the developer's perspective.

02:06:56.800 --> 02:06:59.280
I'm not... myself, I'm not a developer,

02:06:59.360 --> 02:07:02.280
but let me just start as an appetiser.

02:07:02.360 --> 02:07:04.480
-He will serve the main dish.
-[laughter]

02:07:05.280 --> 02:07:08.120
So, from my point of view,

02:07:08.200 --> 02:07:09.760
this size of a success,

02:07:09.840 --> 02:07:13.920
and I believe the battle royale game

02:07:14.000 --> 02:07:17.240
has opened up India gaming industry

02:07:17.320 --> 02:07:19.280
into the different direction,

02:07:19.360 --> 02:07:22.240
compared to, you know,
what has existed before,

02:07:22.320 --> 02:07:23.840
had existed before that.

02:07:23.920 --> 02:07:26.400
It actually happens not very often,

02:07:26.480 --> 02:07:30.000
and it doesn't really happen
with a lot of intention.

02:07:30.080 --> 02:07:33.080
It happens in a very, maybe, luckily,

02:07:33.160 --> 02:07:35.720
or, you know, very coincidentally.

02:07:35.800 --> 02:07:37.960
I think it could happen because of...

02:07:38.040 --> 02:07:41.160
definitely, like,
4G penetration was there,

02:07:41.240 --> 02:07:43.320
and then there was no other genre of game

02:07:43.400 --> 02:07:47.200
which has that sort of reach
before battle royale.

02:07:47.280 --> 02:07:51.160
And also, battle royale game
is not on just mobile

02:07:51.240 --> 02:07:52.960
and console and PC,

02:07:53.040 --> 02:07:57.680
it has opened up shooter games
into different, sort of--

02:07:57.760 --> 02:07:59.920
I mean, expanded the appeal.

02:08:00.000 --> 02:08:04.200
So that actually coincides
in that time period.

02:08:04.280 --> 02:08:07.320
And also, after two years, COVID happened,

02:08:07.400 --> 02:08:11.880
which also amplified that, uh,
that sort of trend.

02:08:11.960 --> 02:08:16.440
So I wanted to emphasise
in a slightly different manner for this

02:08:16.520 --> 02:08:20.960
because I feel that if India wants
to become a powerhouse in gaming,

02:08:21.040 --> 02:08:23.320
especially game development perspective,

02:08:23.400 --> 02:08:28.160
I think young people in India
should try many games

02:08:28.240 --> 02:08:29.720
and try to make their own games.

02:08:30.440 --> 02:08:35.960
I haven't seen many game developers
who become very successful

02:08:36.040 --> 02:08:38.160
in the first title.

02:08:38.240 --> 02:08:41.160
I think even a 19-year-old boy on Roblox,

02:08:41.240 --> 02:08:44.400
he might have made
five, ten different games,

02:08:44.480 --> 02:08:47.480
and then maybe
it's 11th game or 15th game.

02:08:47.560 --> 02:08:51.200
So I think you should not

02:08:51.280 --> 02:08:54.080
try to become perfect to start something.

02:08:54.160 --> 02:08:55.800
You should try something original
on your own,

02:08:55.880 --> 02:08:57.920
even if you feel you're not ready.

02:08:58.880 --> 02:09:01.280
So I have a question for you.

02:09:01.360 --> 02:09:03.760
You launched BGMI in India, you did RTV,

02:09:03.840 --> 02:09:05.680
you have done Bullet Echo two days ago.

02:09:06.720 --> 02:09:09.880
The spends that you are doing
towards popularising the game

02:09:09.960 --> 02:09:12.840
or making the esports
for that particular title popular,

02:09:13.920 --> 02:09:15.600
will it be even, like...

02:09:15.680 --> 02:09:20.080
What percentage would you allot to RTV
or Bullet Echo compared to BGMI?

02:09:20.160 --> 02:09:21.680
-Explain RTV, Bullet Echo.
-Road to Valor.

02:09:21.760 --> 02:09:24.360
-It's a game that Krafton launched.
-[Sean] It's a strategy...

02:09:24.440 --> 02:09:26.040
[Animesh] Yeah,
and it took off really well,

02:09:26.120 --> 02:09:28.480
and even I was playing it,
and then, interest fell off.

02:09:28.560 --> 02:09:31.520
Because, like, interest fell off for me
and a lot of other creators

02:09:31.600 --> 02:09:33.280
because we saw that the esports ecosystem

02:09:33.360 --> 02:09:36.880
is not building as great
as you guys are doing for BGMI.

02:09:37.600 --> 02:09:40.320
Because this is like the gamer
within me asking you that,

02:09:40.400 --> 02:09:42.160
how do you guys go about it?

02:09:42.240 --> 02:09:44.320
And then why someone should build
every other game

02:09:44.400 --> 02:09:48.600
if a company as big as Krafton
is not, you know,

02:09:48.680 --> 02:09:51.320
trying to build every game
with equal interest?

02:09:52.120 --> 02:09:56.160
That's a very good and tricky
question to answer,

02:09:56.240 --> 02:09:59.760
but I will be just bold enough
to answer, give some answers.

02:10:01.280 --> 02:10:03.600
So, I feel that, um...

02:10:04.600 --> 02:10:07.640
Uh, I think you can try
to make a certain game

02:10:07.720 --> 02:10:12.560
to be esports-compatible
when you first design the game,

02:10:12.640 --> 02:10:14.200
but when you launch the game,

02:10:14.280 --> 02:10:17.000
either it's a soft launch
or a commercial launch,

02:10:17.080 --> 02:10:23.320
you find a lot of gaps between
what you actually felt it would work

02:10:23.400 --> 02:10:25.160
and actually didn't work.

02:10:25.240 --> 02:10:27.080
I think, in case of Road to Valor,

02:10:27.160 --> 02:10:29.800
I think we felt that feeling.

02:10:29.880 --> 02:10:32.040
You design certain things, like,

02:10:32.120 --> 02:10:35.960
one-versus-one would be fun,
and fun to play and fun to watch.

02:10:36.040 --> 02:10:40.160
It was fun to play in a way,
but not so fun to watch, to be honest.

02:10:40.240 --> 02:10:42.840
So we added, recently,
like, two-versus-two.

02:10:42.920 --> 02:10:44.920
We changed the UI for people

02:10:45.000 --> 02:10:47.560
to naturally come into
two-versus-two more.

02:10:47.640 --> 02:10:49.760
Like, dynamic and social experience.

02:10:49.840 --> 02:10:53.480
But maybe, timing-wise,
it's a little late, uh, maybe.

02:10:53.560 --> 02:10:55.520
That's a very interesting insight.

02:10:55.600 --> 02:10:58.920
So games today to work
have to be fun to play,

02:10:59.000 --> 02:11:00.560
but also fun to watch?

02:11:00.640 --> 02:11:02.320
-[Sean] Yeah.
-That's where my business is built.

02:11:03.520 --> 02:11:05.760
Anything else
that you guys think is relevant?

02:11:05.840 --> 02:11:06.960
-Nitish?
-[Nitish] Yeah.

02:11:07.040 --> 02:11:09.760
I just want to add a couple of points
which I think are very important

02:11:09.840 --> 02:11:12.520
for our young Indian developers.

02:11:13.640 --> 02:11:18.360
One is that they need to iterate
and ship fast, okay?

02:11:18.440 --> 02:11:21.440
Because if you start a game
as a young developer with a plan

02:11:21.520 --> 02:11:24.640
that I'll ship it in 18 months
and 24 months,

02:11:24.720 --> 02:11:27.240
they run out of money,
it doesn't happen, right?

02:11:27.320 --> 02:11:28.640
And they lose confidence.

02:11:28.720 --> 02:11:32.840
So, I think, initially at least,
they need to take on games and projects

02:11:32.920 --> 02:11:35.880
which are shippable fast,
and then they can get their MVP out,

02:11:35.960 --> 02:11:38.840
or the minimum viable product out,

02:11:38.920 --> 02:11:41.600
and then look at the data and iterate it.

02:11:41.680 --> 02:11:44.280
And if the data is a disaster,
then maybe give it one or two shots

02:11:44.360 --> 02:11:45.720
and move on to the next project.

02:11:46.320 --> 02:11:50.520
I see a lot of developers
get stuck in this loop, otherwise,

02:11:50.600 --> 02:11:51.880
if they're not shipping out.

02:11:51.960 --> 02:11:54.440
And that's a big failure for many of them.

02:11:54.520 --> 02:11:55.880
So, I just wanna highlight that.

02:11:55.960 --> 02:11:57.280
I think the second thing is,

02:11:58.120 --> 02:12:01.200
it's very important
that they focus on the right metrics.

02:12:01.280 --> 02:12:06.880
I often say it's important for them
to focus on the real metrics

02:12:06.960 --> 02:12:09.040
versus the vanity metrics early on.

02:12:09.120 --> 02:12:11.600
And just to give an example
of what I mean,

02:12:11.680 --> 02:12:14.320
usually, when a developer comes to me

02:12:14.400 --> 02:12:15.880
and says,

02:12:15.960 --> 02:12:18.880
"I have 50,000 downloads of my game",

02:12:19.640 --> 02:12:24.200
to me, immediately,
that's largely a vanity metric, right?

02:12:24.280 --> 02:12:27.640
I don't react much to that
because I'm being honest.

02:12:27.720 --> 02:12:30.000
The downloads may mean nothing.

02:12:30.760 --> 02:12:32.440
But if the developer comes and tells me,

02:12:32.520 --> 02:12:36.040
"My D1 retention is 40%,

02:12:36.720 --> 02:12:39.480
my D7 retention is 20%."

02:12:39.560 --> 02:12:41.320
-D7 being?
-[Nitish] Day seven.

02:12:41.400 --> 02:12:42.840
-[Joseph] Day seven.
-The retention of the user.

02:12:42.920 --> 02:12:45.040
Suddenly,
my eyes will start lighting up, right?

02:12:45.120 --> 02:12:48.280
I'll be telling my BD team,
"Okay, meet this developer."

02:12:48.360 --> 02:12:51.240
Do you have a mechanism where
young people can come pitch you games?

02:12:51.320 --> 02:12:52.480
Yeah, absolutely.

02:12:52.560 --> 02:12:55.080
So we launched something
called Nazara Publishing now,

02:12:55.160 --> 02:12:58.280
which is actually meant
to help developers,

02:12:58.360 --> 02:13:01.080
because we really believe
that Make In India

02:13:01.160 --> 02:13:03.000
is a big opportunity
for Indian developers.

02:13:03.080 --> 02:13:05.040
For India and for the world, right?

02:13:05.120 --> 02:13:08.080
So we, of course,
have to have that, and we do have that.

02:13:08.160 --> 02:13:11.120
So how does someone
pitch Nazara Publishing?

02:13:11.200 --> 02:13:13.240
They come to publishing.nazara.com

02:13:13.320 --> 02:13:16.480
-and fill in an application form.
-Nice.

02:13:16.560 --> 02:13:19.000
Do you guys have that, too?
At Krafton and Lila?

02:13:19.080 --> 02:13:20.880
-[Sean] Yeah, we do.
-[Joseph] We don't.

02:13:20.960 --> 02:13:23.120
I mean, they are more like a pure core.

02:13:23.200 --> 02:13:25.760
We're focused on building
one or two games.

02:13:25.840 --> 02:13:27.240
We can't make anything else.

02:13:27.840 --> 02:13:29.640
What is the biggest hurdle you're facing

02:13:29.720 --> 02:13:31.200
in building the game
that you are right now?

02:13:31.280 --> 02:13:32.480
Talent.

02:13:32.560 --> 02:13:33.800
-Yeah?
-Yeah.

02:13:34.760 --> 02:13:36.120
[Nikhil] Because you're in India?

02:13:36.200 --> 02:13:38.400
-[Joseph] Yes.
-Or talent at a cost?

02:13:38.480 --> 02:13:40.160
I touched upon this before, right?

02:13:40.240 --> 02:13:44.480
Because there are so many people
who leave India,

02:13:44.560 --> 02:13:46.200
and it's hard to, you know,

02:13:46.280 --> 02:13:49.280
it's hard to argue for someone
who wants to live in another country,

02:13:49.360 --> 02:13:51.520
who wants to make dramatically more money.

02:13:51.600 --> 02:13:53.000
Why would you wanna stay in India?

02:13:54.600 --> 02:13:58.320
But if the games are going
to compete in the same market,

02:13:58.400 --> 02:14:01.160
one could argue that you could
pay them the same amount of money.

02:14:01.840 --> 02:14:03.880
Once we're profitable, sure.

02:14:03.960 --> 02:14:06.880
And I think that in some industries,

02:14:06.960 --> 02:14:09.360
like, to some degree,
that's starting to happen.

02:14:09.440 --> 02:14:15.120
So, we've seen a pretty fast acceleration
in the compensation of engineers

02:14:15.200 --> 02:14:17.680
over the past four or five years,
as the world became more remote.

02:14:17.760 --> 02:14:19.080
Certainly after COVID,

02:14:19.160 --> 02:14:21.560
I think engineers got paid
dramatically more, right?

02:14:21.640 --> 02:14:24.800
So, we're starting to see
some of that impact as well.

02:14:24.880 --> 02:14:29.120
But one thing I would want
young people to think about,

02:14:29.800 --> 02:14:32.200
really try to start with,

02:14:32.280 --> 02:14:34.880
"What do you want from your life?"

02:14:34.960 --> 02:14:36.160
I think that's a question

02:14:36.240 --> 02:14:39.840
that not enough young people
have asked themselves.

02:14:40.920 --> 02:14:44.200
And I think that some people
have bought into, like,

02:14:44.280 --> 02:14:46.960
these notions of, you know,

02:14:47.040 --> 02:14:53.200
the popularised notions of quiet quitting,
side hustle, things like that.

02:14:53.280 --> 02:14:57.920
And I just think that if more people
really thought critically about

02:14:58.000 --> 02:15:00.600
what they're really searching for
in their life,

02:15:00.680 --> 02:15:02.640
that they'd be able
to make better decisions

02:15:02.720 --> 02:15:04.680
about the path that they would choose.

02:15:05.520 --> 02:15:08.880
And there's an exercise, actually,
I believe it was Clayton Christensen

02:15:08.960 --> 02:15:11.920
who wrote about an exercise
that he recommended for people,

02:15:12.000 --> 02:15:14.760
which is to think about your life

02:15:14.840 --> 02:15:17.800
when you're on your deathbed,
and thinking back,

02:15:17.880 --> 02:15:19.480
and what would make you proud?

02:15:19.560 --> 02:15:23.040
How would you measure the value
of your life looking back?

02:15:23.120 --> 02:15:24.880
I think not enough young people do that.

02:15:24.960 --> 02:15:27.480
And I think that that's something

02:15:27.560 --> 02:15:29.760
that, as an older guy
who didn't think about that

02:15:29.840 --> 02:15:33.920
for way too much of my life, I wish I had.

02:15:34.000 --> 02:15:37.760
I want to highlight or pick

02:15:37.840 --> 02:15:41.200
five most relevant skill sets

02:15:41.280 --> 02:15:43.120
required to build a career in gaming.

02:15:43.200 --> 02:15:45.600
Each one of you can tell me one.

02:15:46.200 --> 02:15:47.400
What do we start with?

02:15:47.480 --> 02:15:49.200
You mentioned art earlier.

02:15:49.280 --> 02:15:50.400
-[Joseph] Yeah.
-[Nikhil] So...

02:15:50.480 --> 02:15:52.120
-Oh, you mean the disciplines?
-[Nikhil] Yeah.

02:15:52.200 --> 02:15:53.560
So, there's probably
four main disciplines.

02:15:53.640 --> 02:15:56.160
There's art, engineering,

02:15:56.240 --> 02:15:59.320
or development, um,

02:15:59.400 --> 02:16:02.640
third is product management or production,

02:16:03.680 --> 02:16:06.840
-and fourth is design.
-[Sean] Game design.

02:16:06.920 --> 02:16:08.200
Design, yeah.

02:16:08.280 --> 02:16:10.760
And fifth is, if I can go with the fifth,

02:16:10.840 --> 02:16:12.920
is, I think, which is very important,

02:16:13.000 --> 02:16:14.640
is also your data analytics.

02:16:14.720 --> 02:16:16.400
-[Sean] Data analytics.
-[Joseph] Yeah.

02:16:16.480 --> 02:16:18.360
-Being able to understand data...
-Yeah.

02:16:18.440 --> 02:16:23.640
...and react to data is very important.

02:16:23.720 --> 02:16:25.840
Okay, so, what does somebody need

02:16:25.920 --> 02:16:28.520
to build a career in art
in the gaming world?

02:16:29.880 --> 02:16:31.040
[Sean] Hmm.

02:16:32.480 --> 02:16:35.360
I mean, get the necessary skills.

02:16:35.440 --> 02:16:38.560
Also, there's a big difference
between 2D and 3D art.

02:16:38.640 --> 02:16:39.840
[Nikhil] Mm-hmm.

02:16:39.920 --> 02:16:42.240
There's a difference between doing, like,

02:16:42.320 --> 02:16:44.960
concept art versus, like, production art.

02:16:45.040 --> 02:16:48.480
There's a lot of nuance there within art.

02:16:49.400 --> 02:16:51.240
So give me--
Okay, let's say there's 3D art,

02:16:51.320 --> 02:16:52.800
-there's 2D art.
-[Joseph] Yeah.

02:16:52.880 --> 02:16:56.680
And then, within that, there's also, like,

02:16:56.760 --> 02:16:59.200
are you focused on characters
or are you focused on environment?

02:16:59.280 --> 02:17:00.320
[Nikhil] Okay.

02:17:01.080 --> 02:17:02.160
[Joseph] Um...

02:17:03.360 --> 02:17:05.240
And how does somebody learn

02:17:05.320 --> 02:17:08.000
how to make 2D art, 3D art,
character, or environment...

02:17:08.080 --> 02:17:09.680
Usually, there's schools for that.

02:17:09.760 --> 02:17:11.320
For example?

02:17:11.400 --> 02:17:12.920
I don't know the name
of the schools in India.

02:17:13.000 --> 02:17:15.720
In India, it could be something like
Arena Animation or something.

02:17:15.800 --> 02:17:19.560
And how much does somebody
working in the art side of gaming

02:17:19.640 --> 02:17:21.440
make as a starting pay?

02:17:21.520 --> 02:17:23.640
-Not much. [laughs]
-[Sean] Art is lower side.

02:17:23.720 --> 02:17:25.640
-[Joseph] It's the lowest.
-Yeah?

02:17:25.720 --> 02:17:27.320
But depends who the consumer is.

02:17:27.400 --> 02:17:29.960
But lower side is how much? In India?

02:17:31.000 --> 02:17:36.240
I would say the very lowest I've seen
is, like, five lakhs or less.

02:17:36.320 --> 02:17:37.600
-[Nikhil] Per year?
-[Sean] Entry-level.

02:17:37.680 --> 02:17:39.920
[Joseph] Entry-level.
We're talking entry-level.

02:17:40.000 --> 02:17:41.600
[Nikhil] Five lakhs a year.

02:17:41.680 --> 02:17:44.760
And you also mentioned,
Joseph and Nitish actually,

02:17:44.840 --> 02:17:50.160
that AI might make
this entire section redundant very fast.

02:17:50.240 --> 02:17:51.480
It might be, yeah.

02:17:51.560 --> 02:17:53.840
At least a lower or middle-level,
up to middle-level.

02:17:53.920 --> 02:17:56.240
Maybe very senior,

02:17:56.320 --> 02:17:58.200
or maybe someone at the, like...

02:17:58.280 --> 02:18:00.480
who can make some direction.

02:18:01.400 --> 02:18:02.720
Maybe they...

02:18:02.800 --> 02:18:05.760
But then they can be replaced
by some game designer or choreographer.

02:18:05.840 --> 02:18:08.760
Yeah, I mean, I don't know if you guys
have checked out suno.ai,

02:18:08.840 --> 02:18:10.800
but, like, if you haven't,
you absolutely should.

02:18:10.880 --> 02:18:13.600
You just give it, like, some descriptions,

02:18:13.680 --> 02:18:15.840
it'll automatically create music.

02:18:15.920 --> 02:18:17.680
And you can see where that is today.

02:18:17.760 --> 02:18:19.960
In two to three years, I...

02:18:20.040 --> 02:18:22.880
We could be living in a world
where most of the music we hear

02:18:22.960 --> 02:18:26.080
is AI-generated
rather than generated by human beings.

02:18:26.160 --> 02:18:28.520
Similarly for art,

02:18:28.600 --> 02:18:31.080
we're kind of getting to a place

02:18:31.160 --> 02:18:33.440
where you can, kind of, describe things

02:18:33.520 --> 02:18:36.200
and then many variations
just kind of pop up.

02:18:36.920 --> 02:18:38.640
-Um...
-[Nikhil] So, you wouldn't recommend--

02:18:38.720 --> 02:18:41.360
If you had a 14-year-old child,
you wouldn't say...

02:18:41.440 --> 02:18:44.400
If I'm thinking macro,
I would be like, "Ugh, art?"

02:18:44.480 --> 02:18:46.920
-[Nikhil] No.
-I'd probably--

02:18:47.000 --> 02:18:50.040
Unless you really had
a very specific skill.

02:18:50.120 --> 02:18:52.280
-[Nikhil] Mm-hmm.
-Because I think, ultimately,

02:18:52.360 --> 02:18:55.320
masters at their craft
are masters at their craft.

02:18:55.400 --> 02:18:59.080
But otherwise, I would probably avoid it.

02:18:59.160 --> 02:19:00.880
So you're swimming
against the tide in art.

02:19:00.960 --> 02:19:03.560
Yes. And maybe
in engineering, too, because...

02:19:03.640 --> 02:19:06.640
What does the engineering
breakdown look like?

02:19:06.720 --> 02:19:08.160
So, for...

02:19:08.240 --> 02:19:10.400
Well, I would say there isn't...

02:19:10.480 --> 02:19:14.840
there's more of a linear path
in engineering, I would say.

02:19:14.920 --> 02:19:16.800
Except for-- You're generally thinking

02:19:16.880 --> 02:19:19.040
in terms of front-end versus back-end.

02:19:19.120 --> 02:19:22.600
And in the front-end,
you're generally going to be working

02:19:22.680 --> 02:19:26.960
with one of the two primary game engines,
Unity or Unreal.

02:19:27.040 --> 02:19:29.960
And so, you would learn either C# or C++

02:19:30.040 --> 02:19:32.080
depending on which engine you use.

02:19:32.160 --> 02:19:34.160
And then for back-end...

02:19:34.240 --> 02:19:38.000
So the front-end means, like,
the thing you actually play, right?

02:19:38.080 --> 02:19:41.440
The combat, the characters
that move around, all the functionality.

02:19:41.520 --> 02:19:42.720
Like the UI, in a way.

02:19:42.800 --> 02:19:45.040
All that stuff. That's included there.

02:19:45.120 --> 02:19:46.920
And then the back-end is like

02:19:47.000 --> 02:19:50.760
when you're saving your stats
to the back-end server, the netcode,

02:19:50.840 --> 02:19:52.560
so that you can play
against other players.

02:19:52.640 --> 02:19:54.040
All the stuff you kind of don't see,

02:19:54.120 --> 02:19:56.880
but makes the game operate
in the back-end.

02:19:56.960 --> 02:19:58.560
So, then, generally speaking,

02:19:58.640 --> 02:20:01.440
you have engineers oriented around
one of those two,

02:20:01.520 --> 02:20:03.040
either front-end or back-end.

02:20:03.120 --> 02:20:05.280
But you also have some full-stack guys.

02:20:05.360 --> 02:20:06.680
So you would go C#,

02:20:06.760 --> 02:20:09.600
learn how to use Unity, Unreal,
and become really proficient in that.

02:20:09.680 --> 02:20:12.720
Yeah, I would probably recommend

02:20:12.800 --> 02:20:15.360
for India, for right now, Unity, C#.

02:20:15.440 --> 02:20:19.520
But later, I would recommend C++, Unreal.

02:20:19.600 --> 02:20:21.120
Unreal is trying to take over.

02:20:21.200 --> 02:20:24.760
But you know, in the long term,
if current trends continue,

02:20:24.840 --> 02:20:27.360
Unreal is likely the engine of choice

02:20:27.440 --> 02:20:29.760
-in the not-too-distant future.
-Nice.

02:20:29.840 --> 02:20:32.480
And how much would somebody
in engineering make on average,

02:20:32.560 --> 02:20:34.680
-front and back-end?
-It depends.

02:20:34.760 --> 02:20:37.120
-That depends on the school.
-[chuckles]

02:20:37.720 --> 02:20:40.680
Right? So, like,
if you go to IIT and you come out,

02:20:40.760 --> 02:20:43.080
you can make, you know, 40-50 lakhs.

02:20:43.160 --> 02:20:45.880
-I mean, it's, uh...
-With no experience?

02:20:45.960 --> 02:20:48.320
With no experience. It's possible, yeah.

02:20:48.400 --> 02:20:50.600
Assuming that you will catch up very fast.

02:20:50.680 --> 02:20:51.720
Yeah.

02:20:51.800 --> 02:20:54.200
And also assuming
that you will actually get hired.

02:20:54.280 --> 02:20:57.040
But he's saying they're lacking talent.
They're looking for people.

02:20:57.120 --> 02:20:59.800
Actually, you know,
I see a lot of job openings on LinkedIn

02:20:59.880 --> 02:21:02.480
from the popular developers or publishers.

02:21:02.560 --> 02:21:06.360
I don't see any opening
for a newbie into the industry.

02:21:06.440 --> 02:21:07.680
-[Nikhil] Really?
-Yes.

02:21:07.760 --> 02:21:09.000
I might be wrong here,

02:21:09.080 --> 02:21:12.160
but from the openings
that I've tried to go by,

02:21:12.240 --> 02:21:15.320
I don't think big studios
are hiring people who are freshers.

02:21:15.400 --> 02:21:18.320
The small guys. What we still do,
we still hire freshers.

02:21:18.400 --> 02:21:20.280
[Sean] We also...

02:21:20.360 --> 02:21:23.760
We try to hire, like, experienced guys,

02:21:24.720 --> 02:21:26.320
but, then, it didn't work out very well.

02:21:26.400 --> 02:21:27.560
And then, there is some gap.

02:21:27.640 --> 02:21:30.960
Like, we expect this level of experience,
but they don't...

02:21:31.040 --> 02:21:32.640
So we actually changed the direction.

02:21:32.720 --> 02:21:34.600
On the engineering side though,
there's a big gap, right?

02:21:34.680 --> 02:21:36.760
We generally don't like to hire from IIT

02:21:36.840 --> 02:21:39.680
just because there's such a huge premium
for those guys.

02:21:39.760 --> 02:21:42.800
But, yeah, it can come down quite a bit.

02:21:42.880 --> 02:21:47.080
Is there a way somebody
who does engineering,

02:21:47.160 --> 02:21:50.720
learns Unity, Unreal, C#, C++,

02:21:50.800 --> 02:21:53.960
can get experience
without having a full-time job?

02:21:54.040 --> 02:21:55.520
-Yeah.
-[Nikhil] Internship opportunities?

02:21:55.600 --> 02:21:59.000
They build their own projects,
publish them,

02:21:59.080 --> 02:22:00.760
submit them to GitHub.

02:22:00.840 --> 02:22:04.760
So, yeah, there's a lot of ways
where you can distinguish yourself

02:22:04.840 --> 02:22:08.000
as a good engineer if you wanted to.

02:22:08.080 --> 02:22:10.080
But, also,

02:22:10.160 --> 02:22:12.600
I think the thing that's missing
from most of the people

02:22:12.680 --> 02:22:16.280
that I've interviewed in India
for game development,

02:22:16.360 --> 02:22:17.960
unlike other places,

02:22:18.040 --> 02:22:22.480
is just hardcore, like,
math and logic skills.

02:22:22.560 --> 02:22:25.640
That's something
that is critical as an engineer,

02:22:25.720 --> 02:22:27.920
but seems to be lacking quite a lot.

02:22:29.320 --> 02:22:31.360
Okay, even from the IIT crowd?

02:22:31.440 --> 02:22:32.840
No, the IIT guys are fine.

02:22:32.920 --> 02:22:35.200
[laughter]

02:22:36.440 --> 02:22:38.080
Do you hire from the same place?

02:22:39.480 --> 02:22:42.480
Yeah, but, you know,
we have a very distributed way of working.

02:22:42.560 --> 02:22:45.360
So, we have different studios that we own,

02:22:45.440 --> 02:22:48.840
and each have their own different policies
of how they are recruiting.

02:22:48.920 --> 02:22:50.560
-Right.
-It's not very centralised.

02:22:50.640 --> 02:22:52.520
[Nikhil] Right, right. Okay.

02:22:52.600 --> 02:22:54.840
Production? Product management?

02:22:55.880 --> 02:22:59.000
Yeah, so product management is,
I would say,

02:22:59.960 --> 02:23:06.000
a pretty difficult skill
to, kind of, learn on your own.

02:23:06.080 --> 02:23:11.120
It does-- In my opinion,
it requires, like, hands-on practice.

02:23:11.200 --> 02:23:13.880
Um, but there are a number
of online resources.

02:23:13.960 --> 02:23:17.720
We provide some resources as well
that teach about product management.

02:23:17.800 --> 02:23:20.720
So, I can share
some of those links, but I--

02:23:20.800 --> 02:23:23.240
Would it typically be an engineering guy

02:23:23.320 --> 02:23:26.000
upgrading or getting promoted
to be a product manager?

02:23:26.080 --> 02:23:28.760
Not necessarily. Not usually.

02:23:28.840 --> 02:23:33.240
But I will say that
in our product team at Lila,

02:23:33.320 --> 02:23:36.640
two of our product managers,
we hired from engineering.

02:23:36.720 --> 02:23:38.240
And similar to Sean's case...

02:23:39.560 --> 02:23:42.480
what I have realised is that,
in our case, too,

02:23:42.560 --> 02:23:47.360
we prefer to hire people who are new
but hungry and wanting to learn

02:23:47.440 --> 02:23:50.560
versus people who have worked
at an existing game company in India

02:23:50.640 --> 02:23:52.240
for four to five years because...

02:23:53.280 --> 02:23:55.440
I kind of touched upon this before.

02:23:55.520 --> 02:23:59.760
Live services and live operating a game,
that set of skills is very different.

02:23:59.840 --> 02:24:03.360
It's a difference between
0-to-1 versus 1-to-N.

02:24:03.440 --> 02:24:05.360
What is the skill?

02:24:05.440 --> 02:24:07.960
The skill in terms of, like,
new game development

02:24:08.520 --> 02:24:12.440
is so different from live operations
where everything's kind of figured out.

02:24:12.520 --> 02:24:13.600
It's like...

02:24:13.680 --> 02:24:17.360
I'm just following
the normal playbook, right?

02:24:17.440 --> 02:24:18.640
I think...

02:24:18.720 --> 02:24:23.960
In new game development,
you have to be kind of brutal,

02:24:24.040 --> 02:24:26.360
very effective.

02:24:26.440 --> 02:24:28.920
The communication style...

02:24:29.000 --> 02:24:32.840
There's a whole difference
in culture and mentality

02:24:32.920 --> 02:24:36.040
for new game development
versus live operations.

02:24:36.120 --> 02:24:40.680
Does it also equate to the nuance
of scale, building for scale?

02:24:40.760 --> 02:24:42.600
Is that the product manager's role?

02:24:42.680 --> 02:24:45.560
Well, I think it's building for
product-market fit

02:24:45.640 --> 02:24:47.240
relative to 1-to-N,

02:24:47.320 --> 02:24:48.920
where you are building for larger scale.

02:24:50.840 --> 02:24:53.280
And I'm assuming these guys
get paid the most, right?

02:24:53.360 --> 02:24:56.320
I would say engineers
right now get paid the most.

02:24:56.400 --> 02:24:57.840
-More than product managers.
-[Joseph] Yes.

02:24:57.920 --> 02:24:59.400
-So this would be--
-[Joseph] The second most.

02:24:59.480 --> 02:25:01.840
Thirty lakhs, 20 lakhs.

02:25:01.920 --> 02:25:03.760
Uh, starting off, it's less.

02:25:03.840 --> 02:25:06.600
I think starting off, product managers...

02:25:07.920 --> 02:25:09.520
I mean, again, it depends on the school,

02:25:09.600 --> 02:25:12.200
but I mean, you know,
I think starting product managers

02:25:12.280 --> 02:25:13.880
would make ten lakhs or less.
I don't know.

02:25:13.960 --> 02:25:16.080
You guys know the numbers
better than I do.

02:25:16.160 --> 02:25:19.120
I agree. Like product manager
in the junior level,

02:25:19.200 --> 02:25:21.960
they don't make too much difference.

02:25:22.040 --> 02:25:25.040
So, their entry salary would be lower...

02:25:25.120 --> 02:25:27.160
-[Joseph] Lower, yeah.
-Slightly higher than artists.

02:25:27.240 --> 02:25:32.280
But I think if they go to the producer,
like we are the main producer level,

02:25:32.360 --> 02:25:35.480
then their salary
can be as equal as engineers.

02:25:35.560 --> 02:25:37.440
-On the higher end.
-[Sean] On the higher end.

02:25:37.520 --> 02:25:38.520
And the design?

02:25:39.560 --> 02:25:41.160
Design, so--

02:25:41.240 --> 02:25:44.240
I would have assumed
art and design are very similar, no?

02:25:44.320 --> 02:25:45.320
It's not like art design.

02:25:45.400 --> 02:25:48.240
-It's more like game... the core gameplay.
-[Joseph] Game design.

02:25:48.320 --> 02:25:52.400
Now, I would say that design
is the weakest area in India.

02:25:52.480 --> 02:25:53.800
Yeah.

02:25:53.880 --> 02:25:55.400
So finding a good designer...

02:25:55.480 --> 02:25:57.880
I don't even know
where you go to learn that.

02:25:57.960 --> 02:25:58.960
Why is that?

02:25:59.880 --> 02:26:01.080
[Joseph] Um...

02:26:01.960 --> 02:26:03.400
-[Nitish speaking indistinctly]
-I don't know.

02:26:03.480 --> 02:26:06.200
Yeah. No, no.
It's because traditionally in India,

02:26:06.280 --> 02:26:10.800
animation art has always been
an industry, right?

02:26:10.880 --> 02:26:14.680
Even job work for just animation,
forget gaming.

02:26:14.760 --> 02:26:18.520
Similarly, coding across industries
has always been there.

02:26:18.600 --> 02:26:21.560
-[Nikhil] Mm-hmm.
-But design specifically for a game,

02:26:21.640 --> 02:26:25.400
which requires, "How do you
make a game that is engaging?" Right?

02:26:25.480 --> 02:26:28.320
How do you get the user
in that flow state?

02:26:29.120 --> 02:26:33.320
I think that thinking, it comes naturally
when you are really exposed to it

02:26:33.400 --> 02:26:34.880
over a very long period of time.

02:26:34.960 --> 02:26:39.840
So if I am a designer, a game designer,
I will pick when to shoot,

02:26:39.920 --> 02:26:43.840
when the real characters come in,
when the static characters go out,

02:26:43.920 --> 02:26:45.280
stuff like that?

02:26:45.360 --> 02:26:48.360
-[Nitish] Somewhat, all of that.
-[Animesh] That's the gameplay structure.

02:26:48.440 --> 02:26:50.920
It's not "design"
as much as figuring the flow?

02:26:51.000 --> 02:26:52.000
It's complex.

02:26:52.080 --> 02:26:54.480
Yeah. It's complicated
'cause there's actually, like...

02:26:54.560 --> 02:26:57.880
I would probably characterise
game design in two parts.

02:26:57.960 --> 02:27:00.360
One is gameplay, right? Which is like...

02:27:01.080 --> 02:27:02.160
For any kind of...

02:27:02.240 --> 02:27:04.240
The way you typically think
about a game, you know,

02:27:04.320 --> 02:27:06.520
for Snake, what do you do?
What are the actions?

02:27:06.600 --> 02:27:09.000
What are the, kind of,
specific things happening?

02:27:09.080 --> 02:27:11.840
And then the second part of design
is systems design.

02:27:11.920 --> 02:27:13.240
You mentioned meta, right?

02:27:13.320 --> 02:27:17.560
And so the meta or systems part
is like the progression-compulsion part,

02:27:17.640 --> 02:27:20.800
where you might have a crafting system,
you might be building a house.

02:27:20.880 --> 02:27:22.320
It's not the main gameplay.

02:27:22.400 --> 02:27:24.640
You might play the game, earn some stuff,

02:27:24.720 --> 02:27:26.720
and then go craft something
somewhere else, right?

02:27:26.800 --> 02:27:28.760
But these two are generally separate.

02:27:28.840 --> 02:27:32.280
And generally, like,
someone great at gameplay design,

02:27:32.360 --> 02:27:35.320
in terms of the combat, feel of the guns,
things like that,

02:27:35.400 --> 02:27:38.720
is often different from the person
who is designing the systems.

02:27:40.000 --> 02:27:42.600
-And--
-I would say the game design

02:27:42.680 --> 02:27:46.560
requires the most creativity
among all other disciplines.

02:27:46.640 --> 02:27:53.240
And then it can be generally taught
through some kind of apprenticeship,

02:27:53.320 --> 02:27:57.720
but it also requires kind of natural-born
or educated creativity.

02:27:57.800 --> 02:28:04.000
So which... If you don't have that
culture of bringing up those talents,

02:28:04.080 --> 02:28:06.880
then it might not come out easily so...

02:28:06.960 --> 02:28:09.880
I actually think
Indians could be great at design.

02:28:09.960 --> 02:28:12.240
They just need
the proper educational research.

02:28:12.320 --> 02:28:14.840
Yeah, yeah, bridging that sort of...

02:28:14.920 --> 02:28:18.960
the creativity in their culture
and in their brain

02:28:19.040 --> 02:28:23.280
and transforming it into
the more professional or practical level.

02:28:23.360 --> 02:28:26.560
That actually is difficult to happen.

02:28:26.640 --> 02:28:29.760
And where can an Indian learn that?

02:28:29.840 --> 02:28:30.840
A 20-year-old.

02:28:31.440 --> 02:28:36.160
They can start by designing for Roblox,
for example, on the UGC platforms.

02:28:38.240 --> 02:28:41.400
But I guess
one of the drawbacks for India is,

02:28:41.480 --> 02:28:44.720
because, like most of the people
I know building for Roblox,

02:28:44.800 --> 02:28:47.880
they don't do it on their phone,
they do it on a PC.

02:28:47.960 --> 02:28:50.920
And because there aren't
a lot of homes with PCs,

02:28:51.000 --> 02:28:55.160
that may be one of the things
holding India back.

02:28:55.240 --> 02:28:58.000
-Um...
-Why don't they do it on their phone?

02:28:58.080 --> 02:28:59.720
It's just too difficult, right?

02:28:59.800 --> 02:29:02.040
And then if you're coding, like in Luau...

02:29:02.120 --> 02:29:03.840
I mean, you don't wanna be doing that
on your phone.

02:29:05.240 --> 02:29:07.640
But that's different in the West?
People are...

02:29:07.720 --> 02:29:10.240
Almost every home has PC in their house,

02:29:10.320 --> 02:29:12.800
as well as, you know,
tablets and other things, so...

02:29:12.880 --> 02:29:16.040
But, I mean... Similar for China.
There aren't a...

02:29:16.120 --> 02:29:18.160
I mean, there are some places that have...

02:29:18.840 --> 02:29:19.840
Uh, I think there's...

02:29:19.920 --> 02:29:21.480
PC penetration
is probably higher in China,

02:29:21.560 --> 02:29:24.320
but still not as abundant
as, like, US and other places.

02:29:24.400 --> 02:29:26.640
How much does a game designer make?

02:29:27.480 --> 02:29:29.520
-Like an artist?
-[Nikhil laughs]

02:29:29.600 --> 02:29:30.960
[Sean] It varies a lot.

02:29:31.040 --> 02:29:32.760
Yeah, it varies a lot, but pretty low.

02:29:32.840 --> 02:29:37.200
Maybe around what an artist makes.
Slightly higher, but not much.

02:29:37.280 --> 02:29:40.120
Like as much as the art guy?

02:29:40.760 --> 02:29:43.000
Maybe a little bit more.
A little bit. Tiny bit.

02:29:43.080 --> 02:29:44.080
Eight.

02:29:45.680 --> 02:29:47.280
-[Sean] Seven, eight.
-Sort of four...

02:29:47.360 --> 02:29:49.160
-Entry.
-[Joseph] Yeah. For entry?

02:29:49.240 --> 02:29:51.080
Less than eight. Yeah.

02:29:51.840 --> 02:29:55.120
But that's surprising 'cause this seems
like the most critical part of the--

02:29:55.200 --> 02:29:56.520
But that's because they don't have...

02:29:56.600 --> 02:29:59.720
Like, if you were
a really good game designer,

02:29:59.800 --> 02:30:01.720
then sure, you could make a lot more.

02:30:01.800 --> 02:30:05.120
Yeah, and I have seen,
like, creative director...

02:30:05.200 --> 02:30:08.680
a creative director who actually set
the direction of the core gameplay

02:30:08.760 --> 02:30:12.520
and even certain part
of the out-game elements.

02:30:12.600 --> 02:30:17.040
They are maybe as equal
as cofounder or founder

02:30:17.120 --> 02:30:19.800
in terms of stock options or, you know,

02:30:19.880 --> 02:30:21.840
incentives they get
from the success of the game.

02:30:21.920 --> 02:30:23.280
I mean, gaming is a creative field.

02:30:23.360 --> 02:30:27.240
So, yeah, there's certainly potential
for high payouts.

02:30:27.320 --> 02:30:28.560
Data analytics?

02:30:31.520 --> 02:30:33.080
What does he do?

02:30:33.160 --> 02:30:36.240
It's all about looking
at the underlying data

02:30:36.320 --> 02:30:38.000
that is being generated by a game.

02:30:39.160 --> 02:30:40.960
For example, what are the data points?

02:30:41.040 --> 02:30:42.560
Retention is one of the biggest ones.

02:30:44.240 --> 02:30:49.240
For example, if 100 people
played your game on the first day

02:30:49.320 --> 02:30:52.480
when they downloaded the game,
how many came back the next day?

02:30:52.560 --> 02:30:55.080
Now, once you know
that 40 came back the next day,

02:30:55.160 --> 02:30:58.040
which is a good retention generally,
you lost 60.

02:30:58.120 --> 02:31:00.080
Then you need to get into your game data

02:31:00.160 --> 02:31:02.760
and see what are the drop-off points.

02:31:02.840 --> 02:31:05.560
Where am I losing these users
or these players, right?

02:31:05.640 --> 02:31:08.480
Are they launching the game
and dropping off

02:31:08.560 --> 02:31:11.400
from the main menu of the game
without playing anything?

02:31:11.480 --> 02:31:13.600
Are they going into a certain level?

02:31:13.680 --> 02:31:16.520
Are they getting stuck there
and then dropping off?

02:31:16.600 --> 02:31:20.240
So, there's a lot of in-depth data
that you need to get into

02:31:20.320 --> 02:31:22.360
-to understand how you can improve...
-[Nikhil] Mm-hmm.

02:31:22.440 --> 02:31:24.840
...the engagement of your game, right?

02:31:24.920 --> 02:31:29.480
So, I think no game can--
Unless it's just a hit by itself--

02:31:29.560 --> 02:31:33.240
And how does somebody learn that,
inculcate that skill?

02:31:33.920 --> 02:31:35.880
I think it's, uh...

02:31:35.960 --> 02:31:37.240
[Nikhil] Is it college? Is it...

02:31:37.320 --> 02:31:39.040
[Nitish] No, of course, it's...

02:31:39.120 --> 02:31:42.000
You need to have
a very strong grip on numbers.

02:31:42.080 --> 02:31:43.080
How do you get that?

02:31:44.360 --> 02:31:46.480
-I'm assuming...
-[Animesh] Arts, maths?

02:31:46.560 --> 02:31:48.720
-...you're strong in maths, et cetera.
-[overlapping conversations]

02:31:48.800 --> 02:31:50.600
-Khan Academy?
-[Joseph and Nikhil laugh]

02:31:50.680 --> 02:31:52.520
There's also aptitude to data
and numbers, right?

02:31:52.600 --> 02:31:54.680
-Khan Academy teaches maths?
-Yeah, it's good.

02:31:54.760 --> 02:31:57.840
It's aptitude to basic aptitude
and interest in data and numbers.

02:31:57.920 --> 02:31:59.880
Where do you hire your data analytics guy?

02:32:00.760 --> 02:32:03.880
I think we've hired them...
at least for us,

02:32:03.960 --> 02:32:06.920
many of them are from some
of these good business schools.

02:32:07.000 --> 02:32:08.480
-Business schools?
-[Nitish] Yeah.

02:32:08.560 --> 02:32:10.360
And how much do you pay
these people typically?

02:32:12.040 --> 02:32:15.520
We just have our product managers do it,
so we don't have a dedicated data analyst.

02:32:15.600 --> 02:32:17.480
Yeah, I mean, we...

02:32:17.560 --> 02:32:20.880
At least at a corporate team
where we have a few people

02:32:20.960 --> 02:32:25.680
looking at data of a lot of our studios...

02:32:27.160 --> 02:32:29.440
maybe 20, 30 lakhs a year.

02:32:30.760 --> 02:32:32.120
It's a lot.

02:32:32.200 --> 02:32:33.480
That's entry-level?

02:32:34.600 --> 02:32:36.480
No, I mean,
we don't have entry-level at corporate.

02:32:36.560 --> 02:32:38.520
We have, like, six people looking at data.

02:32:38.600 --> 02:32:40.160
But I think if I were to bring it down
to entry-level,

02:32:40.240 --> 02:32:42.280
I would assume
it would be around ten, right?

02:32:42.360 --> 02:32:44.240
Yeah, yeah.

02:32:44.320 --> 02:32:47.360
Now, I think the interesting question
is to Animesh.

02:32:47.440 --> 02:32:49.360
What skill sets?

02:32:49.440 --> 02:32:52.560
I think I'll just give a few advices
on how to be a gamer

02:32:52.640 --> 02:32:53.840
because there's no rule of thumb

02:32:53.920 --> 02:32:56.000
-on how you can be a gamer?
-Yeah.

02:32:56.680 --> 02:32:58.960
First I would say, in India...

02:33:00.240 --> 02:33:02.160
First thing, backup.
It needs to be mentioned

02:33:02.240 --> 02:33:03.880
that until you have reached that spot,

02:33:03.960 --> 02:33:06.160
it's always your backup thing
you are chasing.

02:33:06.240 --> 02:33:07.640
It's a passion project.

02:33:07.720 --> 02:33:09.920
To become a gamer yourself is also
a passion project that you're working on.

02:33:10.000 --> 02:33:12.440
When do you transition
from passion to full-time?

02:33:12.520 --> 02:33:16.120
I would say your first contract

02:33:16.200 --> 02:33:21.280
where you're getting paid
at least 35K a month.

02:33:21.360 --> 02:33:22.400
[Nikhil] Rupees.

02:33:22.480 --> 02:33:27.160
...rupees, is where I can say
that it's your profession from here on.

02:33:27.240 --> 02:33:28.760
You're talking about gamer
or content creator?

02:33:28.840 --> 02:33:29.840
[Animesh] Gamer.

02:33:29.920 --> 02:33:33.320
Content creator, I don't believe,
should ever chase money or contracts.

02:33:33.400 --> 02:33:35.160
Build on your own.
There is no rule of thumb.

02:33:35.240 --> 02:33:38.960
Even I cannot give any pieces of advice
because it's so many factors.

02:33:39.040 --> 02:33:40.680
How good the person is,
how creative they are,

02:33:40.760 --> 02:33:43.320
how fast they go viral,
what clicks, whatnot,

02:33:43.400 --> 02:33:45.560
but to a gamer. So it starts there.

02:33:45.640 --> 02:33:49.320
Second is your game type, you know,
what sort of games you played.

02:33:49.400 --> 02:33:53.320
It's not always necessary
to chase the herd,

02:33:53.400 --> 02:33:55.240
which is, like,
going for battle royale games

02:33:55.320 --> 02:33:56.680
or a shooting game.

02:33:56.760 --> 02:34:00.080
Very fine example, Tirth Mehta,
who was also a part of my panel,

02:34:00.160 --> 02:34:03.800
won an Asian Games medal
way back in 2017 for Hearthstone.

02:34:03.880 --> 02:34:05.160
So that is another way.

02:34:05.240 --> 02:34:08.400
So, you can always try to step out
of the normal thing

02:34:08.480 --> 02:34:09.640
and find a different game.

02:34:10.360 --> 02:34:13.600
Third would be knowing the...

02:34:13.680 --> 02:34:17.440
So, if you're in India, you want to ensure
that the publisher of that game

02:34:17.520 --> 02:34:21.000
is taking enough interest in India
to build around that game.

02:34:21.080 --> 02:34:24.240
For example, there's a game
called Dota 2, for say.

02:34:24.320 --> 02:34:26.840
It does not have
an active publisher interest in India.

02:34:26.920 --> 02:34:29.240
However, it's a very, very
big game outside.

02:34:29.320 --> 02:34:31.640
As big as...
There's an event called The International

02:34:31.720 --> 02:34:36.240
whose price pool goes
beyond $30 million for the main event.

02:34:36.320 --> 02:34:37.720
But if the publisher
is not interested in it,

02:34:37.800 --> 02:34:39.720
then I would suggest,
don't opt for a game,

02:34:39.800 --> 02:34:41.920
because then it would be
very difficult for you

02:34:42.000 --> 02:34:45.240
to get into events or represent India
at an international stage,

02:34:45.320 --> 02:34:48.440
because you might be clubbed
with the Oceanic region

02:34:48.520 --> 02:34:51.760
or entire South Asia region
or the SEA region, which is difficult.

02:34:52.520 --> 02:34:54.960
Fourth would be,
if you're going for a team game,

02:34:55.040 --> 02:34:56.920
I would say, at first...

02:34:57.000 --> 02:34:58.440
So, everyone asks me how to build a team.

02:34:58.520 --> 02:35:00.720
It's a very normal question
if you're playing a team game.

02:35:00.800 --> 02:35:04.640
I think you cannot just go out
and find other professional players

02:35:04.720 --> 02:35:06.680
who would want to build a team with you.

02:35:06.760 --> 02:35:07.920
You just start casually.

02:35:08.000 --> 02:35:11.040
You get a few gamers,
get to know people online,

02:35:11.120 --> 02:35:12.640
and it's a process. It could...

02:35:12.720 --> 02:35:14.880
The process could be finished
in two months.

02:35:14.960 --> 02:35:17.680
You might not find a team
in the next five years.

02:35:17.760 --> 02:35:21.760
There is no rule of thumb again.
It's just, how social you are,

02:35:21.840 --> 02:35:25.600
how well you are aligned,
how well you can talk to people.

02:35:25.680 --> 02:35:26.800
It's like those elements come--

02:35:26.880 --> 02:35:29.000
Your characteristic and your personality
comes into play

02:35:29.080 --> 02:35:30.160
when you're finding a team.

02:35:30.240 --> 02:35:32.240
Skill, though, comes at a later stage.

02:35:33.160 --> 02:35:36.800
Fourth would be, uh,
once you are contracted...

02:35:37.680 --> 02:35:40.360
That's when the real hustle starts,
if you are ever contracted.

02:35:40.440 --> 02:35:42.880
But I believe, right now, in India,

02:35:42.960 --> 02:35:45.240
Krafton... with this Grind
that Krafton is doing,

02:35:45.320 --> 02:35:48.080
they have recognised 256
tier one and tier two.

02:35:48.160 --> 02:35:50.120
Tier one means top teams of India.

02:35:50.200 --> 02:35:51.880
There's no-- It's a very subjective thing.

02:35:51.960 --> 02:35:54.560
Again, there is no benchmark
of what a tier-one team is.

02:35:54.640 --> 02:35:56.680
Then there are tier-two teams
who are trying to move

02:35:56.760 --> 02:35:58.680
into bigger events and qualify.

02:35:58.760 --> 02:36:01.360
So, Krafton has right now identified
256 teams.

02:36:01.440 --> 02:36:06.520
That means there are 256 good odd teams,
which means, 1,250 odd players are...

02:36:06.600 --> 02:36:08.920
if not in a contract,
they are doing something in gaming

02:36:09.000 --> 02:36:10.760
and they might have treated it
as a profession.

02:36:10.840 --> 02:36:12.840
But I would say
there are another thousand.

02:36:12.920 --> 02:36:15.200
So, the number of teams are growing.

02:36:15.280 --> 02:36:17.960
There are so many teams
coming up in tier-two cities.

02:36:18.040 --> 02:36:20.600
A businessman, a shop owner,
trying to build a team of his own,

02:36:20.680 --> 02:36:22.120
maybe because his son insisted.

02:36:22.200 --> 02:36:23.400
So, those are things happening.

02:36:23.480 --> 02:36:25.480
So, the point is people
need to be aware about...

02:36:25.560 --> 02:36:27.680
A gamer needs to be aware
of what's going on around him.

02:36:27.760 --> 02:36:30.760
Don't just look at Thug or a MortaL
and try to be them directly.

02:36:30.840 --> 02:36:33.440
It was not easy for everyone. For anyone.

02:36:33.520 --> 02:36:36.080
And then I would say,
when you get contracted,

02:36:36.160 --> 02:36:38.240
that's when you start doing your research.

02:36:38.320 --> 02:36:41.000
You have to just follow the correct way
to move up the ladder.

02:36:41.080 --> 02:36:43.480
Don't get complacent at where you are.
That's what happens.

02:36:43.560 --> 02:36:46.280
Even in my team, you know, I've had...

02:36:46.360 --> 02:36:48.960
I guess, in last six years,
contracted 80 players

02:36:49.040 --> 02:36:50.840
who have moved on to now different teams.

02:36:50.920 --> 02:36:53.040
Some have called it, hung their boots.

02:36:53.120 --> 02:36:57.080
But I think, I always want my players
to keep moving on at a better stage.

02:36:57.160 --> 02:36:58.960
Even if not better,
but at a parallel stage.

02:36:59.040 --> 02:37:01.600
But I think it's...
A gamer needs to keep moving places.

02:37:01.680 --> 02:37:03.760
Don't get stuck, especially in India.

02:37:03.840 --> 02:37:05.720
I'd love to come hang out
with you guys once.

02:37:05.800 --> 02:37:07.440
